id.name: hydroxylamine
id.definition: The simplest hydroxylamine, consisting of ammonia bearing a hydroxy substituent. It is an intermediate in the biological nitrification by microbes like bacteria.

id.name: protoporphyrin
id.definition: A cyclic tetrapyrrole that consists of porphyrin bearing four methyl substituents at positions 3, 8, 13 and 17, two vinyl substituents at positions 7 and 12 and two 2-carboxyethyl substituents at positions 2 and 18. The parent of the class of protoporphyrins.

id.name: squalene
id.definition: A triterpene consisting of 2,6,10,15,19,23-hexamethyltetracosane having six double bonds at the 2-, 6-, 10-, 14-, 18- and 22-positions with (all-E)-configuration.

id.name: (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene
id.definition: A 2,3-epoxysqualene in which the chiral centre has S configuration. It is converted to lanosterol by lanosterol synthase (EC 5.4.99.7) in a key rate-limiting step in the biosynthesis of chloesterol, steroid hormones, and vitamin D.

id.name: presqualene diphosphate
id.definition: A triterpenyl phosphate that is presqualene in which the hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a diphosphate group.

id.name: (1->4)-beta-D-xylan
id.definition: A xylan compound with beta-(1->4)-linkages between each xylose.

id.name: (1-hydroxycyclohexyl)acetyl-CoA
id.definition: A 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA having (1-hydroxycyclohexyl)acetyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: (2S,3S)-3-hydroxy-2-methylbutanoyl-CoA
id.definition: An (S)-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (2S,3S)-3-hydroxy-2-methylbutanoic acid.

id.name: (R)-3-hydroxybutanoyl-CoA
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 3-hydroxybutanoyl-CoA.

id.name: (3S)-3-carboxy-3-hydroxypropanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the 3-carboxy group of (3S)-3-carboxy-3-hydroxypropanoic acid.

id.name: citramalyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA having citramalyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: (3S)-citryl-CoA
id.definition: An (S)-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA having (3S)-citryl as the S-acyl group

id.name: trans-tetradec-11-enoyl-CoA
id.definition: A Delta(11)-acyl-CoA having trans-tetradec-11-enoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: cis-tetradec-11-enoyl-CoA
id.definition: A Delta(11)-acyl-CoA having cis-tetradec-11-enoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: cinnamoyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of cinnamic acid.

id.name: (R)-methylmalonyl-CoA
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of methylmalonyl-CoA.

id.name: (S)-methylmalonyl-CoA
id.definition: The (S)-enantiomer of methylmalonyl-CoA.

id.name: (3S)-3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA
id.definition: A 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA where the 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl component has (S)-configuration.

id.name: 3'-dephospho-CoA
id.definition: An adenosine 5'-phosphate that is coenzyme A in which the phosphate group at position 3' has been replaced by a hydrogen atom. It is an intermediate metabolite in pantothenate and CoA biosynthesis

id.name: alk-2-enoyl-CoA
id.definition: An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any alpha,beta-unsaturated fatty acid.

id.name: 2,4-dichlorobenzoyl-CoA
id.definition: A dichlorobenzoyl-CoA having 2,4-dichlorobenzoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: trans-dodec-2-enoyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA having trans-dodec-2-enoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: anthraniloyl-CoA
id.definition: A member of the class of benzoyl-CoAs having 2-aminobenzoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: crotonoyl-CoA
id.definition: The (E)-isomer of but-2-enoyl-CoA.

id.name: 2-furoyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA having 2-furoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: 2-hydroxyphytanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A multi-methyl-branched fatty acyl-CoA having 2-hydroxyphytanoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: 2-methylacetoacetyl-CoA
id.definition: A 3-oxoacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-methylacetoacetic acid.

id.name: 2-methylbutanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A short-chain, methyl-branched fatty acyl-CoA having 2-methylbutanoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: isobutyryl-CoA
id.definition: A short-chain, methyl-branched fatty acyl-CoA that is the S-isobutyryl derivative of coenzyme A.

id.name: 3-hydroxy-3-(3-hydroxy-4-methoxyphenyl)propanoyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-hydroxy-3-(3-hydroxy-4-methoxyphenyl)propanoic acid.

id.name: 3-hydroxy-3-(4-methylpent-3-en-1-yl)glutaryl-CoA
id.definition: The S-3-hydroxy-3-(4-methylpent-3-en-1-yl)glutaryl derivative of CoA.

id.name: 3-hydroxybenzoyl-CoA

id.name: 1-O-sinapoyl-beta-D-glucose

id.name: N-formyl-L-methionine

id.name: oxidised poly(vinyl alcohol)

id.name: 3-ethylcatechol

id.name: carbonyl sulfide

id.name: D-alanyl-D-alanine

id.name: 3alpha,7alpha-dihydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oic acid

id.name: butane-2,3-dione

id.name: isopentenyl diphosphate

id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of ethyl 3-hydroxyhexanoate.

id.name: carbohydrate
id.definition: Any member of the class of organooxygen compounds that is a polyhydroxy-aldehyde or -ketone or a lactol resulting from their intramolecular condensation (monosaccharides); substances derived from these by reduction of the carbonyl group (alditols), by oxidation of one or more hydroxy groups to afford the corresponding aldehydes, ketones, or carboxylic acids, or by replacement of one or more hydroxy group(s) by a hydrogen atom; and polymeric products arising by intermolecular acetal formation between two or more such molecules (disaccharides, polysaccharides and oligosaccharides). Carbohydrates contain only carbon, hydrogen and oxygen atoms; prior to any oxidation or reduction, most have the empirical formula Cm(H2O)n. Compounds obtained from carbohydrates by substitution, etc., are known as carbohydrate derivatives and may contain other elements. Cyclitols are generally not regarded as carbohydrates.

id.name: L-fuculose 1-phosphate

id.name: hypotaurine

id.name: peptide

The term is usually applied to structures formed from alpha-amino acids, but it includes those derived from any amino carboxylic acid. X = OH, OR, NH2, NHR, etc.

id.name: protochlorophyllide
id.definition: An analogue of chlorophyll that lacks the phytol side-chain. The parent of the protochlorophyllide class.

id.name: ecdysone

id.name: 3-methylthiopropylamine

id.name: N-sulfo-D-glucosamine

id.name: (2->6)-beta-D-fructan

id.name: adenine

id.name: pyridoxine

The 4-methanol form of vitamin B6, it is converted intoto pyridoxal phosphate which is a coenzyme for synthesis of amino acids, neurotransmitters, sphingolipids and aminolevulinic acid.

id.name: D-ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate

id.name: codeine

id.name: benzene

A toxic, flammable liquid byproduct of coal distillation, it is used as an industrial solvent. Benzene is a carcinogen that also damages bone marrow and the central nervous system.

id.name: (Z)-but-2-ene-1,2,3-tricarboxylic acid

id.name: guanosine

id.name: inulobiose

While it is the most used gaseous anaesthetic in the world, its major commercial use, due to its solubility under pressure in vegetable fats combined with its non-toxicity in low concentrations, is as an aerosol spray propellant and aerating agent for canisters of 'whipped' cream.

id.name: all-trans-undecaprenyl diphosphate
id.definition: The all-trans-isomer of undecaprenyl diphosphate.

id.name: nororientaline
id.definition: An isoquinoline alkaloid consisting of aa tetrahydroisoquinoline core with 4-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzyl, methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 1, 6 and 7 respectively; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: 6-(alpha-D-glucosaminyl)-1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol
id.definition: A glucosaminylphosphatidylinositol compound consisting of D-glucosamine joined to 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol via a (1->6)-alpha-linkage.

id.name: 3-phosphoglyceric acid
id.definition: A monophosphoglyceric acid having the phospho group at the 3-position. It is an intermediate in metabolic pathways like glycolysis and calvin cycle.

id.name: L-aspartic acid
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of aspartic acid.

id.name: 1-carboxyvinyl carboxyphosphonate
id.definition: An organic phosphonate having O-1-carboxyvinyl and C-carboxy substituents.

id.name: cellobiose
id.definition: A glycosylglucose consisting of two glucose units linked via a beta(1->4) bond.

id.name: D-glutamine
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of glutamine.

id.name: L-erythrulose 1-phosphate
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of erythrulose 1-phosphate.

id.name: 4-nitroaniline
id.definition: A nitroaniline carrying a nitro group at position 4.

id.name: 3',5'-cyclic CMP
id.definition: A 3',5'-cyclic pyrimidine nucleotide having cytosine as the nucleobase.

id.name: (R)-3-hydroxybutyric acid
id.definition: The R-enantiomer of 3-hydroxybutyric acid. Involved in the synthesis and degradation of ketone bodies, it can be used as an energy source by the brain during hypoglycaemia, and for the synthesis of biodegradable plastics.

id.name: 3-hydroxy-3-(4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl)propanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A 3-hydroxypropionyl-CoA having a 4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl group at the 3-position.

id.name: 3-hydroxybenzyl alcohol
id.definition: A hydroxybenzyl alcohol that is phenol substituted at position C-3 by a hydroxymethyl group.

id.name: glycolaldehyde
id.definition: The glycolaldehyde derived from ethylene glycol. The parent of the class of glycolaldehydes.

id.name: N-amidino-L-aspartic acid
id.definition: An aspartic acid derivative comprising L-aspartic acid carrying an N-amidino substituent.

id.name: streptomycin
id.definition: A amino cyclitol glycoside that consists of streptidine having a disaccharyl moiety attached at the 4-position. The parent of the streptomycin class

id.name: 2-carboxy-D-arabinitol
id.definition: The 2-carboxy derivative of D-arabinitol.

id.name: (S)-3'-hydroxy-N-methylcoclaurine
id.definition: An isoquinoline alkaloid having a tetrahydroisoquinoline core with 3,4-dihydroxybenzyl, methoxy and hydroxy groups at the 1-, 6- and 7-positions respectively; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: dimethylmaleate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is obtained from dimethylmaleic acid by removal of a proton from each of the carboxylic acid groups.

id.name: 2-amino-6-(hydroxymethyl)-7,8-dihydropteridin-4-ol
id.definition: A dihydropterin that is 7,8-dihydropteridin-4-ol substituted at positions 2 and 6 by amino and hydroxymethyl groups respectively.

id.name: 2-hydroxyglutaric acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid that is glutaric acid in which one hydrogen alpha- to a carboxylic acid group is substituted by a hydroxy group.

id.name: phospholipid methylene fatty acid - not enabled
ketone
id.definition: A compound in which a carbonyl group is bonded to two carbon atoms: R2C=O (neither R may be H).

id.name: monoacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate
id.definition: An sn-glycero-3-phosphate compound having a single unspecified acyl group at either position 1 or position 2.

id.name: glycoprotein
id.definition: A compound in which a carbohydrate component is covalently bound to a protein component.

id.name: (1R,2R,3R)-prephytoene diphosphate
id.definition: The (1R,2R,3R)-diastereomer of prephytoene diphosphate.

id.name: 3-chloro-D-alanine
id.definition: A 3-chloroalanine that has S configutation at the chiral centre.

id.name: 2-dehydropantoic acid
id.definition: An oxo monocarboxylic acid that is 2-oxobutanoic acid in which both of the hydrogens at position 3 are substituted by methyl groups and one of the hydrogens at position 4 is substituted by a hydroxy group.

id.name: biphenyl
id.definition: A benzenoid aromatic compound that consists of two benzene rings connected by a single covalent bond. Biphenyl occurs naturally in coal tar, crude oil, and natural gas. Formerly used as a fungicide for citrus crops.

id.name: veratraldehyde
id.definition: A dimethoxybenzene that is benzaldehyde substituted by methoxy groups at positions 3 and 4. It is found in peppermint, ginger, raspberry, and other fruits.

id.name: macarpine
id.definition: A benzophenanthridine alkaloid that is sanguinarine bearing two methoxy substituents.

id.name: phosphoramide
id.definition: A compound in which one or more of the OH groups of phosphoric acid have been replaced with an amino or substituted amino group. The term is commonly confined to the phosphoric triamides, P(=O)(NR2)3, since replacement of one or two OH groups produces phosphoramidic acids: P(=O)(OH)(NR2)2 , P(=O)(OH)2(NR2).

id.name: N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosylceramide
id.definition: A glycotriaosylceramide having N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the glycotriaosyl component.

id.name: 6-hydroxyprotopine

id.name: 1-alkyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate
id.definition: An alkyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the alkyl group is at position 1 of the sn-glycerol.

id.name: 7,8-dihydro-7,8-dihydroxykynurenic acid

id.name: 1-guanidino-1-deoxy-scyllo-inositol

id.name: 5-O-phosphono-alpha-D-ribofuranosyl diphosphate
id.definition: A derivative of alpha-D-ribose having a phosphate group at the 5-position and a diphosphate at the 1-position.

id.name: erythritol
id.definition: The meso-diastereomer of butane-1,2,3,4-tetrol.

id.name: L-serine
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of serine.

id.name: 5-dehydro-4-deoxy-D-glucuronate

id.name: hexanoate

id.name: aldehydo-N-acetyl-D-mannosamine

id.name: 2-aminoacrylic acid

id.name: carnitine

id.name: glucotropeolin
id.definition: An aralkylglucosinolic acid that consists of 1-thio-beta-D-glucopyranose attached to a 2-phenyl-N-(sulfooxy)ethanimidoyl group at the anomeric sulfur.

id.name: adipate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of adipic acid.

id.name: (S)-scoulerine
id.definition: A berberine alkaloid isolated from Corydalis saxicola.

id.name: 10-oxocapric acid
id.definition: A capric acid derivative carrying an oxo group at position 10.

id.name: (3,5-diiodo-4-hydroxyphenyl)pyruvic acid
id.definition: A derivative of pyruvic acid carrying a 3,5-diiodo-4-hydroxyphenyl group at the 3-position.

id.name: octopamine
id.definition: Octopamine is a biogenic phenylethanolamine, which has been found to act as a neurotransmitter, neurohormone or neuromodulator in invertebrates.

id.name: long-chain fatty alcohol
id.definition: A fatty alcohol with a chain length of C13 or greater.

id.name: 2,8-dihydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone
id.definition: A hydroxyquinone that is the 2,8-dihydroxy derivative of 1,4-naphthoquinone.

id.name: glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate
id.definition: An aldotriose phosphate that is the 3-phospho derivative of glyceraldehyde. It is an important metabolic intermediate in several central metabolic pathways in all organisms.

id.name: D-xylulose
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of xylulose.

id.name: cysteamine
id.definition: An amine that consists of an ethane skeleton substituted with a thiol group at C-1 and an amino group at C-2.

id.name: urate D-ribonucleotide
id.definition: A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate consisting of 5'-xanthylic acid having an oxo group at the 8-position.

id.name: putrescine
id.definition: A four-carbon alkane-alpha,omega-diamine. It is obtained by the breakdown of amino acids and is responsible for the foul odour of putrefying flesh.

id.name: N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl glycopeptide
id.definition: A glycopeptide having an N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl residue at the non-reducing end.

id.name: 2-phosphoglycolic acid
id.definition: The O-phospho derivative of glycolic acid.

id.name: xylitol

id.name: phosphatidyl-N,N-dimethylethanolamine
id.definition: A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the amino group is dimethylated.

id.name: propanal
id.definition: An aldehyde that consists of ethane bearing a formyl substituent. The parent of the class of propanals.

id.name: nicotinamide
id.definition: A pyridinecarboxamide that is pyridine in which the hydrogen at position 3 is replaced by a carboxamide group.

id.name: flavonol 3-O-(6-O-malonyl-beta-D-glucoside)
id.definition: Any glycosyloxyflavone that consists of a flavonol attached to a 6-O-malonyl-beta-D-glucosyl residue at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.

id.name: 1D-3-amino-1-guanidino-1,3-dideoxy-scyllo-inositol

id.name: methylglyoxal

id.name: 17alpha-estradiol
id.definition: An estradiol that is estra-1,3,5(10)-triene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 17 (the 17alpha stereoisomer).

id.name: O-demethylpuromycin

id.name: 2-oxooctadecanoate
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of the proton from the carboxy group of 2-oxooctadecanoic acid (stearic acid). The major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: stachyose

id.name: Photinus luciferin

id.name: N-methylputrescine

id.name: (R)-lactaldehyde

id.name: 5alpha-cholest-7-en-3beta-ol

id.name: benzaldehyde

id.name: 2'-deoxyguanosine

id.name: 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid

id.name: 3,5-dibromo-4-hydroxybenzonitrile

id.name: bromochloromethane

id.name: thiomorpholine-3-carboxylic acid

id.name: L-asparagine

id.name: 1-alkylglycerone 3-phosphate

id.name: UDP-alpha-D-glucuronic acid

id.name: glycylglycine

id.name: IMP

id.name: L-proline
id.definition: Pyrrolidine in which the pro-S hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a carboxylic acid group. L-Proline is the only one of the twenty DNA-encoded amino acids which has a secondary amino group alpha to the carboxyl group. It is an essential component of collagen and is important for proper functioning of joints and tendons. It also helps maintain and strengthen heart muscles.

id.name: 4,5-dioxopentanoic acid

id.name: 2-methylideneglutaric acid

id.name: D-lysopine

An intermediate in the biosynthesis of narcotic analgesics such as morphine and codeine.

id.name: m-cresol

id.name: L-glutamic 5-semialdehyde

id.name: glucose

id.name: itaconate(2-)

id.name: 1H-pyrazole

id.name: mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate

id.name: carbon monoxide

id.name: poly(vinyl alcohol) macromolecule

id.name: N-isopropylammelide

id.name: D-nopaline

id.name: 2-hydroxy-4-oxobutane-1,2,4-tricarboxylic acid

id.name: 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone

id.name: 1,2-benzoquinone

id.name: N-carbamoyl-D-alpha-amino acid

id.name: phosphatidylglycerol phosphate

id.name: O-(1->4)-alpha-L-dihydrostreptosylstreptidine 6-phosphate
id.definition: A scyllo-inositol phosphate compound having the phosphate group at the 6-position, guanidino groups replacing hydroxy functions at the 1-position and an alpha-L-lyxofuranosyl residue at the 4-position.

id.name: L-sorbose
id.definition: The L enantiomer of sorbose, a ketone-containing hexose (a six-carbon monosaccharide).

id.name: myo-inositol

id.name: Latia luciferin
id.definition: An apo carotenoid sesquiterpenoid that consists of a cylohexene ring substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 6 and 6 and a (1E)-1-(formyloxy)-2-methylbut-1-en-4-yl group at position 2.

id.name: 3-phosphonatopyruvate(3-)

id.name: propionate

id.name: aldehydo-N-acyl-D-glucosamine

id.name: N-succinyl-LL-2,6-diaminopimelic acid

id.name: 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3-phosphate

id.name: 5-phospho-D-ribosylamine

id.name: L-cysteic acid

id.name: deacetylisoipecoside

id.name: (S)-3-hydroxybutyric acid

id.name: beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc-(1-1')-Cer
id.definition: A glycotetraosylceramide having beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the tetrasaccharide component.

id.name: 4,21-dehydrogeissoschizine

id.name: L-phenylalanine

id.name: aniline

id.name: UDP-sugar

id.name: tetrachloroethene

id.name: glucaric acid

id.name: morphine

Morphine acts directly on the central nervous system (CNS) to relieve pain but has a high potential for addiction, with tolerance and both physical and psychological dependence developing rapidly. Morphine is the most abundant opiate found in Papaver somniferum (the opium poppy).

id.name: maltose
id.definition: A glycosylglucose consisting of two D-glucopyranose units connected by an alpha-(1->4)-linkage.

id.name: 2-oxohexanoic acid
id.definition: A straight-chain fatty acid consisting of hexanoic acid having an oxo group at position 2.

id.name: pectin
id.definition: Any mixture of complex, colloidal, macromolecular plant galacturonans containing a large proportion of D-galactopyranosyluronic acid residues in alpha-(1->4) linkage, the carboxy groups of which may be esterified to varying degrees by methyl groups or be partially or completely converted into salts. The structure shown is that of the parent polygalacturonan.

id.name: pyridoxal
id.definition: A pyridinecarbaldehyde that is pyridine-4-carbaldehyde bearing methyl, hydroxy and hydroxymethyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 5 respectively. The 4-carboxyaldehyde form of vitamin B6, it is converted into pyridoxal phosphate, a coenzyme for the synthesis of amino acids, neurotransmitters, sphingolipids and aminolevulinic acid.

id.name: N(6),N(6),N(6)-trimethyl-L-lysine
id.definition: An alpha-amino-acid cation that is the N(6)-trimethyl derivative of L-lysine.

id.name: N(1)-acetylspermine
id.definition: An acetylspermine carrying an acetyl group at position N(1).

id.name: 13-hydroxydocosanoic acid
id.definition: A C22 hydroxy fatty acid with the hydroxy group at the 13-position and intermediate in the synthesis of sophorosyloxydocosanoate; a yeast glycolipid with potential medical and chemical engineering applications.

id.name: D-glucosamine
id.definition: An amino sugar whose structure comprises D-glucose having an amino substituent at position 2.

id.name: D-sorbose
id.definition: Any form of sorbose that has D-configuration.

id.name: N-(3,4-dichlorophenyl)malonamate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-(3,4-dichlorophenyl)malonamic acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: 5'-deoxyadenosine
id.definition: A 5'-deoxyribonucleoside compound having adenosine as the nucleobase.

id.name: 23,24-dihydrocucurbitacin
id.definition: Any cucurbitacin whose C(23)-C(24) double bond has been reduced.

id.name: 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutarate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion that results from the removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaric acid.

id.name: phytol
id.definition: A diterpenoid that is hexadec-2-en-1-ol substituted by methyl groups at positions 3, 7, 11 and 15.

id.name: N-benzoylanthranilate
id.definition: A benzoate that is the conjugate base of N-benzoylanthranilic acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: chorismic acid
id.definition: The (3R,4R)-stereoisomer of 5-[(1-carboxyethenyl)oxy]-6-hydroxycyclohexa-1,3-diene-1-carboxylic acid.

id.name: penicillin
id.definition: Any member of the group of substituted penams containing two methyl substituents at position 2, a carboxylate substituent at position 3 and a carboxamido group at position 6.

id.name: all-trans-retinol
id.definition: A retinol in which all four exocyclic double bonds have E- (trans-) geometry.

id.name: CDP-3,6-dideoxy-D-glucose
id.definition: A CDP-sugar having 3,6-dideoxy-D-glucose as the sugar component.

id.name: N(5)-acyl-L-ornithine
id.definition: An L-ornithine compound having an acyl substituent at the N(5)-position.

id.name: cetraxate
id.definition: A cyclohexanecarboxylate ester that consists of 4-(2-carboxyethyl)phenyl cyclohexanecarboxylate bearing an aminomethyl substituent at the 4-position.

id.name: L-2-aminohexano-6-lactam
id.definition: A 2-aminohexano-6-lactam derived from L-lysine.

id.name: GMP
id.definition: A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having guanine as the nucleobase.

id.name: 4-chlorophenylacetonitrile
id.definition: A nitrile that is acetonitrile in which one of the hydrogens has been replaced by a p-chlorophenyl group.

id.name: testosterone
id.definition: An androstanoid having 17beta-hydroxy and 3-oxo groups, together with unsaturation at C-4-C-5..

id.name: D-aldohexose 6-phosphate
id.definition: Any D-aldose having a six-carbon chain with a phosphate group at C-6.

id.name: linoleic acid
id.definition: An octadecadienoic acid in which the two double bonds are at positions 9 and 12 and have Z (cis) stereochemistry.

id.name: (R)-mandelamide
id.definition: A mandelamide in which the stereocentre at position 2 has R-configuration.

id.name: 16beta-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: A 16-hydroxy steroid in which the hydroxy group at position 16 has a beta-configuration.

id.name: 2-acetamidofluorene
id.definition: The parent of the class of 2-acetamidofluorenes, being an ortho-fused polycyclic arene that consists of 9H-fluorene bearing an acetamido substituent at position 2. It is a carcinogenic and mutagenic derivative of fluorene.

id.name: sulfite
id.definition: Sulfite is an inorganic anion, which is the conjugate base of hydrogen sulfite.

id.name: D-altronate
id.definition: Conjugate base of D-altronic acid.

id.name: CMP
id.definition: A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having cytosine as the nucleobase.

id.name: quinoline
id.definition: The simplest member of the quinoline class of compounds, comprising a benzene ring ortho fused to C-2 and C-3 of a pyridine ring.

id.name: D-ribulose 5-phosphate
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of ribulose 5-phosphate that is one of the end-products of the pentose phosphate pathway.

id.name: D-aspartic acid
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of aspartic acid.

id.name: hypoxanthine
id.definition: A purine nucleobase that consists of purine bearing an oxo substituent at position 6.

id.name: D-mannose 6-phosphate
id.definition: A mannose phosphate in which the phosphate group is attached to position 6.

id.name: macrocin
id.definition: A macrolide antibiotic that is tylonolide having mono- and diglycosyl moieties attached to two of its hydroxy groups.

id.name: 1,2-dihydrovomilenine
id.definition: An indole alkaloid obtained by selective hydrogenation of the 1,2-position of vomilenine.

id.name: (2S)-2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid in which the hydroxy group has a (S)-configuration.

id.name: cystine
id.definition: A sulfur-containing amino acid obtained by the oxidation of two cysteine molecules which are then linked via a disulfide bond.

id.name: D-glyceraldehyde
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of glyceraldehyde.

id.name: isovitexin 2''-O-beta-D-glucoside
id.definition: A disaccharide derivative that is the 2"-O-beta-D-glucosyl derivative of isovitexin .

id.name: porphobilinogen
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid that is pyrole bearing aminomethyl, carboxymethyl and 2-carboxyethyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 4 respectively.

id.name: 17-O-acetylnorajmaline
id.definition: An indole alkaloid obtained by formal acetylation of the 17-hydroxy group of norajmaline.

id.name: 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)lactic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy carboxylic acid that is lactic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 4-hydroxyphenyl group.

id.name: O-acylcarnitine
id.definition: Any carboxylic ester obtained by the O-acylation of carnitine.

id.name: (S)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate
id.definition: A 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate resulting from the removal of the proton from the carboxy group of (S)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid.

id.name: 2-monoglyceride
id.definition: A monoglyceride in which the acyl substituent is located at position 2.

id.name: peptidylproline (omega=0)
id.definition: The cis isomer of the L-proline peptide bond.

id.name: N(5)-ethyl-L-glutamine
id.definition: A N(5)-alkylglutamine where the alkyl group is ethyl. It has been isolated from green tea.

id.name: cis-caffeic acid
id.definition: The cis-isomer of caffeic acid.

id.name: 3-methyloxindole
id.definition: A member of the class of oxindoles that is oxindole (1,3-dihydro-2H-indol-2-one) in which one of the hydrogens at position 3 has been replaced by a methyl group.

id.name: poly[2-O-(N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl)ribitol phosphate]
id.definition: A polymer composed of repeating 2-(N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl)ribitol 1-phosphate units.

id.name: myo-inositol hexakisphosphate
id.definition: A myo-inositol hexakisphosphate in which each hydroxy group of myo-inositol is monophosphorylated.

id.name: 3-chloro-L-alanine
id.definition: A 3-chloroalanine that has R configutation at the chiral centre.

id.name: indan-1-one
id.definition: An indanone that consists of 2,3-dihydro-1H-indene substituted by an oxo group at position 1.

id.name: 4-pyridoxic acid
id.definition: A methylpyridine that is 2-methylpyridine substituted by a hydroxy group at C-3, a carboxy group at C-4, and a hydroxymethyl group at C-5. It is the catabolic product of vitamin B6 and is excreted in the urine.

id.name: 3-(imidazol-5-yl)pyruvic acid
id.definition: An oxo carboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by an imidazol-5-yl group.

id.name: 2-trans,6-trans-farnesyl diphosphate
id.definition: The trans,trans-stereoisomer of farnesyl diphosphate.

id.name: monoglyceride
id.definition: A glyceride in which any one of the R groups (position not specified) is an acyl group while the remaining two R groups can be either H or alkyl groups.

id.name: 10-hydroxycapric acid
id.definition: A 10-carbon, omega-hydroxy fatty acid, shown to be the preferred hydroxylation product (together with the 9-OH isomer) of capric acid in biosystems, and used as a standard in lipid assays; reported to have cytotoxic effects.

id.name: aldehydo-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine
id.definition: The open-chain form of N-acetyl-D-glucosamine.

id.name: 2-(hydroxymethyl)-4-oxobutanoic acid
id.definition: A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is 4-oxobutanoic acid which is substituted by a hydroxymethyl group at position 2.

id.name: valeric acid
id.definition: A straight-chain saturated fatty acid containing five carbon atoms.

id.name: heparan sulfate N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminide
id.definition: A heparan sulfate having an N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminyl residue at the non-reducing end. The heparan sulfate part consists of a variably sulfated repeating disaccharide unit.

id.name: P(1),P(4)-bis(5'-adenosyl) tetraphosphate
id.definition: A diadenosyl tetraphosphate compound having the two 5'-adenosyl residues attached at the P(1)- and P(4)-positions.

id.name: methemoglobin
id.definition: A hemoprotein that is the ferric (Fe(3+)) form of hemoglobin.

id.name: 1-pyrroline-2-carboxylate
id.definition: The anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 1-pyrroline-2-carboxylic acid.

id.name: 3-ketosucrose
id.definition: A glycosyl glycoside which is an intermediate in the breakdown of sucrose. The structure is that of sucrose in which the glucosyl 3-hydroxy group has been reduced to a keto group.

id.name: trimethylsulfonium
id.definition: A sulfonium compound in which the substituents on sulfur are three methyl groups. It is found in the midgut gland of the sea hare, Aplysia brasiliana, and exhibits probable ability to inhibit cholinergic responses.

id.name: (R)-5-phosphomevalonic acid
id.definition: A carboxyalkyl phosphate that is mevalonic acid phosphorylated at position 5.

id.name: dimethyl sulfide
id.definition: A methyl sulfide in which the sulfur atom is substituted by two methyl groups. It is produced naturally by some marine algae.

id.name: 4-nitrophenyl phosphate
id.definition: An aryl phosphate resulting from the mono-esterification of phosphoric acid with 4-nitrophenol.

id.name: L-homocitrulline
id.definition: A L-lysine derivative that is L-lysine having a carbamoyl group at the N(6)-position. It is found in individuals with urea cycle disorders.

id.name: 3-hydroxyphenylacetic acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that is phenylacetic acid in which the hydrogen at position 3 on the benzene ring is replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: geraniol
id.definition: A monoterpenoid consisting of two prenyl units linked head-to-tail and functionalised with a hydroxy group at its tail end.

id.name: cis-4-coumaric acid
id.definition: The cis-form of 4-coumaric acid.

id.name: methylmalonate(2-)
id.definition: A C4-dicarboxylate resulting from the removal of a proton from both carboxylic acid groups of methylmalonic acid.

id.name: UDP-L-rhamnose
id.definition: A UDP-rhamnose in which the rhamnose component has L-configuration.

id.name: dithioerythritol
id.definition: The meso-diastereomer of 1,4-dimercaptobutane-2,3-diol; a sulfur-containing sugar derived from the monosaccharide erythrose; and an epimer of dithiothreitol.

id.name: D-iditol
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of iditol.

id.name: lipoamide
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of lipoic acid with ammonia.

id.name: L-galactono-1,4-lactone
id.definition: A galactonolactone that is 3,4-dihydroxydihydrofuran-2(3H)-one substituted by a 1,2-dihydroxyethyl group at position 5 (the 3S,4S,5R-isomer).

id.name: phaseollidin hydrate
id.definition: A member of the class of pterocarpans that is phaseollidin in which the prenyl group is replaced by a 3-hydroxy-3-methylbutyl group.

id.name: GDP-D-mannuronate
id.definition: A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of GDP-D-mannuronic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: (4-bromophenylsulfanyl)pyruvate
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (4-bromophenylsulfanyl)pyruvic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: 1-alkyl-2-acetyl-3-acyl-sn-glycerol
id.definition: A 1-alkyl-2,3-diacylglycerol in which the acyl group at position 2 is specified as acetyl.

id.name: estrone 3-sulfate
id.definition: A steroid sulfate that is the 3-sulfate of estrone.

id.name: aminomalonic acid
id.definition: An amino dicarboxylic acid that is malonic acid in which one of the methylene hydrogens has been replaced by an amino group.

id.name: 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine
id.definition: A glycerophosphoethanolamine compound having an alk-1-enyl substituent at the 1-position and an acyl substituent at the 2-position.

id.name: aldehyde
id.definition: A compound RC(=O)H, in which a carbonyl group is bonded to one hydrogen atom and to one R group.

id.name: enol-oxaloacetate
id.definition: A C4-dicarboxylate resulting from the removal of a proton from both carboxylic acid groups of enol-oxaloacetic acid.

id.name: L-cystathionine
id.definition: A modified amino acid generated by enzymic means from L-homocysteine and L-serine.

id.name: homocystine
id.definition: An organic disulfide obtained by oxidative dimerisation of homocysteine.

id.name: (S)-atropine
id.definition: An atropine with a 2S-configuration.

id.name: scopoletin
id.definition: A hydroxycoumarin that is umbelliferone bearing a methoxy substituent at position 6.

id.name: 3',5'-cyclic AMP
id.definition: A 3',5'-cyclic purine nucleotide having having adenine as the nucleobase.

id.name: O-palmitoyl-L-carnitine
id.definition: An O-acyl-L-carnitine in which the acyl group is specified as palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl).

id.name: S-(2-hydroxyacyl)glutathione
id.definition: Glutathione substituted on sulfor by a 2-hydroxyacyl group.

id.name: glycolic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid where the methyl group has been hydroxylated.

id.name: hydrogen donor
id.definition: A molecular entity that can undergo oxidation by the loss of hydrogen atom(s).

id.name: 7alpha-hydroxycholesterol
id.definition: The 7alpha-hydroxy derivative of cholesterol.

id.name: 2-methylpropanal oxime
id.definition: An aldoxime derived from 2-methylpropanal.

id.name: N-acyl-D-glutamates(2-)
id.definition: A doubly-charged N-acyl-D-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from removal of protons from both carboxy groups of any N-acyl-D-glutamic acid.

id.name: alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-1D-myo-inositol
id.definition: An alpha-D-galactoside having a 1D-myo-inositol substituent at the anomeric position.

id.name: 7,8-dihydroxykynurenic acid
id.definition: A hydroxyquinoline that is kynurenic acid in which the hydrogens at positions 7 and 8 are replaced by hydroxy groups.

id.name: 5'-S-methyl-5'-thioadenosine
id.definition: Adenosine with the hydroxy group at C-5' substituted with a methylthio (methylsulfanyl) group.

id.name: 3-O-L-alanyl-1-O-phosphatidylglycerol
id.definition: Phosphatidylglycerol substituted at O-3 by a L-alanyl group.

id.name: cyanide
id.definition: A pseudohalide anion that is the conjugate base of hydrogen cyanide.

id.name: L-gamma-glutamyl-L-cysteine
id.definition: A molecular entity formed when L-cysteine amino group binds to the gamma-carbonyl of L-glutamic acid.

id.name: phosphatidylglycerol
id.definition: A glycerophosphoglycerol that is glycerol in which the hydrogen of one of the primary hydroxy groups has been replaced by a phosphatidyl group.

id.name: N-methyl-L-alanine
id.definition: A methyl-L-alanine in which one of the the amino hydrogen of L-alanine is replaced by a methyl group.

id.name: (-)-quinic acid
id.definition: The (-)-enantiomer of quinic acid.

id.name: alditol
id.definition: A carbohydrate that is an acyclic polyol having the general formula HOCH2[CH(OH)]nCH2OH (formally derivable from an aldose by reduction of the carbonyl group).

id.name: 6-alkylaminopurine
id.definition: Any purine bearing an alkylamino substituent at the 6-position.

id.name: 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 4-phosphate
id.definition: A phosphatidylinositol 4-phosphate having 1D-myo-configuration.

id.name: 1,2,3,6-tetrakis-O-galloyl-beta-D-glucose
id.definition: A galloyl-beta-D-glucose compound having four galloyl groups in the 1-, 2-, 3- and 6-positions.

id.name: kievitone hydrate
id.definition: A hydroxyisoflavanone that is isoflavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7, 2' and 4' and a 3-hydroxy-3-methylbutyl group at position 8.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-glutamic acid
id.definition: An N-acyl-L-amino acid that is L-glutamic acid in which one of the amine hydrogens is substituted by an acetyl group.

id.name: L-arabinopyranose
id.definition: The six-membered ring form of L-arabinose.

id.name: allantoate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of allantoic acid.

id.name: Tyr-Arg
id.definition: A dipeptide composed of L-tyrosine and L-arginine joined by a peptide linkage.

id.name: 9-cis,11-trans-octadecadienoate
id.definition: An octadeca-9,11-dienoate that is the conjugate base of 9-cis,11-trans-octadecadienoic acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid functional group.

id.name: methyl beta-D-galactoside
id.definition: A beta-D-galactopyranoside having a methyl substituent at the anomeric position.

id.name: 1-phospho-alpha-D-galacturonic acid
id.definition: An uronic acid phosphate that is alpha-D-galacturonic acid carrying a phosphate group at position 1.

id.name: hydrogencarbonate
id.definition: The carbon oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from carbonic acid.

id.name: (E)-indol-3-ylacetaldehyde oxime
id.definition: An indol-3-ylacetaldehyde oxime in which the oxime moiety has E configuration.

id.name: (2Z)-5-isopropyl-2-methylhexa-2,5-dienal
id.definition: A hexadienal that is hexa-2,5-dienal substituted by a an isopropyl group at position 5 and a methy group at position 2 (the 2Z-stereoisomer).

id.name: alginic acid
id.definition: A linear copolymer macromolecule composed of homopolymeric blocks of 1->4-linked beta-D-mannuronic acid and alpha-L-guluronic acid residues, covalently linked together in different sequences or blocks.

id.name: 5-aminolevulinic acid
id.definition: The simplest delta-amino acid in which the hydrogens at the gamma position are replaced by an oxo group. It is metabolised to protoporphyrin IX, a photoactive compound which accumulates in the skin. Used (in the form of the hydrochloride salt)in combination with blue light illumination for the treatment of minimally to moderately thick actinic keratosis of the face or scalp.

id.name: O-phosphoethanolamine
id.definition: The ethanolamine mono-ester of phosphoric acid, and a metabolite of phospholipid metabolism. This phosphomonoester shows strong structural similarity to the inhibitory neurotransmitter GABA, and is decreased in post-mortem Alzheimer's disease brain.

id.name: phaseollidin
id.definition: A member of the class of pterocarpans that is (6aR,11aR)-pterocarpan substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 9 and a prenyl group at position 10.

id.name: phospholipid cyclopropane fatty acid - not enabled
quercitrin
id.definition: A quercetin O-glycoside that is quercetin substituted by a alpha-L-rhamnosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.

id.name: L-cysteine
id.definition: An optically active form of cysteine having L-configuration.

id.name: cytidine
id.definition: A pyrimidine nucleoside in which cytosine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(1)-glycosidic bond.

id.name: phthalate(2-)
id.definition: A phthalate that is the dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of phthalic acid.

id.name: indole-3-acetonitrile
id.definition: A nitrile that is acetonitrile where one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 1H-indol-3-yl group.

id.name: uracil
id.definition: A common and naturally occurring pyrimidine nucleobase in which the pyrimidine ring is substituted with two oxo groups at positions 2 and 4. Found in RNA, it base pairs with adenine and replaces thymine during DNA transcription.

id.name: beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group
id.definition: An N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group obtained formally by removal of the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine.

id.name: biochanin A
id.definition: A member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is 7-hydroxyisoflavone which is substituted by an additional hydroxy group at position 5 and a methoxy group at position 4'. A phytoestrogen, it has putative benefits in dietary cancer prophylaxis.

id.name: toluene
id.definition: The simplest member of the class toluenes consisting of a benzene core which bears a single methyl substituent.

id.name: beta-carotene
id.definition: A cyclic carotene obtained by dimerisation of all-trans-retinol. A strongly-coloured red-orange pigment abundant in plants and fruit and the most active and important provitamin A carotenoid.

id.name: linalool
id.definition: A monoterpenoid that is octa-1,6-diene substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 7 and a hydroxy group at position 3. It has been isolated from plants like Ocimum canum.

id.name: N-(long-chain-fatty-acyl)-L-glutamate
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of any N-(long-chain-fatty-acyl)-L-glutamic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: trans-hexadec-2-enal
id.definition: A hexadecenal containing a double bond at position 2 (the trans-stereoisomer).

id.name: CoA-glutathione
id.definition: An organic disulfide arising from oxidative coupling of the thiol functions of coenzyme A and glutathione.

id.name: L-gulono-1,4-lactone
id.definition: The furanose form of gulonolactone having L-configuration.

id.name: L-homocysteine
id.definition: Homocysteine with L configuration.

id.name: octane
id.definition: A straight chain alkane composed of 8 carbon atoms.

id.name: N(5)-methyl-L-glutamine
id.definition: An N(5)-alkylglutamine where the alkyl group is specified as methyl.

id.name: maltooligosaccharide
id.definition: A glucooligosaccharide derived from glucose monomers linked via alpha-D-1,4 bonds as in maltose. The term is commonly applied to the series of linear oligosaccharides composed of two, three, four, five and six such units of glucose.

id.name: hydroquinone
id.definition: A benzenediol comprising benzene core carrying two hydroxy substituents para to each other.

id.name: inosine
id.definition: A purine nucleoside in which hypoxanthine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.

id.name: 4-hydroxybenzaldehyde
id.definition: A hydroxybenzaldehyde that is benzaldehyde substituted with a hydroxy group at position C-4.

id.name: 6,7-dimethyl-8-(1-D-ribityl)lumazine
id.definition: The pteridine that is lumazine substituted with methyl groups at C-6 and -7 and with a 1-D-ribityl group on N-8.

id.name: 4-aminophenol
id.definition: An amino phenol (one of the three possible isomers) which has the single amino substituent located para to the phenolic -OH group.

id.name: N(6)-methyl-L-lysine
id.definition: An L-lysine derivative that is L-lysine in which one of the hydrogens attached to N(6) is substituted by a methyl group.

id.name: 2-formylbenzoic acid
id.definition: An aldehydic acid which consists of benzoic acid substituted by a formyl group at position 2. Metabolite of ampicillin phthalidyl ester.

id.name: diiodine
id.definition: Molecule comprising two covalently bonded iodine atoms with overall zero charge..

id.name: D-aldohexose
id.definition: Any D-aldose having a chain of six carbon atoms in the molecule.

id.name: 3-nitroacrylic acid
id.definition: An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is acrylic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 3 is replaced by a nitro group.

id.name: (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)acetate
id.definition: A dihydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)acetic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: all-trans-heptaprenyl diphosphate
id.definition: An all-trans-polyprenyl diphosphate composed from seven isoprenyl units.

id.name: 1,2-diacyl-3-beta-D-galactosyl-sn-glycerol
id.definition: A class of galactoglycerolipids that consists of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol having a beta-D-galactosyl residue attached at position 3.

id.name: all-trans-retinyl palmitate
id.definition: An all-trans-retinyl ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of palmitic (hexadecanoic acid) with the hydroxy group of all-trans-retinol.

id.name: L-fuculose
id.definition: A a deoxyketohexose comprising L-tagatose with the hydroxy group at position 6 replaced by hydrogen.

id.name: ferulic acid
id.definition: A ferulic acid consisting of trans-cinnamic acid bearing methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively on the phenyl ring.

id.name: FMN
id.definition: A flavin mononucleotide that is riboflavin (vitamin B2) in which the primary hydroxy group has been converted to its dihydrogen phosphate ester.

id.name: dUMP

id.name: cortisol

Cortisol is a corticosteroid hormone or glucocorticoid produced by zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex, which is a part of the adrenal gland. It is usually referred to as the "stress hormone" as it is involved in response to stress and anxiety, controlled by corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH). It increases blood pressure and blood sugar, and reduces immune responses

id.definition: An N(2)-acetylglutamine that has L-configuration.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-methionine
id.definition: An L-methionine derivative that is L-methionine in which one of the amine hydrogens is substituted by an acetyl group.

id.name: N-acetyl-amino acid
id.definition: An N-acyl-amino acid that has acetyl as the acyl group.

id.name: N-acyl-L-arginine
id.definition: An N-acyl-L-amino acid that is L-arginine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by any acyl group.

id.name: N-cyclopropylammelide
id.definition: A dihydroxy-1,3,5-triazine consisting of ammelide bearing an N-cyclohexyl substituent.

id.name: N-(long-chain-fatty-acyl)-L-glutamic acid
id.definition: An N-acyl-L-glutamic acid in which the acyl group has a chain length of C12 or greater.

id.name: N-methyl-L-alpha-amino acid
id.definition: An non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid in which the amino group bears one or more methyl groups.

id.name: N-methyl-N'-nitro-N-nitrosoguanidine
id.definition: An N-nitroguanidine compound having nitroso and methyl substituents at the N'-position

id.name: N(2)-methylguanine
id.definition: A methylguanine in which the methyl group is located at the N2-position.

id.name: N(6)-methyladenosine
id.definition: A methyladenosine compound with one methyl group attached to N(6) of the adenine nucleobase.

id.name: O-phosphorylhomoserine
id.definition: An O-phosphoamino acid in which the amino acid specified is homoserine.

id.name: sulfoxide
id.definition: An organosulfur compound having the structure R2S=O or R2C=S=O (R =/= H).

id.name: S-palmitoyl-L-cysteine
id.definition: A palmitoyl-L-cysteine in which the palmitoyl group is attached to the sulfur via a thioester linkage.

id.name: S-phospho-L-cysteine
id.definition: A phosphoamino acid consisting of L-cysteine carrying an S-phospho substituent.

id.name: alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->6)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)]-beta-D-mannosyl group
id.definition: A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->6)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)]-beta-D-mannose.

id.name: alpha-N-substituted L-arginine
id.definition: An L-arginine derivative that is L-arginine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the alpha-nitrogen has replaced by another atom or group.

id.name: beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-D-glucosylceramide
id.definition: A glycotetraosylceramide having beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-D-glucose as the tetrasaccharide component.

id.name: beta-D-glucoside
id.definition: Any D-glucoside in which the anomeric centre has beta-configuration.

id.name: bleomycin
id.definition: A glycopeptide produced by the bacterium Streptomyces verticillus. The term, 'bleomycin' refers to a family of structurally related compounds. When used as an anti-cancer agent, the chemotherapeutical forms are primarily bleomycin A2 and B2.

id.name: cephalosporin
id.definition: A class of beta-lactam antibiotics differing from the penicillins in having a 6-membered, rather than a 5-membered, side ring. Although cephalosporins are among the most commonly used antibiotics in the treatment of routine infections, and their use is increasing over time, they can cause a range of hypersensitivity reactions, from mild, delayed-onset cutaneous reactions to life-threatening anaphylaxis in patients with immunoglobulin E (IgE)-mediated allergy.

id.name: cyanohydrin
id.definition: An alpha-hydroxynitrile resulting from the formal addition of hydrogen cyanide to the C=O bond of an aldehyde or ketone.

id.name: dihydroxyindole
id.definition: Any member of the class of hydroxyindoles carrying two hydroxy groups.

id.name: ecdysteroid
id.definition: A class of steroids that include insect moulting and sex hormones.

id.name: estradiol
id.definition: A 3-hydroxy steroid that is estra-1,3,5(10)-triene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 17.

id.name: ethyl ester
id.definition: Any carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid with ethanol.

id.name: glucosyloxyanthraquinone
id.definition: A monosaccharide derivative that is anthracene-9,10-dione substituted by a beta-D-glucopyranosyloxy group at position 1.

id.name: phosphoglyceric acid
id.definition: An aldonic acid phosphate where the aldonic acid component is glyceric acid.

id.name: glycopeptide
id.definition: Any carbohydrate derivative that consists of glycan moieties covalently attached to the side chains of the amino acid residues that constitute the peptide.

id.name: glycosphingolipid
id.definition: A glycosphingolipid is a glycolipid that is a carbohydrate-containing derivative of a sphingoid or ceramide. It is understood that the carbohydrate residue is attached by a glycosidic linkage to O-1 of the sphingoid.

id.name: hexadecenal
id.definition: A monounsaturated fatty acid aldehyde that is hexadecanal which has undergone formal dehydrogenation to introduce a double bond at unspecified position.

id.name: hexuronate
id.definition: A uronate obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy group of any hexuronic acid.

id.name: hydroquinones
id.definition: Benzenediols that have the hydroxy substituents in the 1- and 4-positions.

id.name: hydroxybenzoic acid
id.definition: Any benzoic acid carrying one or more phenolic hydroxy groups on the benzene ring.

id.name: 4-hydroxyindole
id.definition: A member of the class of hydroxyindoles that is 1H-indole substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.

id.name: hydroxykynurenamine
id.definition: Any kynurenamine carrying a hydroxy substituent.

id.name: indole-3-carboxylic acid
id.definition: An indole-3-carboxylic acid carrying a carboxy group at position 3.

id.name: ketoaldehyde
id.definition: Any compound that has an aldehydic and ketonic group in the same molecule.

id.name: keto-D-gluconate
id.definition: A ketogluconate of D-configuration

id.name: lignan
id.definition: Any phenylpropanoid derived from phenylalanine via dimerization of substituted cinnamic alcohols, known as monolignols, to a dibenzylbutane skeleton. Note that while individual members of the class have names ending ...lignane, ...lignene, ...lignadiene, etc., the class names lignan, neolignan, etc., do not end with an "e".

id.name: lyxose
id.definition: An aldopentose that occurs only rarely in nature.

id.name: melanins
id.definition: Melanin is a class of polyphenol compounds, which mainly serve as pigments in plants, animals and protists. The most common biological form is eumelanin.

id.name: metabolite
id.definition: Any intermediate or product resulting from metabolism. The term 'metabolite' subsumes the classes commonly known as primary and secondary metabolites.

id.name: methylcatechol
id.definition: Any member of the class of catechols carrying one or more methyl substituents.

id.name: neutral glycosphingolipid
id.definition: Any glycosphingolipid containing unsubstituted glycosyl moieties.

id.name: neonicotinoid insectide
id.definition: A class of neuro-active insecticides that act at the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor.

id.name: octadecanoate
id.definition: A fatty acid anion 18:0 that is the conjugate base of octadecanoic acid (stearic acid). Stearates have a variety of uses in the pharmaceutical industry.

id.name: oligopeptide
id.definition: A peptide containing a relatively small number of amino acids.

id.name: N(omega),N'(omega)-dimethyl-L-arginine
id.definition: A L-arginine derivative having two methyl groups at the N(omega)- and N'(omega)-positions

id.name: 1,7-dimethylxanthine
id.definition: A dimethylxanthine having the two methyl groups located at positions 1 and 7. It is a metabolite of caffeine and theobromine in animals.

id.name: pentaerythritol tetranitrate
id.definition: A pentaerythritol nitrate in which all four hydroxy groups of pentaerythritol have been converted to the corresponding nitrate ester. It is a vasodilator with properties similar to those of glyceryl trinitrate, but with a more prolonged duration of action, and is used for treatment of angina pectoris. It is also one of the most powerful high explosives known and is a component of the plastic explosive known as Semtex.

id.name: pinocarveol
id.definition: A pinane monoterpenoid that is a bicyclo[3.1.1]heptane substituted by two methyl groups at position 6, a methylidene group at position 2 and a hydroxy group at position 3.

id.name: polyoxin
id.definition: A group of peptide-pyrimidine nucleoside antibiotics produced by Streptomyces cacaoi var asoensis.

id.name: polyprenol
id.definition: Any member of the class of prenols possessing the general formula H-[CH2C(Me)=CHCH2]nOH in which the carbon skeleton is composed of more than one isoprene units.

id.name: prenylquinone
id.definition: A quinone substituted by a polyprenyl-derived side-chain. Prenylquinones occur in all living cells. Due to their amphiphilic character, they are mainly located in biological membranes where they function as electron and proton carriers in the photosynthetic and respiratory electron transport chains. Some prenylquinones also perform more specialised roles sucy as antioxidants and enzyme cofactors. Prenylquinones are classified according to ring structure: the main classes are menaquinones, phylloquinones, ubiquinones and plastoquinones.

id.name: pterocarpans
id.definition: Members of the class of benzofurochromene with a 6a,11a-dihydro-6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene skeleton and its substituted derivatives. They generally bear structural resemblance to isoflavanoids that possess antibiotic activity and are produced by plant tissues in response to infection. They are the 3,4-dihydroderivatives of coumestans.

id.name: purines
id.definition: A class of imidazopyrimidines that consists of purine and its substituted derivatives.

id.name: saponin
id.definition: A glycoside that is a compound containing one or more hydrophilic glycoside moieties combined with a lipophilic triterpenoid or steroid derivative. Found in particular abundance in plant species.

id.name: selenocystathionine
id.definition: A member of the class of cystathionines derived from homoselenocysteine and serine residues joined by a selenide bond.

id.name: sesterterpenoid
id.definition: Any terpenoid derived from a sesterterpene. The term includes compounds in which the C25 skeleton of the parent sesterterpene has been rearranged or modified by the removal of one or more skeletal atoms (generally methyl groups). Sometimes sesterterpenoids are erroneously referred to as sesterpenoids.

id.name: (2E)-5-isopropyl-2-methylhexa-2,5-dienal
id.definition: A hexadienal that is hexa-2,5-dienal substituted by a an isopropyl group at position 5 and a methy group at position 2 (the 2E-stereoisomer).

id.name: 1D-chiro-inositol
id.definition: Belonging to the inositol family of compounds, D-chiro-inositol (DCI) is an isomer of glucose. It is an important secondary messenger in insulin signal transduction.

id.name: pantothenol
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid amide that is 3,3-dimethylbutanamide substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 4 and a 3-hydroxypropyl group at the carbomyl nitrogen.

id.name: methanesulfonic acid
id.definition: An alkanesulfonic acid in which the alkyl group directly linked to the sulfo functionality is methyl.

id.name: (2S,3R)-aldopyranose
id.definition: Any aldose having 2S,3R-threo stereochemistry. A representative structure is provided.

id.name: 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-24-oxo-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA
id.definition: A cholestanoyl-CoA formed by thioester linkage between 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-24-oxo-5beta-cholestan-26-oic acid and coenzyme A.

id.name: 2,2',3-trihydroxydiphenyl ether
id.definition: Diphenyl ether in which the hydrogens at the 2, 3, and 2' positions are substituted by hydroxy groups.

id.name: 2-thienylacetonitrile
id.definition: A nitrile that is acetonitrile where one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 2-thienyl group.

id.name: 3-(4-oxo-4,5-dihydro-1H-imidazol-5-yl)propanoic acid
id.definition: An imidazol-4-one having a 2-carboxyethyl substituent at the 5-position.

id.name: tetrachloromethane
id.definition: A chlorocarbon that is methane in which all the hydrogens have been replaced by chloro groups.

id.name: cinnamic acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that consists of acrylic acid bearing a phenyl substituent at the 3-position. It is found in Cinnamomum cassia.

id.name: benzoylacetyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of benzoylacetic acid.

id.name: 3-aminoisobutyric acid
id.definition: A beta-amino-acid that is isobutyric acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by an amino group.

id.name: omega-aminoaldehyde
id.definition: An amino aldehyde that is an aliphatic aldehyde in which one of the hydrogens of the terminal methyl group has been replaced by an amino group. H2NCH2(CH2)nCHO, where n = 0, 1, 2, etc.

id.name: UDP-3-O-(3-hydroxytetradecanoyl)-D-glucosamine
id.definition: A UDP-amino sugar having 3-O-(3-hydroxytetradecanoyl)-D-glucosamine as the amino sugar component.

id.name: 1,2,6-tris-O-galloyl-beta-D-glucose
id.definition: A galloyl-beta-D-glucose compound having the galloyl groups in the 1-, 2- and 6-positions.

id.name: deisopropylatrazine
id.definition: A diamino-1,3,5-triazine that is N-ethyl-1,3,5-triazine-2,4-diamine substituted by a chloro group at position 6.

id.name: (S)-3-hydroxypalmitoyl-CoA
id.definition: A long-chain (3S)-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (S)-3-hydroxypalmitic acid.

id.name: 3alpha,7alpha,24-trihydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA
id.definition: A cholestanoyl-CoA formed by thioester linkage between 3alpha,7alpha,24-trihydroxy-5beta-cholestanoic acid and coenzyme A.

id.name: streptidine
id.definition: An amino cyclitol that is scyllo-inositol in which the hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 3 are replaced by guanidino groups.

id.name: kinetin
id.definition: A member of the class of 6-aminopurines that is adenine carrying a (furan-2-ylmethyl) substituent at the exocyclic amino group.

id.name: manniflavanone
id.definition: A biflavonoid isolated from Garcinia buchananii and has been shown to exhibit antioxidant activity.

id.name: N-methyl-6-pyridone-3-carboxamide
id.definition: A pyridone that is 2-pyridone substituted with a carboxamide group at C-5 and a methyl group at N-1.

id.name: beta-aminopropionitrile
id.definition: An aminopropionitrile carrying an amino group at the beta-position.

id.name: p-xylene
id.definition: A xylene with methyl groups at positions 1 and 4.

id.name: 1,4-naphthoquinone
id.definition: The parent structure of the family of 1,4-naphthoquinones, in which the oxo groups of the quinone moiety are at positions 1 and 4 of the naphthalene ring. Derivatives have pharmacological properties.

id.name: dehydrodeoxycoformycin
id.definition: A coformycin that is dehydrocoformycin with the hydroxy group at position 2 replaced with a hydrogen.

id.name: (KDO)2-(lauroyl)-lipid IVA
id.definition: A lipid A comprising lipid IVA glycosylated with two 3-deoxy-D-manno-octulosonic acid (KDO) residues and carrying an additional dodecanoyl group.

id.name: N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminide
id.definition: Any N-acetyl-D-glucosaminide having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.

id.name: 7-O-methylluteone
id.definition: A hydroxyisoflavone that is luteone in which the hydroxy group at position 7 is replaced by a methoxy group.

id.name: alpha-linolenic acid
id.definition: A linolenic acid with cis-double bonds at positions 9, 12 and 15. Shown to have an antithrombotic effect.

id.name: gibberellin A53
id.definition: A C20-gibberellin that consists of a tetracyclic skeleton carrying two carboxy substituents.

id.name: o-tolualdehyde
id.definition: A tolualdehyde compound with the methyl substituent at the 2-position.

id.name: 1-methylpyrrolinium
id.definition: An organic cation that is 1-pyrroline bearing an N-methyl substituent.

id.name: methyltestosterone
id.definition: A 17beta-hydroxy steroid that is testosterone bearing a methyl group at the 17alpha position.

id.name: (KDO)-lipid IVA
id.definition: Lipid IVA glycosylated with a single 3-deoxy-D-manno-octulosonic acid (KDO) residue.

id.name: 3-methoxyanthranilic acid
id.definition: An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid in which the hydrogen at position 3 is substituted by a methoxy group. It is a metabolite of kynurenine.

id.name: D-prephenyl lactate
id.definition: A carboxylic acid having D-lactic acid as the carboxylic acid component and a 3-hydroxycyclohexa-1,4-diene as the alcohol component.

id.name: beta-D-fucose
id.definition: A D-fucopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: but-3-yn-1-ol
id.definition: A terminal acetylenic compound that is but-1-yne with one of the methyl hydrogens substituted by a hydroxy group.

id.name: maltohexaose
id.definition: A maltohexaose hexasaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the aldehydo open-chain form.

id.name: phenoxymethylpenicillin
id.definition: A penicillin compound having a 6beta-(phenoxyacetyl)amino side-chain.

id.name: lutein 5,6-epoxide
id.definition: An epoxycarotenol derivative of lutein.

id.name: N-propanoylimidazole
id.definition: An N-acylimidazole compound having propanoyl as the acyl group.

id.name: N-3,5-dichloro-4-hydroxyphenyl-1,4-benzoquinone imine
id.definition: 1,4-benzoquinone imine having a 3,5-dichloro-4-hydroxyphenyl substituent attached to the nitrogen atom.

id.name: styrene
id.definition: A vinylarene that is benzene carrying a vinyl group. It has been isolated from the benzoin resin produced by Styrax species.

id.name: 1-chloro-2,2-bis(4'-chlorophenyl)ethylene
id.definition: A chlorophenylethylene that is chloroethene in which the methylene hydrogens are replaced by 4-chlorophenyl groups.

id.name: trichloroacetate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion that results from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of trichloroacetic acid.

id.name: undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetyl-(N-acetylglucosaminyl)muramoyl-L-alanyl-D-isoglutaminyl-(glycyl)5-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine
id.definition: An undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetylmuramoyl peptide in which the peptide moiety is L-alanyl-D-isoglutaminyl-N(6)-pentaglycyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine.

id.name: 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha,24-tetrahydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA
id.definition: A cholestanoyl-CoA formed by thioester linkage between 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha,24-tetrahydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oic acid and coenzyme A.

id.name: N-glycoloyl-D-glucosamine
id.definition: An N-glycoloylglucosamine of D configuration.

id.name: (S)-3-hydroxytetradecanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A long-chain (3S)-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (S)-3-hydroxytetradecanoic acid.

id.name: 5,6-dihydrothymine
id.definition: A pyrimidone obtained by formal addition of hydrogen across the 5,6-position of thymine.

id.name: 2-dehydro-D-gluconic acid
id.definition: A ketoaldonic acid that is D-gluconic acid in which the hydroxy group at position 2 has been oxidised to a keto group.

id.name: folic acid
id.definition: An N-acyl-amino acid that is a form of the water-soluble vitamin B9. Its biologically active forms (tetrahydrofolate and others) are essential for nucleotide biosynthesis and homocysteine remethylation.

id.name: glycodeoxycholic acid
id.definition: A bile acid glycine conjugate of deoxycholic acid.

id.name: cyanidin 3-O-beta-D-galactoside
id.definition: An anthocyanin cation that is cyanidin(1+) carrying a single beta-D-galactosyl substituent at position 3.

id.name: beta-D-ribopyranose
id.definition: A D-ribopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: D-valine
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of valine.

id.name: 2'-hydroxydaidzein
id.definition: A hydroxyisoflavone that is daidzein bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at position 2'.

id.name: phenylacetylglycine
id.definition: A N-acylglycine that is glycine substituted on nitrogen with a phenylacetyl group.

id.name: prostaglandin J2
id.definition: A member of the class of prostaglandins J that consists of prosta-5,9,13-trien-1-oic acid substituted by an oxo group at position 11 and a hydroxy group at position 15 (the 5Z,13E,15S stereoisomer).

id.name: 16,17-didehydropregnenolone
id.definition: A 3beta-hydroxy steroid that is pregnenolone with a double bond between positions 16 and 17.

id.name: 3-(imidazol-5-yl)lactic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is lactic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by an imidazol-5-yl group.

id.name: 2-fluorobenzoyl-CoA
id.definition: A fluorobenzoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-fluorobenzoic acid.

id.name: leukotriene F4
id.definition: A leukotriene composed of (7E,9E,11Z,14Z)-icosa-7,9,11,14-tetraenoic acid having (5S)-hydroxy and (6R)-(L-gamma-glutamyl-L-cystein-S-yl) substituents.

id.name: juvenile hormone III
id.definition: A member of the juvenile hormone family of compounds that is the methyl ester of (2E,6E)-9-[(2R)-3,3-dimethyloxiran-2-yl]-3,7-dimethylnona-2,6-dienoic acid. Juvenile hormone III is found in most insect species.

id.name: sophoraisoflavanone A
id.definition: A hydroxyisoflavanone that is isoflavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7 and 4', a methoxy substituent at position 2' and a prenyl group at position 3'.

id.name: simazine
id.definition: A diamino-1,3,5-triazine that is N,N'-diethyl-1,3,5-triazine-2,4-diamine substituted by a chloro group at position 6.

id.name: dTDP-4-dehydro-3-methyl-2,6-dideoxy-beta-L-glucose
id.definition: A dTDP-sugar having 4-dehydro-3-methyl-2,6-dideoxy-beta-L-glucose as the sugar component.

id.name: N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosylceramide
id.definition: A sialomonoglycosylceramide having N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosyl as the sialomonoglycosyl component.

id.name: 4-aminobenzenesulfonic acid
id.definition: An aminobenzenesulfonic acid that is aniline sulfonated at the para-position.

id.name: aldehydo-D-mannosamine
id.definition: A D-mannosamine in open-chain aldehydo-form.

id.name: 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5beta-cholest-24-en-26-oyl-CoA
id.definition: A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5beta-cholest-24-en-26-oic acid.

id.name: neoglucobrassicin
id.definition: An indolyl carbohydrate that is glucobrassicin methoxy substituted at position 1 of the indole moiety.

id.name: cinchonine
id.definition: Cinchonan in which a hydrogen at position 9 is substituted by hydroxy (S configuration). It occurs in the bark of most varieties of Cinchona shrubs, and is frequently used for directing chirality in asymmetric synthesis.

id.name: umbelliferone
id.definition: A hydroxycoumarin that is coumarin substituted by a hydroxy group ay position 7.

id.name: precorrin-6X
id.definition: The intermediate in the biosynthesis of vitamin B12 from uroporphyrinogen III in which six methyl groups have been introduced into the tetrapyrrole framework, together with ring contraction.

id.name: alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->8)-alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)-beta-Gal-(1->3)-beta-GalNAc-(1->4)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->8)-alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)]-beta-Gal-(1->4)-beta-Glc-(1-1')-Cer
id.definition: A sialotetraosylceramide consisting of a branched octasaccharide made up from four sialyl residues, two galactose residues, one N-acetylglucosamine residue and a glucose residue at the reducing end attached to the ceramide portion via a beta-linkage.

id.name: rutinose
id.definition: A glycosylglucose in which the glycosyl moiety is L-rhamnose linked alpha to C-6 of D-glucose.

id.name: 3-(6-hydroxyindol-3-yl)lactate
id.definition: The hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(6-hydroxyindol-3-yl)lactic acid.

id.name: 2-fluoroaniline
id.definition: A derivative of aniline in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been substituted by fluorine. It is used as a pharmaceutical intermediate

id.name: P(1),P(2)-bis(5'-adenosyl) triphosphate
id.definition: A diadenosyl triphosphate having the two 5'-adenosyl residues attached at the P(1)- and P(2)-positions.

id.name: 4-hydroxy-2-oxohexanoic acid
id.definition: A hydroxy- and oxo- fatty acid comprising hexanoic acid substituted at C-2 and C-4 with oxo and hydroxy groups respectively.

id.name: L-cysteine thioether
id.definition: Any L-cysteine derivative obtained by conversion of the thiol group into a sulfide.

id.name: trans-oct-2-enoyl-CoA
id.definition: An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of trans-oct-2-enoic acid.

id.name: isatin
id.definition: An indoledione that is the 2,3-diketo derivative of indole.

id.name: hexanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A medium-chain fatty acyl-CoA having hexanoyl as the S-acyl group.

id.name: 3',5'-cyclic IMP
id.definition: A 3',5'-cyclic purine nucleotide having hypoxanthine as the nucleobase.

id.name: methyl oleate
id.definition: A fatty acid methyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of oleic acid with methanol.

id.name: 2,5-dichlorohydroquinone
id.definition: A dichlorohydroquinone that is hydroquinone substituted by chloro groups at positions 2 and 5 respectively.

id.name: O(6)-methyl-2'-deoxyguanosine
id.definition: A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside having O(6)-methylguanine as the nucleobase.

id.name: 5-methylcytosine
id.definition: A pyrimidine that is a derivative of cytosine, having a methyl group at the 5-position.

id.name: 4'-methoxy-5,7-dihydroxyflavanone
id.definition: A dihydroxyflavanone that is flavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 7 and a methoxy group at position 4' (the 2S stereoisomer).

id.name: alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannose
id.definition: The beta-anomer of alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->3)-D-mannopyranose

id.name: prostaglandin C2

id.definition: A member of the class of thromboxanes B that is (5Z,13E)-thromboxa-5,13-dien-1-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 9, 11 and 15.

id.name: alpha-D-mannose
id.definition: D-Mannopyranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.

id.name: gibberellin A19
id.definition: A C20-gibberellin.

id.name: 1-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine
