id.name: 4-nitroacetophenone
id.definition: A member of the class of acetophenones that is acetophenone substituted at the para-position by a nitro group.

id.name: formyl-5-hydroxykynurenamine
id.definition: A hydroxykynurenamine that is 5-hydroxykynurenamine with the hydrogen on the aryl amine replaced by a formyl group.

id.name: 2,6-dimethylaniline
id.definition: A primary arylamine that is aniline in which the hydrogens at the 2- and 6-positions are replaced by methyl groups. It is used in the production of some anasthetics and other chemicals. It is a drug metabolite of lidocaine (local anasthetic).

id.name: sodium fluoride
id.definition: A metal fluoride salt with a Na(+) counterion.

id.name: alpha-L-Fuc-(1->2)-beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc-(1->1')-Cer
id.definition: A glycopentaosylceramide having alpha-L-Fuc-(1->2)-beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the glycopentaosyl component.

id.name: 2-hydroxy-17beta-estradiol
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy steroid that consists of 17beta-estradiol having an additional hydroxy group at position 2.

id.name: picolinic acid
id.definition: A pyridinemonocarboxylic acid in which the carboxy group is located at position 2. It is an intermediate in the metabolism of tryptophan.

id.name: 17alpha-hydroxypregnenolone
id.definition: A hydroxypregnenolone carrying an alpha-hydroxy group at position 17.

id.name: biochanin A 7-O-beta-D-glucoside
id.definition: A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is biochanin A attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via glycosidic linkage.

id.name: 3,4-dihydroxyfluorene
id.definition: A member of the class of hydroxyfluorenes that is 9H-fluorene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4.

id.name: 2,4,6-trichlorophenol
id.definition: A trichlorophenol with phenolic substituents on positions 2, 4 and 6.

id.name: fructose
id.definition: A ketohexose that is an isomer of glucose.

id.name: 1D-6-O-methyl-myo-inositol
id.definition: A member of the class of methyl myo-inositols that is cyclohexane-1,2,3,4,5-pentol substituted by a methoxy group at position 6 ( the 1R,2R,3R,4R,5S,6R-isomer).

id.name: 4,4'-dichlorodiphenylmethane
id.definition: A chlorophenylmethane that is methane in which two of the hydrogens have been replaced by p-chlorophenyl groups.

id.name: phosphatidylinositol phosphate
id.definition: Any member of the phosphoinositide family of compounds, of which seven occur naturally.

id.name: p-cymene
id.definition: A monoterpene that is toluene substituted by an isopropyl group at position 4.

id.name: alpha-licanic acid
id.definition: A trienoic fatty acid comprising alpha-eleostearic acid having a 4-oxo substituent.

id.name: hesperidin
id.definition: A disaccharide derivative that consists of hesperetin substituted by a 6-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.

id.name: liquiritigenin
id.definition: A dihydroxyflavanone compound having the two hydroxy substituents at the 4'- and 7-positions. Isolated from the root of Glycyrrhizae uralensis, it is a selective agonist for oestrogen receptor beta.

id.name: 1-S-hexadecyl-2-O-[hexadecyl(hydroxy)phosphoryl]-1-thio-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine
id.definition: A 1-thio-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine compound having 1-S-hexadecyl- and 2-O-hexadecylphosphono substituents.

id.name: gentianose
id.definition: A trisaccharide composed of beta-D-glucopyranose, alpha-D-glucopyranose and beta-D-fructofuranose units.

id.name: nitroglycerin
id.definition: A nitroglycerol that is glycerol in which the hydrogen atoms of all three hydroxy groups are replaced by nitro groups. It acts as a prodrug, releasing nitric oxide to open blood vessels and so alleviate heart pain.

id.name: L-glucitol
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of glucitol.

id.name: serotonin
id.definition: A primary amino compound that is the 5-hydroxy derivative of tryptamine.

id.name: isoglutamic acid
id.definition: A 1,5-dicarboxylic acid compound having a 3-amino substituent. It has been isolated from the extracts of the algae, Chondria armata.

id.name: erucic acid
id.definition: A docosenoic acid having a cis- double bond at C-13. It is found particularly in brassicas - it is a major component of mustard and rapeseed oils and is produced by broccoli, Brussels sprouts, kale, and wallflowers.

id.name: coumarin
id.definition: A chromenone having the keto group located at the 2-position.

id.name: m-toluate
id.definition: A toluate that is the conjugate base of m-toluic acid.

id.name: fructan
id.definition: Polysaccharides composed of fructose residues.

id.name: D-alpha-aminobutyric acid
id.definition: An optically active form of alpha-aminobutyric acid having D-configuration.

id.name: rubber particle
id.definition: A polymer consisting of cis-linked prenyl units.

id.name: quinoline-4,6-diol
id.definition: Quinoline substituted by hydroxy groups at the 4- and 6-positions. It is the product of 5-hydroxytryptophan metabolism, via monoamine oxidase catalysed conversion of 5-hydroxykynurenamine.

id.name: stearolic acid
id.definition: An octadecynoic acid having its triple bond at position 9.

id.name: flavonols
id.definition: Any hydroxyflavone in which is the ring hydrogen at position 3 of the heterocyclic ring is replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: D-2-aminopentanoic acid
id.definition: A 2-aminopentanoic acid that has R-configuration.

id.name: 2'-deoxyinosine-5'-monophosphate
id.definition: A deoxyinosine phosphate that is 5'-inosinic acid in which the hydroxy group at position 2' by a hydrogen atom.

id.name: dITP
id.definition: A deoxyinosine phosphate compound having a triphosphate group at the 5'-position.

id.name: (1S,2S)-1,2-dihydronaphthalene-1,2-diol
id.definition: The (1S,2S)-isomer of trans-1,2-dihydronaphthalene-1,2-diol.

id.name: (aminomethyl)phosphonic acid
id.definition: A member of the class of phosphonic acids that is phosphonic acid substituted by an aminomethyl group. It is a metabolite of the herbicide glyphosate.

id.name: sinapyl alcohol
id.definition: A primary alcohol, being cinnamyl alcohol hydroxylated at C-4 and methoxylated at C-3 and -5.

id.name: piceatannol
id.definition: A stilbenol that is trans-stilbene in which one of the phenyl groups is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4, while the other phenyl group is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 5.

id.name: heparan sulfate
id.definition: A linear polysaccharide in which the backbone consists of a variably sulfated repeating disaccharide unit.

id.name: 2-deoxy-D-ribose
id.definition: A deoxypentose that is D-ribose in which the hydroxy group at position C-2 is replaced by hydrogen.

id.name: dodecane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with 12 carbon atoms. It has been form the essential oils of various plants including Zingiber officinale (ginger).

id.name: naringin
id.definition: A disaccharide derivative that is (S)-naringenin substituted by a 2-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.

id.name: 9-phenanthrol
id.definition: A phenanthrol that is phenanthrene in which a hydrogen attached to a carbon in the central ring has been replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: piperine
id.definition: A N-acylpiperidine that is piperidine substituted by a (1E,3E)-1-(1,3-benzodioxol-5-yl)-5-oxopenta-1,3-dien-5-yl group at the nitrogen atom. It is an alkaloid isolated from the plant Piper nigrum.

id.name: arachidic acid
id.definition: A C20 striaght-chain saturated fatty acid which forms a minor constituent of peanut (L. arachis) and corn oils. Used as an organic thin film in the production of liquid crystals for a wide variety of technical applications.

id.name: 2'-deoxyinosine-5'-diphosphate
id.definition: A deoxyinosine phosphate compound having a diphosphate group at the 5'-position.

id.name: stigmasterol
id.definition: A 3beta-sterol that consists of 3beta-hydroxystigmastane having double bonds at the 5,6- and 22,23-positions.

id.name: beta-alanine betaine
id.definition: A beta-alanine derivative arising from quaternisation of the nitrogen of beta-alanine with three methyl groups and removal of the proton attached to the carboxy group. It is an osmoprotective compound accumulated by most members of the highly stress-tolerant Plumbaginaceae family.

id.name: fluoromethane
id.definition: A member of the class of fluoromethanes that is methane in which a single hydrogen is substituted by a fluorine atom.

id.name: ethyl N-acetyl-L-tyrosinate
id.definition: An L-tyrosine derivative that is the ethyl ester of N-acetyltyrosine.

id.name: aminophenol
id.definition: A substituted aniline carrying a hydroxy substituent.

id.name: chlorambucil
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that is butanoic acid substituted at position 4 by a 4-[bis(2-chloroethyl)amino]phenyl group. A chemotherapy drug that can be used in combination with the antibody obinutuzumab for the treatment of chronic lymphocytic leukemia.

id.name: propan-1-ol
id.definition: The parent member of the class of propan-1-ols that is propane in which a hydrogen of one of the methyl groups is replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: androsterone 3-glucosiduronic acid
id.definition: A steroid glucosiduronic acid having androsterone as the steroid component.

id.name: gibberellin A3
id.definition: A C19-gibberellin that is a pentacyclic diterpenoid responsible for promoting growth and elongation of cells in plants.

id.name: deoxycholic acid
id.definition: A bile acid that is 5beta-cholan-24-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 12 respectively.

id.name: testosterone 17-glucosiduronic acid
id.definition: A steroid glucosiduronic that is testosterone carrying a glucosiduronic acid residue at position 17.

id.name: octanoic acid
id.definition: A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is heptane in which one of the hydrogens of a terminal methyl group has been replaced by a carboxy group. Octanoic acid is also known as caprylic acid.

id.name: 3-disulfanyl-L-alanine
id.definition: An S-substituted L-cysteine where the S-substituent is specified as sulfanyl.

id.name: octadecanoic acid
id.definition: A C18 straight-chain saturated fatty acid component of many animal and vegetable lipids. As well as in the diet, it is used in hardening soaps, softening plastics and in making cosmetics, candles and plastics.

id.name: dCDP
id.definition: A 2'-deoxycytidine phosphate that is the 2'- deoxy derivative of cytidine 5'-diphosphate (CDP).

id.name: naphthazarin
id.definition: A naphthoquinone that is 1,4-naphthoquinone in which the hydrogens at positions 5 and 8 are replaced by hydroxy groups.

id.name: phenanthrene
id.definition: A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon composed of three fused benzene rings which takes its name from the two terms 'phenyl' and 'anthracene.'

id.name: 2,4-D
id.definition: A chlorophenoxyacetic acid that is phenoxyacetic acid in which the ring hydrogens at postions 2 and 4 are substituted by chlorines.

id.name: enterobactin
id.definition: A siderophore produced by certain members of Enterobacteriaceae, e.g. Escherichia coli and Salmonella.

id.name: p-toluate
id.definition: A toluate that is the conjugate base of p-toluic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: (Z)-hex-3-en-1-ol

id.name: 5alpha-androstane
id.definition: The 5alpha-stereoisomer of androstane.

id.name: beta-D-glucuronic acid

id.name: gibberellin A8
id.definition: A C19-gibberellin.

id.name: dGDP
id.definition: A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-diphosphate having guanine as the nucleobase.

id.name: flavanones
id.definition: Members of the class of flavans with a 3,4-dihydro-2-aryl-2H-1-benzopyran-4-one skeleton and its substituted derivatives.

id.name: tobramycin
id.definition: A amino cyclitol glycoside that is kanamycin B lacking the 3-hydroxy substituent from the 2,6-diaminoglucose ring.

id.name: taurocholic acid
id.definition: A bile acid taurine conjugate of cholic acid that usually occurs as the sodium salt of bile in mammals.

id.name: tetracosanoic acid
id.definition: A C24 straight-chain saturated fatty acid.

id.name: O-propanoylcarnitine
id.definition: An O-acylcarnitine compound having propanoyl as the acyl substituent.

id.name: fatty acid anion
id.definition: The conjugate base of a fatty acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of the corresponding fatty acid.

id.name: menadione
id.definition: A member of the class of 1,4-naphthoquinones that is 1,4-naphthoquinone which is substituted at position 2 by a methyl group. It is used as a nutritional supplement and for the treatment of hypoprothrombinemia.

id.name: 6-methylaminopurine
id.definition: A 6-alkylaminopurine that is 9H-purin-6-amine substituted by a methyl group at the amino nitrogen.

id.name: o-toluate
id.definition: A toluate that is the conjugate base of o-toluic acid.

id.name: cis-2-coumaric acid
id.definition: The cis-isomer of 2-coumaric acid.

id.name: phosphatidylinositol
id.definition: Any glycerophosphoinositol having one phosphatidyl group esterified to one of the hydroxy groups of inositol.

id.name: tetradecanoic acid
id.definition: A straight-chain, fourteen-carbon, long-chain saturated fatty acid mostly found in milk fat.

id.name: melphalan
id.definition: A phenylalanine derivative comprising L-phenylalanine having [bis(2-chloroethyl)amino group at the 4-position on the phenyl ring.

id.name: dodecan-1-ol
id.definition: A fatty alcohol that is dodecane in which a hydrogen from one of the methyl groups is replaced by a hydroxy group. It is registered for use in apple and pear orchards as a Lepidopteran pheromone/sex attractant, used to disrupt the mating behaviour of certain moths whose larvae destroy crops.

id.name: 9-O-acetylneuraminic acid
id.definition: The acetate ester of the primary hydroxy group of neuraminic acid.

id.name: (S)-mevalonic acid
id.definition: The (S)-enantiomer of mevalonic acid.

id.name: 2-benzoylsuccinyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-benzoylsuccinic acid.

id.name: N-phenylacetamide
id.definition: A member of the class of acetamides that is acetamide in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a phenyl group.

id.name: butan-1-ol
id.definition: A primary alcohol that is butane in which a hydrogen of one of the methyl groups is substituted by a hydroxy group. It it produced in small amounts in humans by the gut microbes.

id.name: dimethyl ether
id.definition: An ether in which the oxygen atom is connected to two methyl groups.

id.name: ganglioside
id.definition: A molecule composed of a glycosphingolipid (ceramide and oligosaccharide) with one or more sialic acids linked on the sugar chain.

id.name: 1-O-alkyl-2-O-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine
id.definition: A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the 2-O-acyl component is specifed as arachidonoyl.

id.name: 3'-UMP
id.definition: A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 3'-monophosphate having uracil as the nucleobase.

id.name: pentadecane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with 15 carbon atoms. It is a component of volatile oils isolated from plants species like Scandix balansae.

id.name: P(1),P(5)-bis(5'-adenosyl) pentaphosphate
id.definition: A diadenosyl pentaphosphate having the two 5'-adenosyl residues attached at the P(1)- and P(5)-positions.

id.name: N-alkylphthalic monoamide
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid monoamide resulting from formal condensation between one of the carboxy groups of phthalic acid with any primary alkylamine.

id.name: busulfan
id.definition: A methanesulfonate ester that is butane-1,4-diol in which the hydrogens of the hydroxy groups are replaced by methanesulfonyl groups. An alkylating antineoplastic agent, it is used for the treatment of chronic myeloid leukemia (although it has been largely replaced by newer drugs). It is also used as an insect sterilant.

id.name: N-phenylhydroxylamine
id.definition: An N-substituted amine that is a derivative of aniline in which one of the amino hydrogen atoms is replaced with a hydroxy substituent.

id.name: decan-1-ol
id.definition: A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at C-1 of an unbranched saturated chain of ten carbon atoms.

id.name: N-formylisoglutamic acid
id.definition: A 1,5-dicarboxylic acid compound having a 3-formamido substituent.

id.name: prop-2-yn-1-ol
id.definition: A terminal acetylenic compound that is prop-2-yne substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1.

id.name: 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid
id.definition: A bisphosphoglyceric acid that is glyceric acid carrying two phospho substituents at positions 2 and 3.

id.name: bambermycin
id.definition: A glycophospholipid antibiotic compound with the lipid portion conjugated to a pentasaccharide fraction via a phosphate linkage.

id.name: iprodione
id.definition: An imidazolidine-2,4-dione in which the nitrogen at position 1 is substituted by an N-(isopropyl)carboxamide group while that at position 3 is substituted by a 3,5-dichlorophenyl group. A contact fungicide, it blocks the growth of the fungal mycelium and inhibits the germination of fungal spores. It is used on fruit and vegetable crops affected by various fungal diseases. It is also used as a nematicide.

id.name: cob(III)alamin
id.definition: A cobalamin in which the central cobalt atom has an oxidation state of +3.

id.name: limit dextrin
id.definition: Limit dextrin is the remaining polymer produced by enzymatic hydrolysis of amylopectine with an amylase.

id.name: (2E)-hexenal
id.definition: A 2-hexenal in which the olefinic double bond has E configuration. It occurs naturally in a wide range of fruits, vegetables, and spices.

id.name: 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-D-myo-inositol
id.definition: A 1-acylglycerophosphoinositol in which sn-glycerol, acylated at O(1), is linked through a phospho group at O(3) to O(1) of D-myo-inositol.

id.name: fosfomycin
id.definition: A phosphonic acid having an (R,S)-1,2-epoxypropyl group attached to phosphorus.

id.name: dihydromyricetin
id.definition: A hexahydroxyflavanone that is the 2,3-dihydro derivative of myricetin.

id.name: (R)-adrenaline
id.definition: The R-enantiomer of adrenaline. It is a hormone secreted by the adrenal glands resulting in the 'fight-or-flight' response.

id.name: estrone 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide)
id.definition: The 3-beta-D-glucuronide of estrone.

id.name: N-acetyl-alpha-D-muramoyl-L-alanine
id.definition: A glyco-amino acid compound consisting of an N-acetyl-alpha-D-muramoyl group attached to L-alanine via an amide linkage.

id.name: 7-methyladenine
id.definition: Adenine substituted with a methyl group at position N-7.

id.name: prostaglandin F2beta
id.definition: A prostaglandins Falpha that is prosta-5,13-dien-1-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 9, 11 and 15. It is the 9beta-hydroxy epimer of prostaglandin F2alpha.

id.name: 3-aminophenol
id.definition: An aminophenol that is one of three amino derivatives of phenol which has the single amino substituent located meta to the phenolic -OH group.

id.name: sakuranetin
id.definition: A flavonoid phytoalexin that is (S)-naringenin in which the hydroxy group at position 7 is replaced by a methoxy group.

id.name: 3'-AMP
id.definition: An adenosine 3'-phosphate with a monophosphate group at the 3'-position.

id.name: laetisaric acid
id.definition: A C18, straight-chain, hydroxy fatty acid composed of linoleic acid having an (R)-hydroxy group at the 8-position.

id.name: (25R)-5beta-spirostan-3beta-ol
id.definition: An oxaspiro compound that is(5beta,25R)-spirostan substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3.

id.name: vitamin D2
id.definition: A vitamin D supplement and has been isolated from alfalfa.

id.name: (E)-hexadec-2-enoyl-CoA
id.definition: A hexadec-2-enoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (E)-hexadec-2-enoic acid.

id.name: 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine
id.definition: A lysophosphatidylethanolamine obtained by selective hydrolysis of the 1-acyl substituent of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.

id.name: (-)-abscisic acid
id.definition: The (1'R)-(-) enantiomer of abscisic acid, which does not occur naturally.

id.name: ammonium
id.definition: An onium cation obtained by protonation of ammonia.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-cysteine
id.definition: An N-acetyl-L-amino acid that is the N-acetylated derivative of the natural amino acid L-cysteine.

id.name: calciol
id.definition: A hydroxy seco-steroid that is (5Z,7E)-9,10-secocholesta-5,7,10(19)-triene in which the pro-S hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a hydroxy group. It is the inactive form of vitamin D3, being hydroxylated in the liver to calcidiol (25-hydroxyvitamin D3), which is then further hydroxylated in the kidney to give calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3), the active hormone.

id.name: behenic acid
id.definition: A straight-chain, C22, long-chain saturated fatty acid.

id.name: CDP-alpha-D-glucose
id.definition: A CDP-D-glucose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.

id.name: N-acylsphingosine 1-phosphoethanolamine
id.definition: A ceramide phosphoethanolamine in which the sphingoid component is specified as sphing-4-enine (sphingosine).

id.name: theobromine
id.definition: A dimethylxanthine having the two methyl groups located at positions 3 and 7. A purine alkaloid derived from the cacao plant, it is found in chocolate, as well as in a number of other foods, and is a vasodilator, diuretic and heart stimulator.

id.name: (5-oxo-2-sulfo-2,5-dihydrofuran-2-yl)acetic acid
id.definition: An organosulfonic acid that consists of 5-oxo-2-furylacetic acid bearing a sulfo group at position 2.

id.name: gramine
id.definition: An aminoalkylindole that is indole carrying a dimethylaminomethyl substituent at postion 3.

id.name: N-methyl-N-picrylnitramine
id.definition: A nitramine that is methylamine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a nitro group while the other is substituted by a 2,4,6-trinitrophenyl group. A yellow crystalline powder, it is a high explosive, capable of being detonated by friction, shock, or a spark.

id.name: 5alpha-pregnane-3,20-dione
id.definition: A C21-steroid hormone that is 5alpha-pregnane substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 20. It is a metabolite of progestrone.

id.name: 2-methoxy-17beta-estradiol
id.definition: A 17beta-hydroxy steroid, being 17beta-estradiol methoxylated at C-2.

id.name: 3-methyl-cis,cis-muconic acid
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid that is cis,cis-muconic acid in which the hydrogens at position 3 is substituted by a methyl group.

id.name: amino sugar
id.definition: Any sugar having one or more alcoholic hydroxy groups replaced by substituted or unsubstituted amino groups.

id.name: phenoxyacetyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of phenoxyacetic acid.

id.name: dicarboxylic acid dianion
id.definition: A carboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any dicarboxylic acid.

id.name: N,N-dimethyltryptamine
id.definition: A tryptamine derivative having two N-methyl substituents on the side-chain.

id.name: biphenyl-2,2'-diol
id.definition: A member of the class of hydroxybiphenyls carrying hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 2'.

id.name: ampicillin
id.definition: A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a 2-amino-2-phenylacetamido group.

id.name: strychnine
id.definition: A monoterpenoid indole alkaloid that is strychnidine bearing a keto substituent at the 10-position.

id.name: (1S,2R)-3-(4-chlorophenyl)cyclohexa-3,5-diene-1,2-diol
id.definition: A cyclohexenediol that has cis hydroxy groups at C-1 and C-2, double bonds at C-3 and C-5, and a 4-chlorophenyl substituent at C-3, the configurations at C-1 and C-2 being S and R respectively.

id.name: 2-hydroxy-3-carboxylato-6-oxo-7-methylocta-2,4-dienoate
id.definition: A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of 2-hydroxy-3-carboxy-6-oxo-7-methylocta-2,4-dienoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: (2E,4Z)-6-(4-chlorophenyl)-2-hydroxy-6-oxohexa-2,4-dienoic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid formed by biodegradative cleavage of the dihydroxylated aromatic ring of 2,3-dihydroxybiphenyl.

id.name: 4'-chlorobiphenyl-2,3-diol
id.definition: A member of the class of hydroxybiphenyls that is catechol in which the hydrogen at position 3 is replaced by a p-chlorophenyl group.

id.name: anabasine

id.name: abietic acid
id.definition: An abietane diterpenoid that is abieta-7,13-diene substituted by a carboxy group at position 18.

id.name: (2S,3R)-aldono-1,5-lactone
id.definition: Any aldono-1,5-lactone having 2S,3R-threo stereochemistry. A representative structure is provided.

id.name: 2-hydroxychromene-2-carboxylic acid
id.definition: A chromenemonocarboxylic acid that consists of chromene bearing carboxy and hydroxy substituents at the 2-position.

id.name: cis-acetylacrylic acid
id.definition: A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is (Z)-pent-2-enoic acid in which the 4-position has been oxidised to the corresponding ketone.

id.name: 2,4-dichlorobenzoate

id.name: pinocarvone

id.name: 2-oxoglutaric acid
id.definition: An oxo dicarboxylic acid that consists of glutaric acid bearing an oxo substituent at position 2. It is an intermediate metabolite in Krebs cycle.

id.name: 3-dehydroshikimic acid
id.definition: A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is shikimic acid in which the allylic hydroxy group has been oxidised to the corresponding keto group.

id.name: glutarate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of glutaric acid.

id.name: 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutaric acid
id.definition: An oxo dicarboxylic acid comprising glutaric acid having oxo- and hydroxy substituents at the 2- and 4-positions respectively.

id.name: 2,3-dihydroxybutanedioate
id.definition: A tartaric acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-carboxy-2,3-dihydroxypropanoate.

id.name: 3-phosphonooxypyruvic acid
id.definition: A carboxyalkyl phosphate that is pyruvic acid substituted at position 3 by a 3-phosphonooxy group.

id.name: D-citramalate(2-)
id.definition: A citramalate(2-) that is the conjugate base of D-citramalic acid.

id.name: 3-phosphonopyruvic acid
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid substituted at position 3 by a phospho group.

id.name: L-citramalate(2-)
id.definition: A citramalate(2-) that is the conjugate acid of L-citramalic acid.

id.name: 5alpha,9alpha,10beta-labda-8(20),13-dien-15-yl diphosphate
id.definition: The 5alpha,9alpha,10beta-diastereomer of copalyl diphosphate.

id.name: dTDP-4-dehydro-2,6-dideoxy-D-glucose
id.definition: A dTDP-sugar having 4-dehydro-2,6-dideoxy-D-glucose as the sugar component.

id.name: trichloroacetic acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which all three methyl hydrogens are substituted by chlorine.

id.name: 4-pyridoxate
id.definition: A pyridoxate that is the conjugate base of 4-pyridoxic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: 5-pyridoxate
id.definition: A pyridoxate that is the conjugate base of 5-pyridoxic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: levoglucosan
id.definition: A anhydrohexose that is the 1,6-anhydro-derivative of beta-D-glucopyranose.

id.name: octacosanoic acid
id.definition: A C28, very long straight-chain, saturated fatty acid.

id.name: valerate
id.definition: A short-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of valeric acid; present in ester form as component of many steroid-based pharmaceuticals.

id.name: 3,5-dihydroxyphenylglyoxylic acid
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is glyoxylic acid in which the aldehyde hydrogen is substituted by a 3,5-dihydroxyphenyl group.

id.name: 3-dimethylallyl-4-hydroxybenzoic acid
id.definition: A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 4-hydroxybenzoic acid bearing an additional dimethylallyl substituent at position 3.

id.name: alcuronium chloride
id.definition: Chloride salt of alcuronium.

id.name: amlexanox
id.definition: A pyridochromene-derived monocarboxylic acid having an amino substituent at the 2-position, an oxo substituent at the 5-position and an isopropyl substituent at the 7-position.

id.name: 5,5-diethylbarbituric acid
id.definition: A member of the class of barbiturates, the structure of which is that of barbituric acid substituted at C-5 by two ethyl groups. Formerly used as a hypnotic (sleeping aid).

id.name: carboplatin
id.definition: A platinum coordination entity with cis square-planar geometry in which platinum(II) is coordinated to two ammonia ligands and a bidentate cyclobutane-1,1-dicarboxylate ligand.

id.name: ciclopirox olamine
id.definition: The ethanolamine salt of ciclopirox. A broad spectrum antigfungal agent, it also exhibits antibacterial activity against many Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, and has anti-inflammatory properties. It is used a a topical treatment of fungal skin and nail infections.

id.name: cilnidipine
id.definition: A diesterified 1,4-dihydropyridine-3,5-dicarboxylic acid. A calcium channel blocker, it is used as an antihypertensive.

id.name: cilostazol
id.definition: A lactam that is 3,4-dihydroquinolin-2(1H)-one in which the hydrogen at position 6 is substiuted by a 4-(1-cyclohexyl-1H-tetrazol-5-yl)butoxy group.

id.name: clobazam
id.definition: 7-Chloro-1H-1,5-benzodiazepine-2,4(3H,5H)-dione in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen at position 1 is substituted by a methyl group, whilst that attached to the other nitrogen is substituted by a phenyl group. It is used for the short-term management of acute anxiety and as an adjunct in the treatment of epilepsy in association with other antiepileptics.

id.name: clobetasol propionate
id.definition: The 17-O-propionate ester of clobetasol. A potent corticosteroid, it is used to treat various skin disorders, including exzema and psoriasis.

id.name: copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate
id.definition: The pentahydrate of copper(2+) sulfate. A bright blue crystalline solid.

id.name: fluticasone propionate
id.definition: A trifluorinated corticosteroid that consits of 6alpha,9-difluoro-11beta,17alpha-dihydroxy-17beta-{[(fluoromethyl)sulfanyl]carbonyl}-16-methyl-3-oxoandrosta-1,4-diene bearing a propionyl substituent at position 17; has anti-inflammatory, anti-asthmatic and anti-allergic activity.

id.name: cyclothiazide
id.definition: 3,4-Dihydro-2H-1,2,4-benzothiadiazine 1,1-dioxide substituted at positions 3, 5 and 6 by a 2-norbornen-5-yl group, chlorine, and a sulfonamide group, respectively. A thiazide diuretic, it has been used in the management of hypertension and oedema.

id.name: deslanoside
id.definition: A cardenolide glycoside that is lanatoside C with the acetoxy group replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: dioncopeltine A
id.definition: An isoquinoline alkaloid that is the biaryl resulting from substitution of the hydrogen at the 7-position of (1R,3R)-1,3-dimethyl-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinolin-8-ol by a 1-hydroxy-6-(hydroxymethyl)-8-methoxynaphthalen-5-yl group. It is a naphthylisoquinoline alkaloid found in Triphyophyllum peltatum.

id.name: dioncophylline A
id.definition: An isoquinoline alkaloid that is the biaryl resulting from substitution of the hydrogen at the 7-position of (1R,3R)-1,3-dimethyl-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinolin-8-ol by a 4,5-dimethoxy-2-methylnaphthalen-1-yl group. It is a naphthylisoquinoline alkaloid isolated from the roots and stem barks of Triphyophyllum peltatum and exhibits antifungal, antimalarial, antineoplastic and molluscicidal activites.

id.name: dioncophylline C
id.definition: An isoquinoline alkaloid that is the biaryl resulting from substitution of the hydrogen at the 5-position of (1R,3R)-1,3-dimethyl-1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinolin-8-ol by a 5-hydroxy-4-methoxy-2-methylnaphthalen-1-yl group. It is a naphthylisoquinoline alkaloid isolated from the roots and stem barks of Triphyophyllum peltatum and exhibits antimalarial activity.

id.name: diphenylpyraline hydrochloride
id.definition: The hydrochloride salt of diphenylpyraline. A sedating antihistamine, it is used as the hydrochloride for the symptomatic relief of allergic conditions including rhinitis and hay fever, and in pruritic skin disorders.

id.name: domperidone
id.definition: 1-[3-(Piperidin-1-yl)propyl]-1,3-dihydro-2H-benzimidazol-2-one in which the 4-position of the piperidine ring is substituted by a 5-chloro-1,3-dihydro-2H-benzimidazol-2-on-1-yl group. A dopamine antagonist, it is used as an antiemetic for the short-term treatment of nausea and vomiting, and to control gastrointestinal effects of dopaminergic drugs given in the management of parkinsonism. The free base is used in oral suspensions, while the maleate salt is used in tablet preparations.

id.name: doxifluridine
id.definition: A pyrimidine 5'-deoxyribonucleoside that is 5-fluorouridine in which the hydroxy group at the 5' position is replaced by a hydrogen. It is an oral prodrug of the antineoplastic agent 5-fluorouracil. Designed to circumvent the rapid degradation of 5-fluorouracil by dihydropyrimidine dehydrogenase in the gut wall, it is converted into 5-fluorouracil in the presence of pyrimidine nucleoside phosphorylase.

id.name: emtricitabine
id.definition: An organofluorine compound that is 5-fluorocytosine substituted at the 1 position by a 2-(hydroxymethyl)-1,3-oxathiolan-5-yl group (2R,5S configuration). It is used in combination therapy for the treatment of HIV-1 infection.

id.name: epothilone A
id.definition: An epithilone that is epothilone C in which the double bond in the macrocyclic lactone ring has been oxidised to the corresponding epoxide (the 13R,14S diastereoisomer).

id.name: epothilone B
id.definition: An epithilone that is epithilone D in which the double bond in the macrocyclic ring has been oxidised to the corresponding epoxide (the S,S stereoisomer).

id.name: eprazinone hydrochloride
id.definition: A hydrochloride obtained by combining eprazinone with two molar equivalents of hydrochloric acid.

id.name: ethyl linoleate
id.definition: A long-chain fatty acid ethyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of linoleic acid with the hydroxy group of ethanol.

id.name: ethylparaben
id.definition: An ethyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-hydroxybenzoic acid with ethanol,

id.name: fentanyl citrate
id.definition: The citric acid salt of fentanyl, comprising equimolar amounts of citric acid and fentanyl. A mu-opioid receptor agonist, it is a potent opioid analgesic used in the management of labour pain, postoperative pain, and chronic intractable cancer pain. It is also widely used as the analgesic component of balanced anaesthesia.

id.name: fluorescein
id.definition: A xanthene dye that is highly fluorescent, detectable even when present in minute quantities. Used forensically to detect traces of blood, in analytical chemistry as an indicator in silver nitrate titrations and in microscopy.

id.name: fulvestrant
id.definition: A 3-hydroxy steroid that is 17beta-estradiol in which the 7alpha hydrogen has been replaced by a nonyl group in which one of the hydrogens of the terminal methyl has been replaced by a (4,4,5,5,5-pentafluoropentyl)sulfinyl group. An estrogen receptor antagonist, it is used in the treatment of breast cancer.

id.name: glafenine
id.definition: A carboxylic ester that is 2,3-dihydroxypropyl anthranilate in which the amino group is substituted by a 7-chloroquinolin-4-yl group. A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, glafenine and its hydrochloride salt were used for the relief of all types of pain, but high incidence of anaphylactic reactions resulted in their withdrawal from the market.

id.name: hydrocortisone succinate
id.definition: A derivative of succinic acid in which one of the carboxy groups is esterified by the C-21 hydroxy group of cortisol (hydrocortisone).

id.name: iopamidol
id.definition: A benzenedicarboxamide compound having N-substituted carbamoyl groups at the 1- and 3-positions, iodo substituents at the 2-, 4- and 6-positions and a (2S)-2-hydroxypropanamido group at the 5-position.

id.name: L-4-hydroxyphenylglycine
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of 4-hydroxyphenylglycine.

id.name: militarinone A
id.definition: A pyridine alkaloid that is 1,4-dihydroxypyridin-2(1H)-one substituted by a cis-1,4-dihydroxycyclohexyl group at position 5 and a (2E,4E,6E,8R,10R)-6,8,10-trimethyldodeca-2,4,6-trienoyl moiety at position 3. It is isolated from the mycelium of the entomogenous fungus, Paecilomyces militaris and has been found to induce pronounced neurite sprouting.

id.name: N-methyl-D-aspartic acid
id.definition: An aspartic acid derivative having an N-methyl substituent and D-configuration.

id.name: phytoceramide
id.definition: A ceramide that is phytosphingosine having a fatty acyl group attached to the nitrogen.

id.name: pipamperone dihydrochloride
id.definition: A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of pipamperone with 2 mol eq. of hydrogen chloride. It is used as an antipsychotic.

id.name: saccharin
id.definition: A 1,2-benzisothiazole having a keto-group at the 3-position and two oxo substituents at the 1-position. It is used as an artificial sweetening agent.

id.name: stigmatellin A
id.definition: A member of the class of chromones that is isolated from Stigmatella aurantiaca Sg a15.

id.name: 1,2-diacyl-3-(alpha-D-6-sulfoquinovosyl)-sn-glycerol
id.definition: A glycosylglycerol derivative in which the glycosyl moiety is alpha-D-6-sulfoquinovosyl attached at O-3, with O-1 and O-2 both acylated.

id.name: tiaprofenic acid
id.definition: An aromatic ketone that is thiophene substituted at C-2 by benzoyl and at C-4 by a 1-carboxyethyl group.

id.name: tramadol hydrochloride
id.definition: A racemate consisting of equal amounts of (R,R)- and (S,S)-tramadol hydrochloride. A centrally acting synthetic opioid analgesic, used to treat moderately severe pain. The (R,R)-enantiomer exhibits ten-fold higher analgesic potency than the (S,S)-enantiomer.

id.name: ungeremine
id.definition: A natural product found particularly in Pancratium maritimum and Nerine bowdenii.

id.name: dodecanoyl group
id.definition: A fatty-acyl group derived from dodecanoic (lauric) acid.

id.name: 3-dehydroquinate
id.definition: A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 3-dehydroquinic acid.

id.name: 4-coumarate
id.definition: A coumarate that is the conjugate base of 4-coumaric acid.

id.name: trans-4-coumaric acid
id.definition: The trans-isomer of 4-coumaric acid.

id.name: cis,cis-muconate
id.definition: A muconate that is the conjugate base of (2Z,4Z)-5-carboxypenta-2,4-dienoate.

id.name: (R)-mandelate
id.definition: A mandelate that is the conjugate base of (R)-mandelic acid.

id.name: 6-hydroxyhexanoate
id.definition: A hydroxy fatty acid anion and the conjugate base of 6-hydroxyhexanoic acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.

id.name: arachidonate
id.definition: A long-chain fatty acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of arachidonic acid.

id.name: 6-aminohexanoate
id.definition: An amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of 6-aminohexanoic acid.

id.name: D-glyceric acid
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of glyceric acid.

id.name: all-trans-neoxanthin
id.definition: A neoxanthin in which all of the double bonds have trans geometry.

id.name: 4,4'-diaminodiphenylmethane
id.definition: An aromatic amine that is diphenylmethane substituted at the 4-position of each benzene ring by an amino group.

id.name: nicotinate
id.definition: A pyridinemonocarboxylate that is the conjugate base of nicotinic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannosyl group
id.definition: A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannose.

id.name: 2,4,6-tris(N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl)-alpha-D-mannosyl group
id.definition: A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of 2,4,6-tris(N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl)-alpha-D-mannose.

id.name: N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannosyl group
id.definition: A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannose.

id.name: L-argininium(1+)
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of argininium(1+).

id.name: (R)-2-hydroxyglutaric acid
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid.

id.name: 9-cis,11-trans-octadecadienoic acid
id.definition: An octadeca-9,11-dienoic acid having 9-cis,11-trans-stereochemistry.

id.name: (S)-4-hydroxymandelic acid
id.definition: A 4-hydroxymandelic acid that has S-configuration.

id.name: (R)-4-hydroxymandelic acid
id.definition: A 4-hydroxymandelic acid that has R-configuration.

id.name: 4-hydroxymandelate
id.definition: A 2-hydroxycarboxylate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 4-hydroxymandelic acid.

id.name: cis-aconitic acid
id.definition: The cis-isomer of aconitic acid.

id.name: trans-aconitic acid
id.definition: The trans-isomer of aconitic acid.

id.name: o-orsellinic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is 2,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a methyl group.

id.name: (Z)-5-oxohex-2-enedioic acid
id.definition: An oxo dicarboxylic acid that is (Z)-2-hexenedioic acid in which the hydrogens at position 5 are substituted by an oxo group.

id.name: 3-hydroxy-L-glutamic acid
id.definition: An amino dicarboxylic acid that is L-glutamic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3.

id.name: 4-hydroxy-L-glutamic acid
id.definition: An amino dicarboxylic acid that is L-glutamic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.

id.name: N-amidino-L-aspartate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of N-amidino-L-aspartic acid.

id.name: N-carbamoyl-L-aspartate(2-)
id.definition: An N-carbamoyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of N-carbamoyl-L-aspartic acid.

id.name: enol-phenylpyruvic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is the enol-form of phenylpyruvic acid, consisting of acrylic acid having a hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and a phenyl group at the 3-position.

id.name: pyruvic acid
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is the 2-keto derivative of propionic acid. It is a metabolite obtained during glycolysis.

id.name: p-coumaroylagmatine
id.definition: A member of the class of cinnamamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-coumaric acid with the primary amino group of agmatine.

id.name: D-allothreonine
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of allothreonine. It occurs as a component of peptido-lipids in certain bacteria.

id.name: L-seryl group
id.definition: The univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of L-serine.

id.name: secondary amine
id.definition: A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing two hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.

id.name: methyl group
id.definition: An alkyl group that is the univalent group derived from methane by removal of a hydrogen atom.

id.name: tertiary amine
id.definition: A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.

id.name: primary amine
id.definition: A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one hydrogen atom by a hydrocarbyl group.

id.name: alkene
id.definition: An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having one carbon-carbon double bond and the general formula CnH2n. Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having more than one double bond are alkadienes, alkatrienes, etc.

id.name: N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-1,2-alpha-D-mannosyl-1,6-(N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-1,2-alpha-D-mannosyl-1,3)-beta-D-mannosyl group
id.definition: A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-1,2-alpha-D-mannosyl-1,6-(N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-1,2-alpha-D-mannosyl-1,3)-beta-D-mannose.

id.name: baccatin III
id.definition: A tetracyclic diterpenoid isolated from plant species of the genus Taxus.

id.name: gibberellin A4
id.definition: A C19-gibberellin.

id.name: gibberellin A7
id.definition: A C19-gibberellin that is a pentacyclic diterpenoid responsible for promoting growth and development in plants.

id.name: gibberellin A24
id.definition: A C20-gibberellin that consists of a tetracyclic skeleton bearing two carboxy and a formyl group.

id.name: 1-naphthylacetic acid
id.definition: A naphthylacetic acid substituted by a carboxymethyl group at position 1.

id.name: amine
id.definition: A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.

id.name: epoxide
id.definition: Any cyclic ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a 3-membered ring.

id.name: phosphate group
id.definition: An inorganic group obtained by removal of one of the hydroxy groups from phosphoric acid.

id.name: phloretic acid
id.definition: A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid consisting of propionic acid having a 4-hydroxyphenyl group at the 3-position.

id.name: N(4)-{beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc}-Asn
id.definition: An N(4)-glycosyl-L-asparagine in which the glycosyl component is specified as beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc.

id.name: amide
id.definition: An amide is a derivative of an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) in which an acidic hydroxy group has been replaced by an amino or substituted amino group.

id.name: 2-oxopentanoic acid
id.definition: An oxopentanoic acid carrying an oxo group at position 2.

id.name: indole-3-butyric acid
id.definition: A indol-3-yl carboxylic acid that is butanoic acid carrying a 1H-indol-3-yl substituent at position 1.

id.name: D-mannonic acid
id.definition: The D-stereoisomer of mannonic acid.

id.name: long-chain fatty acyl-CoA
id.definition: A fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any long-chain (C13 to C22) fatty acid.

id.name: (3R)-3-hydroxy-L-aspartate(2-)
id.definition: A C4-dicarboxylate obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 3-hydroxy-L-aspartic acid.

id.name: (R)-10-hydroxyoctadecanoic acid
id.definition: A hydroxy fatty acid that is octadecanoic acid (stearic acid) in which the pro-R hydrogen has been replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: D-gluconic acid
id.definition: A gluconic acid having D-configuration.

id.name: propynoic acid
id.definition: A terminal acetylenic compound that is a 3-carbon, straight-chain, monounsaturated fatty acid having one acetylenic bond.

id.name: bisphenol A
id.definition: A bisphenol that is 4,4'-methanediyldiphenol in which the methylene hydrogens are replaced by two methyl groups.

id.name: 3,3',5,5'-tetrabromobisphenol A
id.definition: A bromobisphenol that is 4,4'-methanediyldiphenol in which the methylene hydrogens are replaced by two methyl groups and the phenyl rings are substituted by bromo groups at positions 2, 2', 6 and 6'. It is a brominated flame retardant.

id.name: vitamin
id.definition: Any micronutrient that is an organic compound. The term "vitamines" (from vita + amines) was coined in 1912 by Casimir Funk, who believed that these compounds were amines.

id.name: atom
id.definition: A chemical entity constituting the smallest component of an element having the chemical properties of the element.

id.name: organosulfur compound
id.definition: An organosulfur compound is a compound containing at least one carbon-sulfur bond.

id.name: alpha-tocotrienol
id.definition: A tocotrienol that is chroman-6-ol substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 5, 7 and 8 and a farnesyl chain at position 2. It has been found in palm oil derived from Elaeis guineensis.

id.name: beta-tocotrienol
id.definition: A tocotrienol that is chroman-6-ol substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 5 and 8 and a farnesyl chain at position 2. It has been isolated from various cultivars of wheat.

id.name: delta-tocotrienol
id.definition: A tocotrienol that is chroman-6-ol substituted by methyl groups at positions 2 and 8 and a farnesyl chain at position 2.

id.name: gamma-tocotrienol
id.definition: A tocotrienol that is chroman-6-ol substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 7 and 8 and a farnesyl chain at position 2.

id.name: antimicrobial agent
id.definition: A substance that kills or slows the growth of microorganisms, including bacteria, viruses, fungi and protozoans.

id.name: carboxylic ester
id.definition: An ester of a carboxylic acid, R(1)C(=O)OR(2), where R(1) = H or organyl and R(2) = organyl.

id.name: 3-hydroxypropionic acid
id.definition: A 3-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is propionic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the terminal carbon is replaced by a hydroxy group.

id.name: phospho sugar
id.definition: Any monosaccharide containing an alcoholic hydroxy group esterified with phosphoric acid.

id.name: glyceric acid
id.definition: A trionic acid that consists of propionic acid substituted at positions 2 and 3 by hydroxy groups.

id.name: L-arabinonic acid
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of arabinonic acid.

id.name: metal atom
id.definition: An atom of an element that exhibits typical metallic properties, being typically shiny, with high electrical and thermal conductivity.

id.name: glycolipid
id.definition: Any member of class of 1,2-di-O-acylglycerols joined at oxygen 3 by a glycosidic linkage to a carbohydrate part (usually a mono-, di- or tri-saccharide). Some substances classified as bacterial glycolipids have the sugar part acylated by one or more fatty acids and the glycerol part may be absent.

id.name: catechols
id.definition: Any compound containing an o-diphenol component.

id.name: catecholamine
id.definition: 4-(2-Aminoethyl)pyrocatechol [4-(2-aminoethyl)benzene-1,2-diol] and derivatives formed by substitution.

id.name: 4-methylthio-2-oxobutanoic acid
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid derived from L-methionine via the action of methionine transaminase.

id.name: carboxylic acid
id.definition: A carbon oxoacid acid carrying at least one -C(=O)OH group and having the structure RC(=O)OH, where R is any any monovalent functional group. Carboxylic acids are the most common type of organic acid.

id.name: alpha-amino acid
id.definition: An amino acid in which the amino group is located on the carbon atom at the position alpha to the carboxy group.

id.name: amino acid
id.definition: A carboxylic acid containing one or more amino groups.

id.name: 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-gluconate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-gluconic acid.

id.name: organic hydroxy compound
id.definition: An organic compound having at least one hydroxy group attached to a carbon atom.

id.name: nucleoside
id.definition: An N-glycosyl compound that has both a nucleobase, normally adenine, guanine, xanthine, thymine, cytosine or uracil, and either a ribose or deoxyribose as functional parents.

id.name: phenols
id.definition: Organic aromatic compounds having one or more hydroxy groups attached to a benzene or other arene ring.

id.name: aromatic alcohol
id.definition: Any alcohol in which the alcoholic hydroxy group is attached to a carbon which is itself bonded to an aromatic ring.

id.name: arenecarbaldehyde
id.definition: Any aldehyde in which the carbonyl group is attached to an aromatic moiety.

id.name: aromatic primary alcohol
id.definition: Any primary alcohol in which the alcoholic hydroxy group is attached to a carbon which is itself bonded to an aromatic ring.

id.name: aromatic carboxylic acid
id.definition: Any carboxylic acid in which the carboxy group is directly bonded to an aromatic ring.

id.name: aromatic amine
id.definition: An amino compound in which the amino group is linked directly to an aromatic system.

id.name: alpha-D-galacturonic acid
id.definition: The alpha-anomer of D-galacturonic acid.

id.name: corrinoid
id.definition: A derivative of the corrin nucleus, which contains four reduced or partly reduced pyrrole rings joined in a macrocycle by three =C- groups and one direct carbon-carbon bond linking alpha positions.

id.name: aldohexose
id.definition: A hexose with a (potential) aldehyde group at one end.

id.name: ribose
id.definition: Any aldopentose where the open-chain form has all the hydroxy groups on the same side in the Fischer projection. Occurrs in two enantiomeric forms, D- and L-ribose, of which only the former is found in nature.

id.name: ketoheptose
id.definition: A heptose with a (potential) ketone group at the 2-position.

id.name: psicose derivative
id.definition: A deoxyketohexose derivative that is formally obtained from a psicose.

id.name: fucose
id.definition: Any deoxygalactose that is deoxygenated at the 6-position.

id.name: 1-nitropyrene
id.definition: A nitroarene that is pyrene substituted at the 1-position by a nitro group. A by-product of combustion, it is the predominant nitrated polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon emitted in a diesel engine.

id.name: 1-hexadecyl-2-[(Z)-octadec-9-enoyl]-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine
id.definition: A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl and alkyl groups are specified as oleoyl and hexadecyl respectively.

id.name: 11(R)-HETE
id.definition: An 11-HETE in which the chiral centre at position 11 has R-configuration.

id.name: 11,12-EET
id.definition: An EET obtained by formal epoxidation of the 11,12-double bond of arachidonic acid.

id.name: 15alpha-hydroxytestosterone
id.definition: An androstanoid that is testosterone substituted by a alpha-hydroxy group at position 15. A natural product found in Daphnia magna exposed to the biocide tributyltin.

id.name: 2,3-di-O-phytanyl-sn-glycerol
id.definition: A dialkylglycerol that is glycerol alkylated at positions 1 and 2 by phytanyl groups with (R)-configuration at position 2.

id.name: oxybenzone
id.definition: A hydroxybenzophenone that is benzophenone which is substituted at the 2- and 4-positions of one of the benzene rings by hydroxy and methoxy groups respectively.

id.name: 2-hydroxyethyl methacrylate
id.definition: An enoate ester that is the monomethacryloyl derivative of ethylene glycol.

id.name: 1,3-benzothiazole-2-thiol
id.definition: 1,3-Benzothiazole substituted at the 2-position with a sulfanyl group.

id.name: 3-formylsalicylic acid
id.definition: A hydroxybenzoic acid that is salicylic acid in which the hydrogen at position 3 is substituted by a formyl group.

id.name: monobenzone
id.definition: The monobenzyl ether of hydroquinone. It is used as a topical drug for medical depigmentation.

id.name: 4-tert-butylphenol
id.definition: A member of the class of phenols that is phenol substituted with a tert-butyl group at position 4.

id.name: 5,6-EET
id.definition: An EET obtained by formal epoxidation of the 5,6-double bond of arachidonic acid.

id.name: 6beta-hydroxytestosterone
id.definition: A 17beta-hydroxy steroid that is testosterone bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at the 6beta-position.

id.name: 8,9-EET
id.definition: An EET obtained by formal epoxidation of the 8,9-double bond of arachidonic acid.

id.name: argipressin
id.definition: The predominant form of mammalian vasopressin (antidiuretic hormone). It is a nonapeptide containing an arginine at residue 8 and two disulfide-linked cysteines at residues of 1 and 6.

id.name: bisphenol F
id.definition: A bisphenol that is methane in which two of the hydrogens have been replaced by 4-hydroxyphenyl groups.

id.name: cefaloglycin
id.definition: A cephalosporin antibiotic containing at the 7beta-position of the cephem skeleton an (R)-amino(phenyl)acetamido group.

id.name: clofibric acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that is isobutyric acid substituted at position 2 by a p-chlorophenoxy group. It is a metabolite of the drug clofibrate.

id.name: colistimethate sodium
id.definition: A mixture where R = H or Me. Colistin in which each of the primary amino groups is converted to the corresponding aminomethanesulfonic acid sodium salt, commonly by the action of formaldehyde followed by sodium bisulfite. A polymyxin antibiotic derivative, it is used in the treatment of severe infections, particularly of multidrug-resistant Gram-negative bacteria such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa and Acinetobacter baumannii.

id.name: dibutyl phthalate
id.definition: A phthalate ester that is the diester obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy groups of phthalic acid with two molecules of butan-1-ol. Although used extensively as a plasticiser, it is a ubiquitous environmental contaminant that poses a risk to humans.

id.name: furfural
id.definition: An aldehyde that is furan with the hydrogen at position 2 substituted by a formyl group.

id.name: glycitein
id.definition: A methoxyisoflavone that is isoflavone substituted by a methoxy group at position 6 and hydroxy groups at positions 7 and 4'. It has been isolated from the mycelia of the fungus Cordyceps sinensis.

id.name: (S)-3-methyl-2-oxovalerate
id.definition: The conjugate base of (S)-3-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid.

id.name: 2,4'-dihydroxyacetophenone
id.definition: A dihydroxyacetophenone that is ethanone substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2 and a 4-hydroxyphenyl group at position 1.

id.name: 2-oxohexanoate
id.definition: A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-oxohexanoic acid.

id.name: 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion
id.definition: An oxo monocarboxylic acid anion in which the oxo group is located at the 2-position.

id.name: 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 4-amino-4-deoxychorismic acid.

id.name: 4-nitrotoluene
id.definition: A mononitrotoluene that consists of toluene bearing a nitro substituent at the 4-position.

id.name: chloroform
id.definition: A one-carbon compound that is methane in which three of the hydrogens are replaced by chlorines.

id.name: 1-benzofuran
id.definition: A benzofuran consisting of fused benzene and furan rings. It is the parent compound of the class of 1-benzofurans.

id.name: L-2-succinylamino-6-oxoheptanedioic acid
id.definition: A tricarboxylic acid consisting of L-2-amino-6-oxoheptanedioic acid having a succinoyl group attached to the nitrogen.

id.name: quaternary ammonium ion
id.definition: A derivative of ammonium, NH4(+), in which all four of the hydrogens bonded to nitrogen have been replaced with univalent (usually organyl) groups.

id.name: quaternary ammonium salt
id.definition: Derivatives of ammonium compounds, (NH4(+))Y(-), in which all four of the hydrogens bonded to nitrogen have been replaced with univalent (usually organyl) groups.

id.name: S-glycosyl compound
id.definition: A glycosyl compound arising formally from the elimination of water from a glycosidic hydroxy group and a S atom bound to a carbon atom, thus creating a C-S bond.

id.name: L-proline betaine
id.definition: An amino acid betaine that is L-proline zwitterion in which both of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen are replaced by methyl groups.

id.name: acylcholine
id.definition: A choline ester formed from choline and a carboxylic acid.

id.name: all-trans-violaxanthin
id.definition: The all-trans-stereoisomer of violaxanthin.

id.name: 1,2,3-trichlorobenzene
id.definition: A trichlorobenzene carrying chloro substituents at positions 1, 2 and 3.

id.name: 1,2-dichlorobenzene
id.definition: A dichlorobenzene carrying chloro substituents at positions 1 and 2.

id.name: all-trans-retinoate
id.definition: A retinoate that is the conjugate base of all-trans-retinoic acid.

id.name: anthracene
id.definition: An ortho-fused tricyclic hydrocarbon comprising three fused benzene rings.

id.name: 9-cis-violaxanthin
id.definition: The 9-cis-stereoisomer of violaxanthin.

id.name: 9'-cis-neoxanthin
id.definition: A neoxanthin in which all of the double bonds have trans geometry except for that at the 9' position, which is cis.

id.name: steroid
id.definition: Any of naturally occurring compounds and synthetic analogues, based on the cyclopenta[a]phenanthrene carbon skeleton, partially or completely hydrogenated; there are usually methyl groups at C-10 and C-13, and often an alkyl group at C-17. By extension, one or more bond scissions, ring expansions and/or ring contractions of the skeleton may have occurred. Natural steroids are derived biogenetically from squalene, so may be considered as triterpenoids.

id.name: 17alpha-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: The alpha-stereoisomer of 17-hydroxy steroid.

id.name: 17beta-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: A 17-hydroxy steroid in which the hydroxy group at position 17 has a beta-configuration.

id.name: 11beta-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: Any 11-hydroxy steroid in which the hydroxy group at position 11 has beta- configuration.

id.name: 3beta-sterol
id.definition: A sterol in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has beta- configuration.

id.name: 7beta-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: A 7-hydroxy steroid in which the hydroxy group at position 7 has beta-configuration.

id.name: fatty acid
id.definition: Any aliphatic monocarboxylic acid derived from or contained in esterified form in an animal or vegetable fat, oil or wax.

id.name: D-fuconate
id.definition: The conjugate base of D-fuconic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: D-mannose 1-phosphate
id.definition: A mannose phosphate that is D-mannose carrying a phosphate group at position 1.

id.name: monosaccharide
id.definition: Parent monosaccharides are polyhydroxy aldehydes H[CH(OH)]nC(=O)H or polyhydroxy ketones H-[CHOH]n-C(=O)[CHOH]m-H with three or more carbon atoms. The generic term 'monosaccharide' (as opposed to oligosaccharide or polysaccharide) denotes a single unit, without glycosidic connection to other such units. It includes aldoses, dialdoses, aldoketoses, ketoses and diketoses, as well as deoxy sugars, provided that the parent compound has a (potential) carbonyl group.

id.name: aspartate(1-)
id.definition: An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of aspartic acid.

id.name: chromate(2-)
id.definition: A chromium oxoanion resulting from the removal of two protons from chromic acid.

id.name: oxoanion
id.definition: An oxoanion is an anion derived from an oxoacid by loss of hydron(s) bound to oxygen.

id.name: primary diamine
id.definition: A primary diamine is a compound derived from a hydrocarbon by replacing two hydrogen atoms by amino groups.

id.name: alkane-alpha,omega-diamine
id.definition: A primary diamine that is ethane or a higher alkane in which a hydrogen of each of the terminal methyl groups has been replaced by an amino group. H2NCH2(CH2)nCH2NH2, where n = 0, 1, 2, etc.

id.name: N-monoacetylalkane-alpha,omega-diamine
id.definition: An acetamide obtained by acetylation of one of the amino groups of any alkane-alpha,omega-diamine. AcNHCH2(CH2)nCH2NH2, where n = 0, 1, 2, etc.

id.name: N-acetylneuraminate
id.definition: A ketoaldonate that is the conjugate base of N-acetylneuraminic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: D-ribose 1-phosphate
id.definition: A ribose monophosphate that is D-ribose substituted at position 1 by a phosphate group.

id.name: 3,3',5,5'-tetrachlorobiphenyl-4,4'-diol
id.definition: A member of the class of hydroxybiphenyls formed formally by chlorination of biphenyl-4,4'-diol at C-3, -3', -5 and -5'.

id.name: trypanothione disulfide
id.definition: Trypanothione disulfide is the oxidized form of N(1),N(8)-bis(glutathionyl)-spermidine from the insect-parasitic trypanosomatid Crithidia fasciculata.

id.name: 5alpha-cholestane
id.definition: The 5alpha-stereoisomer of cholestane.

id.name: furan
id.definition: A monocyclic heteroarene with a structure consisting of a 5-membered ring containing four carbons and one oxygen, with formula C4H4O. It is a toxic, flammable, low-boiling (31degreeC) colourless liquid.

id.name: (+)-pulegone
id.definition: The (5R)-enantiomer of p-menth-4(8)-en-3-one.

id.name: trisodium vanadate
id.definition: An inorganic sodium salt of formula Na3VO4 containing the tetrahedral VO4(3-)

id.name: L-alpha-aminobutyric acid
id.definition: An optically active form of alpha-aminobutyric acid having L-configuration.

id.name: beta-lactam
id.definition: A lactam in which the amide bond is contained within a four-membered ring, which includes the amide nitrogen and the carbonyl carbon.

id.name: (4R)-limonene 1,2-epoxide
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of limonene 1,2-epoxide.

id.name: secondary alcohol
id.definition: A secondary alcohol is a compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom which has two other carbon atoms attached to it.

id.name: dicarboxylic acid
id.definition: Any carboxylic acid containing two carboxy groups.

id.name: trans-cinnamic acid
id.definition: The E (trans) isomer of cinnamic acid

id.name: ester
id.definition: A compound formally derived from an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l > 0) and an alcohol, phenol, heteroarenol, or enol by linking with formal loss of water from an acidic hydroxy group of the former and a hydroxy group of the latter.

id.name: diethyl ether
id.definition: An ether in which the oxygen atom is linked to two ethyl groups.

id.name: xenobiotic
id.definition: A xenobiotic (Greek, xenos "foreign"; bios "life") is a compound that is foreign to a living organism. Principal xenobiotics include: drugs, carcinogens and various compounds that have been introduced into the environment by artificial means.

id.name: N(2)-acetyl-L-lysine
id.definition: An acetyl-L-lysine where the acetyl group is located at the N(2)-posiiton.

id.name: fatty acid ester
id.definition: A carboxylic ester in which the carboxylic acid component can be any fatty acid.

id.name: monocarboxylic acid anion
id.definition: A carboxylic acid anion formed when the carboxy group of a monocarboxylic acid is deprotonated.

id.name: 2-prenyl-1,4-benzoquinone
id.definition: A member of the class of 1,4-benzoquinones that is 1,4-benzoquinone in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been replaced by a prenyl group.

id.name: branched-chain fatty acid
id.definition: Any fatty acid in which the parent hydrocarbon chain has one or more alkyl substituents; a common component in animal and bacterial lipids. The fatty acyl chain is usually saturated and the substituent a methyl group; however, unsaturated BCFAs are found in marine animals, and branches other than methyl are found in microbial lipids.

id.name: anticholesteremic drug
id.definition: A substance used to lower plasma cholesterol levels.

id.name: mandelic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which two of the methyl hydrogens are substituted by phenyl and hydroxyl groups.

id.name: S-(2-hydroxyethyl)glutathione
id.definition: A Glu-Cys-Gly tripeptide derivative of glutathione containing a 2-hydroxyethyl substituent on the S of the Cys residue.

id.name: glutarate(1-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of glutaric acid.

id.name: 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid
id.definition: Any monocarboxylic acid having a 2-oxo substituent.

id.name: sterol ester
id.definition: A steroid ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of a sterol.

id.name: alpha-D-GalpNAc-(1->3)-[alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)]-D-Galp
id.definition: A branched amino trisaccharide consisting of D-galactose having an alpha-L-fucosyl residue at the 2-position and an N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl residue at the 3-position.

id.name: protirelin
id.definition: A tripeptide composed of L-pyroglutamyl, L-histidyl and L-prolinamide residues joined in sequence.

id.name: dioxo monocarboxylic acid
id.definition: Any monocarboxylic acid containing two ketonic or aldehydic oxo groups.

id.name: nonan-1-ol
id.definition: A fatty alcohol consisting of a hydroxy function at C-1 of an unbranched saturated chain of nine carbon atoms. It has been isolated as a component of volatile oils from plants like Hordeum vulgare.

id.name: tridecane
id.definition: A straight chain alkane containing 13 carbon atoms. It forms a component of the essential oils isolated from plants such as Abelmoschus esculentus.

id.name: chloromethane
id.definition: A one-carbon compound that is methane in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a chloro group.

id.name: 3,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydroxy groups are located at positions 3 and 4.

id.name: prostaglandin F3alpha
id.definition: A prostaglandin Falpha that is prosta-5,13,17-trien-1-oic acid carrying three hydroxy substituents at positions 9alpha, 11alpha and 15.

id.name: protein
id.definition: A biological macromolecule minimally consisting of one polypeptide chain synthesized at the ribosome.

id.name: 4-coumaric acid
id.definition: A coumaric acid in which the hydroxy substituent is located at C-4 of the phenyl ring.

id.name: cyclohexanecarboxylic acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that consists of cyclohexane substituted by a carboxy group.

id.name: 2-naphthoic acid
id.definition: A naphthoic acid that is naphthalene carrying a carboxy group at position 2.

id.name: 2-naphthoate
id.definition: A naphthoate that is the conjugate base of 2-naphthoic acid.

id.name: 1-hydroxy-2-naphthoic acid
id.definition: A naphthoic acid with the carboxy group at position 2 and carrying a hydroxy substituent at the 1-position. It is a xenobiotic metabolite produced by the biodegradation of phenanthrene by microorganisms.

id.name: pipecolate
id.definition: A piperidinecarboxylate that is the conjugate base of pipecolic acid.

id.name: quinone
id.definition: Compounds having a fully conjugated cyclic dione structure, such as that of benzoquinones, derived from aromatic compounds by conversion of an even number of -CH= groups into -C(=O)- groups with any necessary rearrangement of double bonds (polycyclic and heterocyclic analogues are included).

id.name: hepoxilin A3
id.definition: A hepoxilin having (5Z,9E,14Z) double bond stereochemistry, an 8-hydroxy substituent and an 11S,12S-epoxy group.

id.name: trioxilin A3
id.definition: A trioxilin having (5Z,9E,14Z) double bond configuration; and 8-, (11R)- and (12S)-hydroxy substituents.

id.name: shikimate
id.definition: A cyclohexenecarboxylate that is the conjugate base of shikimic acid.

id.name: beta-cellobiose
id.definition: A cellobiose with beta configuration at the reducing-end glucose residue.

id.name: beta-lactose
id.definition: The beta-anomer of lactose.

id.name: alpha-lactose
id.definition: The alpha-anomer of lactose.

id.name: disaccharide
id.definition: A compound in which two monosaccharides are joined by a glycosidic bond.

id.name: chenodeoxycholate
id.definition: Conjugate base of chenodeoxycholic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: 3alpha,7alpha,12beta-trihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid
id.definition: A trihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid that is 5beta-cholan-24-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3, 7 and 12 (the 3alpha,7alpha,12beta stereoisomer).

id.name: 3,4-dihydroxybenzoate
id.definition: A dihydroxybenzoate having the two hydroxy groups located at the 3- and 4-positions.

id.name: 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)pyruvate
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)pyruvic acid.

id.name: glycochenodeoxycholate
id.definition: A N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of glycochenodeoxycholic acid.

id.name: but-2-enoate
id.definition: The conjugate base of but-2-enoic acid.

id.name: taurolithocholic acid
id.definition: The bile acid taurine conjugate of lithocholic acid.

id.name: molybdate
id.definition: A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from molybdic acid

id.name: glycochenodeoxycholic acid
id.definition: A bile acid glycine conjugate having 3alpha,7alpha-dihydroxy-5beta-cholan-24-oyl as the bile acid component.

id.name: 1-naphthoate
id.definition: A naphthoate that is the conjugate base of 1-naphthoic acid.

id.name: glycerophosphocholine
id.definition: The glycerol phosphate ester of a phosphocholine. A nutrient with many different roles in human health.

id.name: glycerophosphoinositol
id.definition: Any glycerophospholipid having the polar alcohol inositol esterified to the phosphate group at the sn-3 position of the glycerol backbone.

id.name: dichloroacetic acid
id.definition: An organochlorine compound comprising acetic acid carrying two chloro substituents at the 2-position. It occurs in nature in seaweed, Asparagopsis taxiformis.

id.name: angelic acid
id.definition: The (Z)-isomer of 2-methylbut-2-enoic acid. It is found in plant species of the family Apiaceae.

id.name: (9Z,11E,13S,14Z)-13-hydroperoxyoctadeca-9,11,14-trienoate
id.definition: The conjugate base of (9Z,11E,13S,14Z)-13-hydroperoxyoctadeca-9,11,14-trienic acid.

id.name: (9Z,13S,15Z)-12,13-epoxyoctadeca-9,11,15-trienoate
id.definition: An unsaturated fatty acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of (9Z,13S,15Z)-12,13-epoxyoctadeca-9,11,15-trienoic acid.

id.name: homocitrate(3-)
id.definition: Tricarboxylate anion of homocitric acid.

id.name: (E)-glutaconate(2-)
id.definition: The (E)-isomer of glutaconate(2-).

id.name: cis-1,6-dihydroxycyclohexa-2,4-dienecarboxylate
id.definition: The anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of cis-1,6-dihydroxycyclohexa-2,4-dienecarboxylic acid.

id.name: 1-naphthoic acid
id.definition: A naphthoic acid carrying a carboxy group at position 1.

id.name: 1-oleoylglycerone 3-phosphate
id.definition: A 1-acylglycerone 3-phosphate in which the acyl group is specified as oleoyl.

id.name: hopan-22-ol
id.definition: A hopanoid that is hopane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 22.

id.name: 13-(beta-D-glucosyloxy)docosanoic acid
id.definition: A beta-D-glucoside consisting of docosanoic (behenic) acid having a beta-D-glucosyloxy group at position 13.

id.name: 13-(beta-D-glucosyloxy)docosanoate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 13-(beta-D-glucosyloxy)docosanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

id.name: 17beta-estradiol 3-glucosiduronic acid
id.definition: A steroid glucosiduronic acid that consists of 17beta-estradiol having a beta-glucuronyl residue attached at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.

id.name: 2-methoxy-17beta-estradiol 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide)
id.definition: A steroid glucosiduronic acid that is 2-methoxy-17beta-estradiol having a single beta-D-glucuronic acid residue attached at position 3.

id.name: galactosylceramide
id.definition: Any of the cerebrosides in which the monosaccharide head group is galactose.

id.name: alpha-Neup5NAc-(2->3)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-Glcp-(1-1')-Cer
id.definition: A sialotetraosylceramide consisting of a linear pentasaccharide made up from one sialyl residue, two galactose residues, one N-acetylgalactosamine residue and a glucose residue at the reducing end attached to the ceramide portion via a beta-linkage.

id.name: 2-hydroxy-6-(2-hydroxyphenyl)-6-oxo-cis,cis-hexa-2,4-dienoate
id.definition: A 6-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxy-6-(2-hydroxyphenyl)-6-oxo-cis,cis-hexa-2,4-dienoic acid.

id.name: N-acetylanthranilic acid
id.definition: An amidobenzoic acid consisting of anthranilic acid carrying an N-acetyl group.

id.name: N-methylanthranilate
id.definition: An aromatic amino-acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N-methylanthranilic acid.

id.name: 3-hydroxy-4-methylanthranilate
id.definition: The conjugate base of 3-hydroxy-4-methylanthranilic acid.

id.name: 3-hydroxyanthranilate
id.definition: A hydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid.

id.name: N-benzoyl-4-methoxyanthranilate
id.definition: A methoxybenzoate that it is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N-benzoyl-4-methoxyanthranilate.

id.name: N-formylanthranilic acid
id.definition: An amidobenzoic acid consisting of anthranilic acid carrying an N-formyl group.

id.name: triterpenoid
id.definition: Any terpenoid derived from a triterpene. The term includes compounds in which the C30 skeleton of the parent triterpene has been rearranged or modified by the removal of one or more skeletal atoms (generally methyl groups).

id.name: o-toluic acid
id.definition: A methylbenzoic acid that is benzoic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 2.

id.name: p-toluic acid
id.definition: A methylbenzoic acid in which the methyl substituent is located at position 4.

id.name: glyoxylate
id.definition: The conjugate base of glyoxylic acid.

id.name: phenylglyoxylate
id.definition: A member of the class of glyoxylates, that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of phenylglyoxylic acid.

id.name: 6-methylsalicylate
id.definition: A hydroxybenzoate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 6-methylsalicylic acid.

id.name: 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)lactate
id.definition: A 2-hydroxy carboxylate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)lactic acid.

id.name: 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine
id.definition: An alkyl,acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which unspecified alkyl and acyl groups are located at positions 1 and 2 respectively.

id.name: 2-acetyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine
id.definition: A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the 2-O-acyl group is specified as acetyl; a potent phospholipid activator and mediator of many leukocyte functions, including platelet aggregation, inflammation, and anaphylaxis.

id.name: 1-alkyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine
id.definition: An alkyl,acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which unspecified alkyl and acyl groups are located at positions 1 and 2 respectively.

id.name: alpha-pinene
id.definition: A pinene that is bicyclo[3.1.1]hept-2-ene substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 6 and 6 respectively.

id.name: p-menthan-3-one
id.definition: A p-menthane monoterpenoid that is p-menthane substituted by an oxo group at position 3.

id.name: mesobiliverdin
id.definition: A bilin that consists of 3,18-diethyl-2,7,13,17-tetramethyl-1,19,22,24-tetrahydro-21H-biline-8,12-dipropanoic acid bearing two oxo substituents at positions 1 and 19.

id.name: pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid
id.definition: A pyrrolecarboxylic acid that is 1H-pyrrole carrying a carboxy substituent at position 2.

id.name: 1-pyrroline-2-carboxylic acid
