id.definition: The product resulting from formal oxidation of DL-proline by loss of hydrogen from the nitrogen and from the carbon alpha to the carboxylic acid, with the formation of a C=N bond.

id.name: 3alpha-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: A 3-hydroxy steroid in which the 3-hydroxy substituent is in the alpha-position.

id.name: 3beta-hydroxy steroid
id.definition: A 3-hydroxy steroid in which the 3-hydroxy substituent is in the beta-position.

id.name: (3S)-citramalyl-CoA
id.definition: The (3S)-diastereomer of citramalyl-CoA.

id.name: cation
id.definition: A monoatomic or polyatomic species having one or more elementary charges of the proton.

id.name: thiourea
id.definition: The simplest member of the thiourea class, consisting of urea with the oxygen atom substituted by sulfur.

id.name: nucleotide
id.definition: A nucleotide is a nucleoside phosphate resulting from the condensation of the 3 or 5 hydroxy group of a nucleoside with phosphoric acid.

id.name: mesaconate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is the conjugate base of mesaconic acid.

id.name: perillyl-coenzyme A
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of perillic acid.

id.name: ribonucleoside 3'-monophosphate
id.definition: A ribonucleoside monophosphate in which the phosphate group is at the ribosyl 3-position.

id.name: 4-oxoproline
id.definition: The 4-isomer of oxoproline.

id.name: L-3-oxoalanine
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of 3-oxoalanine.

id.name: L-2-aminoadipic acid
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of 2-aminoadipic acid.

id.name: 2-aminoadipic acid
id.definition: An alpha-amino acid that is adipic acid bearing a single amino substituent at position 2. An intermediate in the formation of lysine.

id.name: 3-hydroxybutanoyl-CoA
id.definition: A hydroxybutanoyl-CoA having 3-hydroxybutanoyl as the S-acyl component.

id.name: epichlorohydrin
id.definition: An epoxide that is 1,2-epoxypropene in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by chlorine.

id.name: EC 3.1.3.16 (phosphoprotein phosphatase) inhibitor
id.definition: Any EC 3.1.3.* (phosphoric monoester hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of phosphoprotein phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.16).

id.name: glucan
id.definition: A polysaccharide composed of glucose residues.

id.name: galactan
id.definition: Polysaccharides composed of galactose residues.

id.name: xylan
id.definition: Polysaccharides composed of xylose residues.

id.name: phytanate
id.definition: A branched-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of phytanic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.

id.name: 1-alkyl-2-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate
id.definition: An acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate that has the acyl group located at position 2 with an additional alkyl substituent at position 1.

id.name: mucopolysaccharide
id.definition: Any of the group of polysaccharides composed of alternating units from uronic acids and glycosamines, and commonly partially esterified with sulfuric acid.

id.name: proteoglycan
id.definition: A glycoprotein in which the carbohydrate units are polysaccharides that contain amino sugars. The protein is glycosylated by one or more (up to about 100) glycosaminoglycans.

id.name: chondroitin sulfate
id.definition: Any of a class of 10--60 kDa glycosaminoglycan sulfates, widely distributed in cartilage and other mammalian connective tissues.

id.name: cyclic ether
id.definition: Any ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a ring.

id.name: alpha-amanitin
id.definition: A heterodetic cyclic peptide consisting of eight amino acid residues and containing a thioether bridge between a cysteine and a tryptophan residue. It is found in a number of poisonous mushrooms, including Amanita phalloides (the death cap), Galerina marginata, and and Conocybe filaris.

id.name: sterol 3-beta-D-glucoside
id.definition: Any beta-D-glucoside derived from a sterol.

id.name: 3-isopropenylpimeloyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-isopropenylpimelic acid.

id.name: folic acids
id.definition: A group of heterocyclic compounds based on the pteroic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamic acid units.

id.name: meso-tetrakis(N-methyl-4-pyridyl)porphine(4+)
id.definition: An organic cation that is porphyrin bearing four 1-methylpyridinium-4-yl groups at the 5-, 10-, 15- and 20-positions.

id.name: 2-deoxy-alpha-D-glucoside
id.definition: Any 2-deoxy-D-glucoside having alpha-configuration about the anomeric centre.

id.name: 2-methoxyestrone 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide)
id.definition: A steroid glucosiduronic acid that is 2-methoxyestrone having a single beta-D-glucuronic acid residue attached at position 3.

id.name: ribulose 5-phosphate
id.definition: A ribulose phosphate in which the phosphate group is attached at position 5.

id.name: D-galactopyranose 1-phosphate
id.definition: A D-galactose phosphate that consists of D-galactopyranose having a single phospho substituent located at the 1-position. It is an intermediate obtained during the the galactose metabolism.

id.name: monohydroxyanthraquinone
id.definition: An anthraquinone in which the anthraquinone moiety is substituted by a single hydroxy group.

id.name: hydroxyanthraquinones
id.definition: An anthraquinone substituted with one or more hydroxy groups.

id.name: D-xylose 5-phosphate
id.definition: A xylose phosphate that is D-xylose carrying a phosphate group at position 5.

id.name: 1D-myo-inositol 5-phosphate
id.definition: An inositol having myo- configuration substituted at position 5 by a phosphate group.

id.name: anthracene blue SWR
id.definition: A hexahydroxyanthraquinone that is anthracene-9,10-dione in which the six hydroxy substituents are located at positions 1, 2, 4, 5, 6 and 8. Used as as a hematoxylin substitute in H staining.

id.name: D-fructofuranose 1-phosphate
id.definition: The furanose form of D-fructose 1-phosphate.

id.name: O-phospho-L-threonine
id.definition: A L-threonine derivative phosphorylated at the side-chain hydroxy function.

id.name: acid
id.definition: An acid is a molecular entity capable of donating a hydron (Bronsted acid) or capable of forming a covalent bond with an electron pair (Lewis acid).

id.name: phosphatidylinositol 4-phosphate
id.definition: A phosphatidylinositol monophosphate carrying the phosphate group at the 4-position.

id.name: phorbol 13-acetate 12-myristate
id.definition: A phorbol ester that is phorbol in which the hydroxy groups at the cyclopropane ring juction (position 13) and the adjacent carbon (position 12) have been converted to the corresponding acetate and myristate esters.

id.name: phenyl phosphate
id.definition: An aryl phosphate resulting from the mono-esterification of phosphoric acid with phenol.

id.name: sphingosine 1-phosphate
id.definition: A phosphosphingolipid that consists of sphingosine having a phospho group attached at position 1

id.name: fatty acyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any fatty acid.

id.name: omega-carboxyacyl-CoA
id.definition: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with one of the carboxy groups of any alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid.

id.name: aryl dialkyl phosphate
id.definition: Any aryl phosphate having a single aryl substituent and two alkyl substituents.

id.name: 5-(beta-D-galactosyloxy)-L-lysine
id.definition: A 5-glycosyloxy-L-lysine in which the glycosyl fragment is specified as beta-D-galactose.

id.name: gamma-lactone
id.definition: A lactone having a five-membered lactone ring.

id.name: carboxamide
id.definition: An amide of a carboxylic acid, having the structure RC(=O)NR2. The term is used as a suffix in systematic name formation to denote the -C(=O)NH2 group including its carbon atom.

id.name: luteolin 7-O-[(beta-D-glucosyluronic acid)-(1->2)-(beta-D-glucosiduronic acid)] 4'-O-beta-D-glucosiduronic acid
id.definition: A luteolin glucosiduronic acid that consists of luteolin substituted by a beta-D-glucopyranosyluronic acid-(1->2)-beta-D-glucopyranosiduronic acid group at position 7 and a beta-D-glucopyranosyluronic acid group at position 4' via glycosidic linkages.

id.name: (1->3)-beta-D-glucan
id.definition: A beta-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->3) linkages.

id.name: mannose
id.definition: An aldohexose that is the C-2 epimer of glucose.

id.name: allose
id.definition: An aldohexose that is the C-3 epimer of glucose.

id.name: gulose
id.definition: An aldohexose that is the C-3 epimer of galactose.

id.name: talose
id.definition: An aldohexose that is the C-2 epimer of galactose.

id.name: O-phosphoserine
id.definition: A serine derivative that is serine substituted at the oxygen atom by a phosphono group.

id.name: O-phospho-D-serine
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of O-phosphoserine.

id.name: phosphonic ester
id.definition: A phosphonic acid derivative in which one or both OH groups have been esterified.

id.name: 5-phospho-beta-D-ribosylamine
id.definition: The beta-anomer of 5-phospho-D-ribosylamine.

id.name: undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetylmuramoyl-L-alanyl-D-gamma-glutamyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine
id.definition: An undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetylmuramoyl peptide in which the peptide element is L-alanyl-D-gamma-glutamyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine.

id.name: glycerophospholipid
id.definition: Any glycerolipid having a phosphate group ester-linked to a terminal carbon of the glycerol backbone.

id.name: 6-hydroxypseudooxynicotine
id.definition: The 6-hydroxy derivative of pseudooxynicotine.

id.name: O(4)-phospho-L-tyrosine
id.definition: A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-tyrosine phosphorylated at the phenolic hydroxy group.

id.name: butane
id.definition: A straight chain alkane composed of 4 carbon atoms.

id.name: pentane
id.definition: A straight chain alkane consisting of 5 carbon atoms.

id.name: 2-naphthylacetic acid
id.definition: A naphthylacetic acid carrying a carboxy group at position 2.

id.name: plant hormone
id.definition: A plant growth regulator that modulates the formation of stems, leaves and flowers, as well as the development and ripening of fruit. The term includes endogenous and non-endogenous compounds (e.g. active compounds produced by bacteria on the leaf surface) as well as semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds.

id.name: indane
id.definition: An ortho-fused bicyclic hydrocarbon consisting of a benzene ring fused to a cyclopentane ring; a high-boiling (176 (o)C) colourless liquid.

id.name: hydroxycoumarin
id.definition: Any coumarin carrying at least one hydroxy substituent.

id.name: colistin
id.definition: A multi-component mixture comprising mostly of colistin A (R = Me) and B (R = H), with small amounts of colistin C and other polymyxins, produced by certain strains of Bacillus polymyxa var. colistinus. An antibiotic, it is used as its sulfate salt (for oral or topical use) or as the sodium salt of the N-methylsulfonic acid derivative (the injectable form) in the treatment of severe Gram-negative infections, partiularly those due to Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

id.name: dopamine 3-O-sulfate
id.definition: An aryl sulfate that is dopamine in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a sulfo group.

id.name: 2H-pyran-2-one
id.definition: The simplest member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 2H-pyran with an oxo substituent at position 2.

id.name: 1-(3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl)-N-acylsphingosine
id.definition: A glycodiaosylceramide having 3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the disaccharide component and N-acylsphingosine as the sphingoid base.

id.name: cyanuric acid
id.definition: The enol tautomer of isocyanuric acid.

id.name: propazine
id.definition: A diamino-1,3,5-triazine that is N,N'-di(propan-2-yl)-1,3,5-triazine-2,4-diamine substituted by a chloro group at position 6.

id.name: cyanazine
id.definition: A chloro-1,3,5-triazine that is 2-chloro-1,3,5-triazine substituted by an ethyl amino and a (2-cyanopropan-2-yl)amino group at positions 6 and 4 respectively.

id.name: cardenolide glycoside
id.definition: Any member of the class of cardenolides with glycosyl residues attached to position 3.

id.name: benzenesulfinate
id.definition: An organosulfinate that is the conjugate base of benzenesulfinic acid obtained by deprotonation of the sulfinic acid group.

id.name: indanone
id.definition: An ortho-fused bicyclic compound consisting of a benzene ring fused to a cyclopentanone.

id.name: (1-naphthyl)methanol
id.definition: A naphthylmethanol that is methanol in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group is replaced by a naphthalen-1-yl group.

id.name: naphthylmethanol
id.definition: A primary alcohol that is methanol in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a naphthyl or a substituted naphthyl group.

id.name: ferrienterobactin
id.definition: An iron chelate that is (3S,7S,11S)-3,7,11-triamino-1,5,9-trioxacyclododecane-2,6,10-trione in which each nitrogen has been acylated by a 2,3-dihydroxybenzoyl group, the six phenolic oxygen atoms being coordinated to Fe(III).

id.name: (-)-11-hydroxy-9,10-dihydrojasmonic acid
id.definition: A dihydrojasmonic acid that is 9,10-dihydrojasmonic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 11 (the 1R,2R-stereoisomer).

id.name: phytosiderophore
id.definition: Any of low-molecular-mass iron(III)-chelating compounds produced by plants for the purpose of the transport and sequestration of iron.

id.name: chelator
id.definition: A ligand with two or more separate binding sites that can bind to a single metallic central atom, forming a chelate.

id.name: physcion
id.definition: A dihydroxyanthraquinone that is 9,10-anthraquinone bearing hydroxy substituents at positions 1 and 8, a methoxy group at position 3, and a methyl group at position 6. It has been widely isolated and characterised from both terrestrial and marine sources.

id.name: bacteriochlorophyll
id.definition: Chlorophylls of photosynthetic bacteria.

id.name: chlorophyllide
id.definition: Chlorophylls lacking the terpenoid side chain such as phytyl or farnesyl.

id.name: fumonisin B1
id.definition: A diester that results from the condensation of the 1-carboxy groups of two molecules of propane-1,2,3-tricarboxylic acid with hydroxy groups at positions 14 and 15 of (2S,3S,5R,10R,12S,14S,15R,16R)-2-amino-12,16-dimethylicosane-3,5,10,14,15-pentol.

id.name: (1S,4R)-1-hydroxylimonen-2-one
id.definition: An optically active form of 1-hydroxylimonen-2-one having (1S,4R)-configuration.

id.name: pyrrolidines
id.definition: Any of a class of heterocyclic amines having a saturated five-membered ring.

id.name: O-beta-D-glucosyl-trans-zeatin
id.definition: The trans-isomer of O-beta-D-glucosylzeatin.

id.name: L-ascorbate
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of ascorbate and conjugate base of L-ascorbic acid, arising from selective deprotonation of the 3-hydroxy group. Required for a range of essential metabolic reactions in all animals and plants.

id.name: EC 1.13.11.27 (4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate dioxygenase) inhibitor
id.definition: An EC 1.13.11.* (oxidoreductase acting on single donors and incorporating 2 atoms of oxygen) inhibitor that interferes with the activity of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate dioxygenase (EC 1.13.11.27).

id.name: 4-nitrophenyl N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminide
id.definition: An N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminide having a 4-nitrophenyl substituent at the anomeric position.

id.name: muconic acid
id.definition: A hexadienedioic acid with unsaturation at positions 2 and 4.

id.name: N-acetyl-D-glucosaminate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-D-glucosaminic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: azadirachtin B
id.definition: A member of the class of azadirachtin found in the neem tree, Azadirachta indica.

id.name: acetonitrile
id.definition: A nitrile that is hydrogen cyanide in which the hydrogen has been replaced by a methyl group.

id.name: EC 1.9.3.1 (cytochrome c oxidase) inhibitor
id.definition: An EC 1.9.3.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor heme group, oxygen as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of cytochrome c oxidase (EC 1.9.3.1).

id.name: 3-methyladenine
id.definition: A methyladenine that is adenine substituted with a methyl group at position N-3.

id.name: tetrahydroxyflavone
id.definition: Any hydroxyflavone carrying four hydroxy substituents.

id.name: 1,2-epoxypropane
id.definition: An epoxide that is oxirane substituted by a methyl group at position 2.

id.name: dihydroxyflavone
id.definition: Any hydroxyflavone in which two ring hydrogens are replaced by hydroxy substituents.

id.name: flavan
id.definition: The simplest member of the class of flavans that is chromane substituted by a phenyl group at position 2.

id.name: isoflavan
id.definition: The simplest member of the class of isoflavans that is chromane substituted by a phenyl substituent at position 3.

id.name: isoflavones
id.definition: Any isoflavonoid with a 3-aryl-1-benzopyran-4-one (3-aryl-4H-chromen-4-one) skeleton and its substituted derivatives.

id.name: 3-chlorophenol
id.definition: A monochlorophenol carrying the chloro substituent at position 3.

id.name: indole alkaloid
id.definition: An alkaloid containing an indole skeleton.

id.name: durene
id.definition: A tetramethylbenzene carrying methyl groups at positions 1, 2, 4 and 5.

id.name: pyrene
id.definition: An ortho- and peri-fused polycyclic arene consisting of four fused benzene rings, resulting in a flat aromatic system.

id.name: 5-oxopentanoic acid
id.definition: An oxopentanoic acid with the oxo group in the 5-position.

id.name: thiacloprid
id.definition: A nitrile that is cyanamide in which the hydrogens are replaced by a 1,3-thiazolidin-2-ylidene group which in turn is substituted by a (6-chloropyridin-3-yl)methyl group at the ring nitrogen.

id.name: imiprothrin
id.definition: Mixture of 20\% (1R)-cis- (CHEBI:39372) and 80\% (1R)-trans- (CHEBI:39373) isomers.

id.name: 2-(N-morpholiniumyl)ethanesulfonate
id.definition: A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 6.15 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: chromenol
id.definition: Any chromene carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.

id.name: tocol
id.definition: A chromanol with a chroman-6-ol skeleton that is substituted at position 2 by a saturated or triply-unsaturated hydrocarbon chain consisting of three isoprenoid units.

id.name: pyrimidines
id.definition: Any compound having a pyrimidine as part of its structure.

id.name: timolol
id.definition: 1,2,5-Thiadiazole substituted at the 3 position by a 3-(tert-butylamino)-2-hydroxypropoxy group and at the 4 position by a morpholin-4-yl group. The (S)-(-) enantiomer, also known as timolol, is a beta-adrenergic antagonist and is used in the mangement of glaucoma, hypertension, angina pectoris and myocardial infarction, and for the prevention of migraine.

id.name: 2,2,2-tetramine
id.definition: A polyazaalkane that is decane in which the carbon atoms at positions 1, 4, 7 and 10 are replaced by nitrogens.

id.name: atorvastatin
id.definition: A dihydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is a member of the drug class known as statins, used primarily for lowering blood cholesterol and for preventing cardiovascular diseases.

id.name: 12-hydroxylauric acid
id.definition: A medium-chain fatty acid that is the 12-hydroxylated derivative of lauric acid.

id.name: diflunisal
id.definition: An organofluorine compound comprising salicylic acid having a 2,4-difluorophenyl group at the 5-position.

id.name: metsulfuron methyl
id.definition: A N-sulfonylurea in which the sulfonyl group is attached to a 2-(methoxycarbonyl)phenyl group while a (4-methoxy-6-methyl-1,3,5-triazin-2-yl group replaces one of the amino hydrogens of the remaining urea group.

id.name: 8-anilinonaphthalene-1-sulfonic acid
id.definition: A naphthalenesulfonic acid that is naphthalene-1-sulfonic acid substituted by a phenylamino group at position 8.

id.name: dihydrogenphosphate
id.definition: A monovalent inorganic anion that consists of phosphoric acid in which one of the three OH groups has been deprotonated.

id.name: 3,4-xylenol
id.definition: A member of the class of phenols that is phenol substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 4.

id.name: valproic acid
id.definition: A branched-chain saturated fatty acid that comprises of a propyl substituent on a pentanoic acid stem.

id.name: propylamine
id.definition: A member of the class of alkylamines that is propane substituted by an amino group at C-1.

id.name: 3-methylpyridine
id.definition: A methylpyridine that is pyridine substituted by a methyl group at position 3.

id.name: 3-nitrotoluene
id.definition: A mononitrotoluene carrying a nitro group at position 3.

id.name: D-cycloserine
id.definition: A 4-amino-1,2-oxazolidin-3-one that has R configuration. It is an antibiotic produced by Streptomyces garyphalus or S. orchidaceus and is used as part of a multi-drug regimen for the treatment of tuberculosis when resistance to, or toxicity from, primary drugs has developed. An analogue of D-alanine, it interferes with bacterial cell wall synthesis in the cytoplasm by competitive inhibition of L-alanine racemase (which forms D-alanine from L-alanine) and D-alanine--D-alanine ligase (which incorporates D-alanine into the pentapeptide required for peptidoglycan formation and bacterial cell wall synthesis).

id.name: amitrole
id.definition: A member of the class of triazoles that is 1H-1,2,4-triazole substituted by an amino group at position 3. Used to control annual grasses and aquatic weeds (but not on food crops because it causes cancer in laboratory animals). Its use within the EU was banned from September 2017 on the grounds of potential groundwater contamination and risks to aquatic life; there have also been concerns about its endocrine-disrupting properties.

id.name: (-)-rolipram
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of rolipram.

id.name: 5-fluorouridine
id.definition: An organofluorine compound that is uridine bearing a fluoro substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.

id.name: 5-methyl-1H-benzimidazole
id.definition: A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1H-benzimidazole in which the hydrogen at position 5 is substituted by a methyl group.

id.name: 6-methylpurine
id.definition: Purine bearing a methyl substituent at position 6.

id.name: allopurinol
id.definition: A bicyclic structure comprising a pyrazole ring fused to a hydroxy-substituted pyrimidine ring.

id.name: lovastatin
id.definition: A fatty acid ester that is mevastatin carrying an additional methyl group on the carbobicyclic skeleton. It is used in as an anticholesteremic drug and has been found in fungal species such as Aspergillus terreus and Pleurotus ostreatus (oyster mushroom).

id.name: 8-hydroxy-2'-deoxyguanosine
id.definition: Guanosine substituted at the purine 8-position by a hydroxy group. It is used as a biomarker of oxidative DNA damage.

id.name: TMC-95A
id.definition: A 17-membered macrocyclic lactam that incorporates a phenol and a substituted indole moiety. It includes a R-hydroxy group at position 11 and a (3-methyl-2-oxopentanoyl)amino group at position at position 18 with a S-methyl group. It acts as a proteasome inhibitor and is obtained from Apiospora montagnei Sacc. TC 1093, isolated from a soil sample.

id.name: 2-octaprenylphenol
id.definition: A 2-polyprenylphenol in which the polyprenyl chain contains 8 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: N-acetylglycine
id.definition: An N-acylglycine where the acyl group is specified as acetyl.

id.name: 9,10-anthraquinone
id.definition: An anthraquinone that is anthracene in which positions 9 and 10 have been oxidised to carbonyls.

id.name: 2'-O-methyladenosine 5'-monophosphate
id.definition: A adenosine 5'-phosphate that is the 2'-O-methyl derivative of adenosine 5'-monophosphate.

id.name: acetyl group
id.definition: A group, formally derived from acetic acid by dehydroxylation, which is fundamental to the biochemistry of all forms of life. When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.

id.name: alpha-D-GalpA-(1->4)-alpha-D-GalpA
id.definition: A digalacturonic acid in which two alpha-D-galactopyranuronic acid units are joined via a (1->4)-linkage.

id.name: alpha-cyclodextrin
id.definition: A cycloamylose composed of six alpha-(1->4) linked D-glucopyranose units.

id.name: alpha-D-fructofuranose 1,6-bisphosphate
id.definition: A D-fructofuranose 1,6-bisphosphate with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: aminoguanidine
id.definition: A one-carbon compound whose unique structure renders it capable of acting as a derivative of hydrazine, guanidine or formamide.

id.name: beta-D-allose
id.definition: A D-allopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: (S)-adrenaline
id.definition: The S-enantiomer of adrenaline.

id.name: 2,5-dinitrophenol
id.definition: A dinitrophenol having the nitro groups at the 2- and 5-positions.

id.name: 4-methoxybenzoic acid
id.definition: A methoxybenzoic acid substituted with a methoxy group at position C-4.

id.name: 3,4-dihydroxy-9,10-dioxo-9,10-dihydroanthracene-2-sulfonic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxyanthraquinone that is 1,2-dihydroxyanthraquinone compound carrying an additional sulfo substituent at the 3-position. The monosodium salt is the biological stain 'alizarin red S'.

id.name: bis-tris propane
id.definition: A water-soluble buffer substance used for the preparation of the biochemical and biological buffer solutions; pKa = 6.8 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: N,N-bis(2-hydroxyethyl)glycine
id.definition: A bicine that is a Good's buffer substance, pKa = 8.35 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: astaxanthin
id.definition: A carotenone that consists of beta,beta-carotene-4,4'-dione bearing two hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 3' (the 3S,3'S diastereomer). A carotenoid pigment found mainly in animals (crustaceans, echinoderms) but also occurring in plants. It can occur free (as a red pigment), as an ester, or as a blue, brown or green chromoprotein.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-alanine
id.definition: An N-acetyl-L-amino acid that is L-alanine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by an acetyl group.

id.name: ecgonine benzoate
id.definition: A benzoate ester metabolite of cocaine formed by hydrolysis of the methyl ester group, catalysed by carboxylesterases.

id.name: beta-D-fructopyranose
id.definition: A D-fructopyranose in which the anomeric centre has beta-configuration.

id.name: benzamidine
id.definition: A carboxamidine that is benzene carrying an amidino group.

id.name: beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactopyranose
id.definition: A beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-D-galactopyranose with a beta-configuration at the reducing end anomeric center.

id.name: benfotiamine
id.definition: A thioester that is a synthetic analogue of thiamine obtained by acylative cleavage of the thiazole ring and O-phospohorylation.

id.name: crotonic acid
id.definition: A but-2-enoic acid with a trans- double bond at C-2. It has been isolated from Daucus carota.

id.name: N,N,N-trimethylglycinium
id.definition: A quaternary ammonium ion in which the substituents on nitrogen are methyl (three) and carboxymethyl.

id.name: benzyl benzoate
id.definition: A benzoate ester obtained by the formal condensation of benzoic acid with benzyl alcohol. It has been isolated from the plant species of the genus Polyalthia.

id.name: (R)-2-benzylsuccinic acid
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 2-benzylsuccinic acid.

id.name: bis-tris
id.definition: A buffer substance useful for calibration of glass electrodes and for the preparation of the biochemical and biological buffer solutions; pKa = 6.46 at 25 degreeC.

id.name: tetradecane
id.definition: A straight chain alkane consisting of 14 carbon atoms.

id.name: 1H-benzimidazole
id.definition: The 1H-tautomer of benzimidazole.

id.name: benzophenone
id.definition: The simplest member of the class of benzophenones, being formaldehyde in which both hydrogens are replaced by phenyl groups.

id.name: cholesterol sulfate
id.definition: A steroid sulfate that is cholesterol substituted by a sulfoxy group at position 3.

id.name: ethyl propionate
id.definition: A propanoate ester of ethanol.

id.name: celecoxib
id.definition: A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole which is substituted at positions 1, 3 and 5 by 4-sulfamoylphenyl, trifluoromethyl and p-tolyl groups, respectively. A cyclooxygenase-2 inhibitor, it is used in the treatment of arthritis.

id.name: gamma-carboxy-L-glutamic acid
id.definition: A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-glutamic acid in which one of the gamma-hydrogens is substituted by a carboxy group.

id.name: N-cyclohexyl-N'-(4-iodophenyl)urea
id.definition: A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea in which a hydrogen attached to one nitrogen is replaced by a cyclohexyl group and a hydrogen attached to the other nitrogen is replaced by a p-iodophenyl group.

id.name: 4-phenylbutyric acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid the structure of which is that of butyric acid substituted with a phenyl group at C-4. It is a histone deacetylase inhibitor that displays anticancer activity. It inhibits cell proliferation, invasion and migration and induces apoptosis in glioma cells. It also inhibits protein isoprenylation, depletes plasma glutamine, increases production of foetal haemoglobin through transcriptional activation of the gamma-globin gene and affects hPPARgamma activation.

id.name: cholesteryl linoleate
id.definition: The (9Z,12Z)-stereoisomer of cholesteryl octadeca-9,12-dienoate.

id.name: 1-(3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl)-N-[(15Z)-tetracos-15-enoyl]sphingosine
id.definition: An N-acyl-beta-D-galactosylsphingosine having a sulfo group at the 3-position on the galactose ring and (15Z)-tetracos-15-enoyl as the N-acyl group.

id.name: D-pipecolic acid
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of pipecolic acid.

id.name: cyclohexane-1,2-dione
id.definition: A cyclohexanedione carrying oxo substituents at positions 1 and 2.

id.name: crystal violet
id.definition: An organic chloride salt that is the monochloride salt of crystal violet cation. It has been used in creams for the topical treatment of bacterial and fungal infections, being effective against some Gram-positive bacteria (notably Staphylococcus species) and some pathogenic fungi (including Candida species) but use declined following reports of animal carcinogenicity. It has also been used for dying wood, silk, and paper, as well as a histological stain.

id.name: N-carboxy-L-methionine
id.definition: A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-methionine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amino group bas been replaced by a carboxy group.

id.name: S-hydroxy-L-cysteine
id.definition: A cysteine derivative consisting of L-cysteine carrying an S-hydroxy-substituent.

id.name: decane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with 10 carbon atoms.

id.name: ddTTP
id.definition: A pyrimidine 2',3'-dideoxyribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate having thymine as the nucleobase.

id.name: sebacic acid
id.definition: An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,8-dicarboxy derivative of octane.

id.name: dexamethasone
id.definition: A fluorinated steroid that is 9-fluoropregna-1,4-diene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 11, 17 and 21, a methyl group at position 16 and oxo groups at positions 3 and 20. It is a synthetic member of the class of glucocorticoids.

id.name: 1H-indene
id.definition: An ortho-fused bicyclic arene comprising of benzene and cyclopentene rings.

id.name: decamethonium
id.definition: A quaternary ammonium ion that is a depolarising muscle relaxant whose structure comprises a decane-1,10-diamine core in which each amino group carries three methyl substituents.

id.name: (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)acetic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxyphenylacetic acid having the two hydroxy substituents located at the 3- and 4-positions. It is a metabolite of dopamine.

id.name: 2-(difluoromethyl)ornithine
id.definition: A fluoroamino acid that is ornithine substituted by a difluoromethyl group at position 2.

id.name: (-)-taxifolin
id.definition: The (2S,3S)-stereoisomer of taxifolin.

id.name: H3[(2R)-HP-DO3A]
id.definition: An optically active tricarboxylic acid that consists of 1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane bearing three carboxymethyl substituents at positions 1, 4 and 7 as well as an (R)-2-hydroxypropyl group at position 10.

id.name: daunorubicin
id.definition: A natural product found in Actinomadura roseola.

id.name: 2,4-dinitrophenol
id.definition: A dinitrophenol having the nitro groups at the 2- and 4-positions.

id.name: duroquinone
id.definition: A member of the class of 1,4-benzoquinones that is 1,4-benzoquinone in which all four hydrogens are substituted by methyl groups.

id.name: 2,4-dioxopentanedioic acid
id.definition: An oxodicarboxylic acid that is glutaric acid which is substituted by oxo groups at positions 2 and 4.

id.name: digoxigenin
id.definition: A hydroxy steroid that consists of 5beta-cardanolide having a double bond at the 20(22)-position as well as hydroxy groups at the 3beta-, 12beta- and 14beta-positions. It has been isolated from the plant species of the genus Digitalis.

id.name: D-norleucine
id.definition: The D-enantiomer of 2-aminohexanoic acid.

id.name: (R)-lactic acid
id.definition: An optically active form of lactic acid having (R)-configuration.

id.name: daidzein 7-O-beta-D-glucoside
id.definition: A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is daidzein attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage. It is used in the treatment of alcohol dependency (antidipsotropic).

id.name: digitoxigenin
id.definition: A 5beta-cardenolide that is 5beta-cardanolide with hydroxy substituents at the 3beta- and 14beta-positions and double bond unsaturation at C(20)-C(22).

id.name: emodin
id.definition: A trihydroxyanthraquinone that is 9,10-anthraquinone which is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1, 3, and 8 and by a methyl group at position 6. It is present in the roots and barks of numerous plants (particularly rhubarb and buckthorn), moulds, and lichens. It is an active ingredient of various Chinese herbs.

id.name: (-)-epigallocatechin
id.definition: A flavan-3,3',4',5,5',7-hexol having (2R,3R)-configuration.

id.name: ethane
id.definition: An alkane comprising of two carbon atoms.

id.name: (4R,5S)-dethiobiotin
id.definition: The (4R,5S)-isomer of dethiobiotin.

id.name: 2-[4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl]ethanesulfonic acid
id.definition: A HEPES that is ethanesulfonic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a 4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl group. A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 7.55 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: erythromycin A
id.definition: An erythromycin that consists of erythronolide A having 2,6-dideoxy-3-C-methyl-3-O-methyl-alpha-L-ribo-hexopyranosyl and 3,4,6-trideoxy-3-(dimethylamino)-beta-D-xylo-hexopyranosyl residues attahced at positions 4 and 6 respectively.

id.name: tricosanoic acid
id.definition: A very long-chain fatty acid that is tricosane in which one of the methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.

id.name: flavone
id.definition: The simplest member of the class of flavones that consists of 4H-chromen-4-one bearing a phenyl substituent at position 2.

id.name: pentadecanoic acid
id.definition: A straight-chain, fifteen-carbon carboxylic acid with no heteroatoms; a long-chain of mainly ruminant origin.

id.name: fisetin
id.definition: A 7-hydroxyflavonol with additional hydroxy groups at positions 3, 3' and 4'.

id.name: 4-(trifluoromethyl)phenol
id.definition: A member of the class of (trifluoromethyl)benzenes that is p-cresol in which the methyl group is perfluorinated. It is a metabolite of the drug fluoxetine.

id.name: beta-L-fucose
id.definition: A L-fucopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: alpha-D-quinovopyranose
id.definition: The pyranose form of D-quinovose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position .

id.name: flufenamic acid
id.definition: An aromatic amino acid consisting of anthranilic acid carrying an N-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl substituent. An analgesic and anti-inflammatory, it is used in rheumatic disorders.

id.name: gamma-butyrolactone
id.definition: A butan-4-olide that is tetrahydrofuran substituted by an oxo group at position 2.

id.name: 3-aminobenzoic acid
id.definition: An aminobenzoic acid carrying an amino group at position 3.

id.name: alpha-D-glucuronic acid
id.definition: A D-glucopyranuronic acid in which the anomeric centre has alpha-configuration.

id.name: (R)-amphetamine
id.definition: A 1-phenylpropan-2-amine that has R configuration.

id.name: aldehydo-D-glucose
id.definition: The open chain form of D-glucose.

id.name: geneticin
id.definition: An aminoglycoside antibiotic produced by Micromonospora rhodorangea. It blocks polypeptide synthesis by inhibiting the elongation step in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells.

id.name: gabapentin
id.definition: A gamma-amino acid that is cyclohexane substituted at position 1 by aminomethyl and carboxymethyl groups. Used for treatment of neuropathic pain and restless legs syndrome.

id.name: 5-dehydro-4-deoxy-D-glucarate(2-)
id.definition: A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of 5-dehydro-4-deoxy-D-glucarate.

id.name: guanidine
id.definition: An aminocarboxamidine, the parent compound of the guanidines.

id.name: alpha-L-galactose
id.definition: A L-galactopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric center.

id.name: galanthamine
id.definition: A benzazepine alkaloid isolated from certain species of daffodils.

id.name: L-erythro-7,8-dihydrobiopterin
id.definition: A 7,8-dihydrobiopterin in which the 1,2-dihydroxypropyl group has (1R,2S)-configuration; naturally occurring form.

id.name: 7,8-didemethyl-8-hydroxy-5-deazariboflavin
id.definition: Riboflavin in which the nitrogen at position 5 is replaced by CH and the methyl groups at positions 7 and 8 are substituted by hydrogen and hydroxy, respectively.

id.name: (S)-3-phenyllactic acid
id.definition: The (S)-enantiomer of 3-phenyllactic acid.

id.name: heptane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with seven carbon atoms. It has been found in Jeffrey pine (Pinus jeffreyi).

id.name: alpha-L-gulose
id.definition: A L-gulopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: (R)-3-hydroxylauric acid
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 3-hydroxylauric acid. An intermediate in fatty acid biosynthesis.

id.name: isobutylbenzene
id.definition: An alkylbenzene that is benzene carrying an isobutyl substituent.

id.name: 5-iododeoxycytidine monophosphate
id.definition: A 2'-deoxycytidine phosphate that is 2'-deoxycytidine-5'-monophosphate in which the hydrogen at position 5 on the cytosine ring is replaced by iodine.

id.name: L-erythro-isocitric acid
id.definition: The (1R,2R)-stereoisomer of isocitric acid.

id.name: isoursodeoxycholic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid that is (5beta)-cholan-24-oic acid substituted by beta-hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 7.

id.name: L-alloisoleucine
id.definition: An optically active form of alloisoleucine having L-(2S,3R)-configuration.

id.name: hydrogen iodide
id.definition: A diatomic molecule containing covalently bonded hydrogen and iodine atoms.

id.name: hydrogenphosphate
id.definition: A phosphate ion that is the conjugate base of dihydrogenphosphate.

id.name: 1,5,5-trimethylpyrrolidin-2-one
id.definition: A member of the class of pyrrolidine-2-ones that is pyrrolidine-2-one in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen and both of the hydrogens at position 5 are replaced by methyl groups.

id.name: 3-[isopropyl(4-methylbenzoyl)amino]-5-phenylthiophene-2-carboxylic acid
id.definition: An amido thiophene-2-carboxylic acid derivative used as an inhibitor of HCV (Hepatitis C Virus) RNA polymerase.

id.name: kojic acid
id.definition: A pyranone that is 4H-pyran substituted by a hydroxy group at position 5, a hydroxymethyl group at position 2 and an oxo group at position 4. It has been isolated from the fungus Aspergillus oryzae.

id.name: N(6)-carboxy-L-lysine
id.definition: An L-lysine derivative consisting of L-lysine carrying a carboxy substituent at the N(6)-position.

id.name: obeticholic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid that is chenodeoxycholic acid carrying an additional ethyl substituent at the 6alpha-position. A semi-synthetic bile acid which acts as a farnesoid X receptor agonist and is used for treatment of primary biliary cholangitis.

id.name: icosane
id.definition: A straight chain alkane composed of 20 carbon atoms. It has been isolated from the leaves of Agave attenuata.

id.name: lumiflavin
id.definition: A compound showing yellow-green fluorescence, formed by a photolysis of riboflavin in alkaline solution.

id.name: beta-L-fructofuranose
id.definition: A L-fructofuranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: isomyristic acid
id.definition: A branched-chain saturated fatty acid consisting of tridecanoic acid carrying a 12-methyl group.

id.name: (4R)-5-oxo-L-leucine
id.definition: A L-leucine derivative that is L-leucine substituted by an oxo group at position 5.

id.name: (S)-lipoic acid
id.definition: The (S)-enantiomer of lipoic acid. Not found in nature, it may exert detrimental effects on biosystems.

id.name: methyl 4,6-dideoxy-4-(3-deoxy-L-glycero-tetronamido)-2-O-methyl-alpha-D-mannopyranoside
id.definition: An N-acyl-hexosamine that is the methyl alpha-glycoside of the terminal moiety, and presumed antigenic determinant, of the O-specific polysaccharide of Vibrio cholerae O:1, serotype Ogawa.

id.name: alpha-D-mannose 6-phosphate
id.definition: The alpha-anomer of D-mannose 6-phosphate.

id.name: methyl alpha-D-mannoside
id.definition: A methyl mannoside having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.

id.name: 2-methyl-L-glutamine
id.definition: A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-glutamine substituted by a methyl group at position 2.

id.name: 2,2'-[(2-amino-2-oxoethyl)imino]diacetic acid
id.definition: A tricarboxylic acid amide that is a Good's buffer substance, pKa = 6.6 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: melagatran
id.definition: A member of the class of azetidines that is (2S)-azetidine 2-carboxylic acid in which the carboxylic acid has been converted to the amide corresponding to formal condensation with 4-(aminomethyl)benzenecarboximidamide and in which the hydrogen attached to the azetidine nitrogen is replaced by a (2R)-2-cyclohexyl-2-[(carboxymethyl)amino]acetyl group.

id.name: N-methyl-L-phenylalanine
id.definition: A phenylalanine derivative consisting of L-phenylalanine having a methyl substuent attached to the alpha-amino function.

id.name: N-methylleucine
id.definition: A leucine derivative obtained by replacement of one of the amino hydrogens of leucine by a methyl group.

id.name: N(6),N(6)-dimethyl-L-lysine
id.definition: An L-lysine derivative comprising L-lysine having two methyl substituents attached to the side-chain amino group.

id.name: N-methyl-L-methionine
id.definition: A methyl-L-methionine having the methyl group attached to the alpha-amino function.

id.name: isopropyl dihydrogen phosphate
id.definition: Monophosphorylated isopropyl alcohol.

id.name: molybdopterin
id.definition: A molybdopterin that is the O-phospho derivative of [(5aR,8R,9aR)-2-amino-4-oxo-6,7-disulfanyl-3,5,5a,8,9a,10-hexahydro-4H-pyrano[3,2-g]pteridin-8-yl]methanol.

id.name: methyl L-leucinate
id.definition: The methyl ester of L-leucine.

id.name: N(4)-methyl-L-asparagine
id.definition: An N-methyl-L-asparagine with a single methyl substituent attached to the amide nitrogen.

id.name: 3-(N-morpholino)propanesulfonic acid
id.definition: A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 7.2 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: tiamulin
id.definition: A carbotricyclic compound that is pleuromutilin in which the hydroxyacetate group is replaced by a 2-{[2-(diethylamino)ethyl]sulfanyl}acetate group. An antibacterial drug, tiamulin is used in veterinary medicine (generally as its hydrogen fumarate salt) for the treatment of swine dysentery caused by Serpulina hyodysenteriae.

id.name: terbutryn
id.definition: A methylthio-1,3,5-triazine that is 2-(methylsulfanyl)-1,3,5-triazine substituted by a tert-butylamino and an ethylamino group at positions 2 and 4 respectively.

id.name: 1-aminocyclopropylphosphonate(1-)
id.definition: An organophosphonate oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from the phosphonic acid group of 1-aminocyclopropylphosphonic acid.

id.name: butylbenzene
id.definition: An alkylbenzene that is benzene substituted by a butyl group at position 1.

id.name: N-methyl-L-valine
id.definition: An optically active form of N-methylvaline having L-configuration.

id.name: naphthalene-2-sulfonic acid
id.definition: A naphthalenesulfonic acid in which the sulfo group is linked to position 2 of the naphthalene ring.

id.name: 6-(alpha-D-glucosaminyl)-1D-myo-inositol
id.definition: A D-glucosaminide consisting of 2-aminoglucosamine attached to 1D-myo-inositol at the 6-position via an alpha-linkage.

id.name: metyrapone
id.definition: An aromatic ketone that is 3,3-dimethylbutan-2-one in which the methyl groups at positions 1 and 4 are replaced by pyridin-3-yl groups. A steroid 11beta-monooxygenase (EC 1.14.15.4) inhibitor, it is used in the diagnosis of adrenal insufficiency.

id.name: (15Z)-tetracosenoic acid
id.definition: A tetracosenoic acid having a cis-double bond at position 15.

id.name: L-m-tyrosine
id.definition: A hydroxyphenylalanine that is L-phenylalanine with a substituent hydroxy group at position 3.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-glutamate(2-)
id.definition: An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of N-acetyl-L-glutamic acid.

id.name: (1R,2S)-1,2-dihydronaphthalene-1,2-diol
id.definition: The cis-1,2-dihydronaphthalene-1,2-diol with a (1R,2S)-configuration.

id.name: N-tris(hydroxymethyl)methyl-2-aminoethanesulfonic acid
id.definition: A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 7.5 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: nitrofurazone
id.definition: A semicarbazone resulting from the formal condensation of semicarbazide with 5-nitrofuraldehyde. A broad spectrum antibacterial drug, although with little activity against Pseudomonas species, it is used as a local application for burns, ulcers, wounds and skin infections.

id.name: duvoglustat
id.definition: An optically active form of 2-(hydroxymethyl)piperidine-3,4,5-triol having 2R,3R,4R,5S-configuration.

id.name: N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine 6-sulfate
id.definition: A galactosamine sulfate that is N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine in which the hydroxy group at position 6 has been converted to its sulfate derivative.

id.name: lawsone
id.definition: 1,4-Naphthoquinone carrying a hydroxy function at C-2. It is obtained from the leaves of Lawsonia inermis.

id.name: hydroxyurea
id.definition: A member of the class of ureas that is urea in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group. An antineoplastic used in the treatment of chronic myeloid leukaemia as well as for sickle-cell disease.

id.name: nimesulide
id.definition: An aromatic ether having phenyl and 2-methylsulfonamido-5-nitrophenyl as the two aryl groups.

id.name: 3-nitro-L-tyrosine
id.definition: A 3-nitrotyrosine comprising L-tyrosine having a nitro group at the 3-position on the phenyl ring.

id.name: N,N,N-trimethyl-N-(4-oxopentyl)ammonium
id.definition: A quaternary ammonium ion in which the substituents on nitrogen are methyl (three) and 4-oxopentyl.

id.name: N-ethylmaleimide
id.definition: A member of the class of maleimides that is the N-ethyl derivative of maleimide.

id.name: (S)-2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid
id.definition: The (S)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid. Derived from the metabolism of the branched-chain amino acids, it belongs to the 2-hydroxycarboxylic acid group of amino acid metabolites.

id.name: (10E,12Z)-octadecadienoic acid
id.definition: An octadeca-10,12-dienoic acid having (10E,12Z)-configuration.

id.name: 2'-hydroxybiphenyl-2-sulfinic acid
id.definition: An organosulfinic acid that is benzenesulfinic acid in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been replaced by a 2-hydroxyphenyl group.

id.name: 8-oxoguanine
id.definition: An oxopurine that is guanine which is substituted by an oxo group at position 8.

id.name: okadaic acid
id.definition: A polycyclic ether that is produced by several species of dinoflagellates, and is known to accumulate in both marine sponges and shellfish. A polyketide, polyether derivative of a C38 fatty acid, it is one of the primary causes of diarrhetic shellfish poisoning (DSP). It is a potent inhibitor of specific protein phosphatases and is known to have a variety of negative effects on cells.

id.name: alpha-D-glucosamine
id.definition: A 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: 3-oxooctanoic acid
id.definition: A derivative of octanoic acid carrying a beta-oxo group; a possible metabolite of 2-octynoic acid.

id.name: homogentisic acid
id.definition: A dihydroxyphenylacetic acid having the two hydroxy substituents at the 2- and 5-positions.

id.name: N-(5'-phosphopyridoxyl)-L-alanine
id.definition: An alanine derivative arising from reductive N-alkylation of L-alanine by pyridoxal-5-phosphate.

id.name: tetraphenylphosphonium
id.definition: A polyatomic cation consisting of four phenyl groups attached to a central phosphonium.

id.name: phosphoenolpyruvic acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that is acrylic acid substituted by a phosphonooxy group at position 2. It is a metabolic intermediate in pathways like glycolysis and gluconeogenesis.

id.name: propofol
id.definition: A phenol resulting from the formal substitution of the hydrogen at the 2 position of 1,3-diisopropylbenzene by a hydroxy group.

id.name: acepromazine
id.definition: A member of the class of phenothiazines that is 10H-phenothiazine substituted by an acetyl group at position 2 and a 3-(dimethylamino)propyl group at position 10.

id.name: 2,2'-piperazine-1,4-diylbisethanesulfonic acid
id.definition: A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 6.8 at 20 degreeC.

id.name: dioxidophosphate(1-)
id.definition: A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of hydroxyphosphanone.

id.name: D-alpha-phenylglycine
id.definition: The R stereoisomer of alpha-phenylglycine.

id.name: phosphonic acid
id.definition: A phosphorus oxoacid that consists of a single pentavalent phosphorus covalently bound via single bonds to a single hydrogen and two hydroxy groups and via a double bond to an oxygen. The parent of the class of phosphonic acids.

id.name: N-[4-(4-nitrophenylphospho)butanoyl]-D-alanine
id.definition: An N-[4-(4-nitrophenylphospho)butanoyl]alanine that has R at the chiral carbon.

id.name: 5-(2-ethoxyethyl)-5-[4-(4-fluorophenoxy)phenoxy]barbituric acid
id.definition: A member of the class of barbiturates that is barbituric acid in which the hydrogens at position 5 are replaced by 2-ethoxyethyl and 4-(4-fluorophenoxy)phenoxy groups. It is a potent and selective inhibitor of matrix MMP-13 (metalloproteinase-13, collagenase 3).

id.name: phosphite(3-)
id.definition: A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from phosphorous acid.

id.name: 7-cyano-7-deazaguanine
id.definition: A pyrrolopyrimidine that is 7-deazaguanine substituted at position 7 by a cyano group.

id.name: pentamidine
id.definition: A diether consisting of pentane-1,5-diol in which both hydroxyl hydrogens have been replaced by 4-amidinophenyl groups. A trypanocidal drug that is used for treatment of cutaneous leishmaniasis and Chagas disease.

id.name: (4S,10Z,16R)-phycourobilin
id.definition: A urobilin that consists of 3,18-diethyl-2,7,13,17-tetramethyl-1,4,5,15,16,19,22,24-octahydro-21H-biline-8,12-dipropanoic acid bearing two oxo substituents at positions 1 and 19 (the 4S,10Z,16R-iseomer).

id.name: Ro 320-1195
id.definition: An organofluorine compound that is 4-benzoylpyrazole in which the phenyl is substituted at position 3 by a (2,3-dihydroxypropyl)oxy group and in which the pyrazole moiety is substituted at positions 1 and 5 by a 4-fluorophenyl group and an amino group, respectively.

id.name: methylphosphonic acid
id.definition: A one-carbon compound that is phosphonic acid in which the hydrogen attached to the phosphorus is substituted by a methyl group.

id.name: pivalic acid
id.definition: A branched, short-chain fatty acid composed of propanoic acid having two methyl substituents at the 2-position.

id.name: 1,2-dilauroyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate
id.definition: A 1-acyl-2-dodecanoyl-sn-glycerol-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is also dodecanoyl (lauroyl).

id.name: diphosphate(2-)
id.definition: A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from diphosphoric acid.

id.name: (R)-dihydrolipoic acid
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer and bioactive form of dihydrolipoic acid.

id.name: 6-deoxyinosine 5'-phosphate
id.definition: The 5'-monophosphate of 6-deoxyinosine.

id.name: pyrazinecarboxamide
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of pyrazinoic acid (pyrazine-2-carboxylic acid) with ammonia. A prodrug for pyrazinoic acid, pyrazinecarboxamide is used as part of multidrug regimens for the treatment of tuberculosis.

id.name: hexadecane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with 16 carbon atoms. It is a component of essential oil isolated from long pepper.

id.name: adenine arabinoside
id.definition: A purine nucleoside in which adenine is attached to arabinofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.

id.name: phosphoramidon
id.definition: A dipeptide isolated from the cultures of Streptomyces tanashiensis.

id.name: sulfanilamide
id.definition: A sulfonamide in which the sulfamoyl functional group is attached to aniline at the 4-position.

id.name: methylcarbamic acid
id.definition: An amino acid consisting of carbamic acid having an N-methyl substituent.

id.name: ritonavir
id.definition: An L-valine derivative that is an antiretroviral drug from the protease inhibitor class used to treat HIV infection and AIDS, it is often used as a fixed-dose combination with another protease inhibitor, lopinavir. Also used in combination with dasabuvir sodium hydrate, ombitasvir and paritaprevir (under the trade name Viekira Pak) for treatment of chronic hepatitis C virus genotype 1 infection as well as cirrhosis of the liver.

id.name: (S)-2-hydroxypropylphosphonic acid
id.definition: 2-Hydroxypropylphosphonic acid with S configuration at the chiral centre.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-serine
id.definition: An N-acetyl-L-amino acid in which the amino acid specified is L-serine. Metabolite observed in cancer metabolism.

id.name: ricinelaidic acid
id.definition: A straight-chain, 18:1, long-chain fatty acid having a trans- double bond at position 9 and an R-oriented hydroxy group at position 12.

id.name: (R)-2-methylbutyric acid
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 2-methylbutanoic acid.

id.name: 5-hydroxypentanoic acid
id.definition: An omega-hydroxy fatty acid consisting of pentanoic acid carrying a hydroxy group at C-5.

id.name: heptanoic acid
id.definition: A C7, straight-chain fatty acid that contributes to the odour of some rancid oils. Used in the preparation of esters for the fragrance industry, and as an additive in cigarettes.

id.name: salicylhydroxamic acid
id.definition: A hydroxamic acid that is N-hydroxybenzamide carrying a phenolic hydroxy group at position 2.

id.name: (R)-1-phenylethanol
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 1-phenylethanol.

id.name: 4-oxopentanoic acid
id.definition: An oxopentanoic acid with the oxo group in the 4-position.

id.name: succinylcholine
id.definition: A quaternary ammonium ion that is the bis-choline ester of succinic acid.

id.name: S-methylcysteine
id.definition: A cysteine derivative that is L-cysteine in which the hydrogen attached to the sulfur is replaced by a methyl group.

id.name: trans-resveratrol
id.definition: A resveratrol in which the double bond has E configuration.

id.name: 3,3,3-tetramine
id.definition: A polyazaalkane consisting of a 13-membered straight chain alkane with aza-groups at the 1-, 5-, 9- and 13-positions.

id.name: troleandomycin
id.definition: A semi-synthetic macrolide antibiotic obtained by acetylation of the three free hydroxy groups of oleandomycin. Troleandomycin is only found in individuals that have taken the drug.

id.name: dipropyl disulfide
id.definition: An organic disulfide where the alkyl groups specified are propyl. It is a component of the essential oils obtained from Allium.

id.name: imatinib
id.definition: A benzamide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-[(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)methyl]benzoic acid with the primary aromatic amino group of 4-methyl-N(3)-[4-(pyridin-3-yl)pyrimidin-2-yl]benzene-1,3-diamine. Used (as its mesylate salt) for treatment of chronic myelogenous leukemia and gastrointestinal stromal tumours.

id.name: 2-thienylacetic acid
id.definition: A thiophene compound having a carboxymethyl group at the 2-position.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-threonine
id.definition: A N-acetyl-L-amino acid that is the N-acetyl derivative of L-threonine.

id.name: paclitaxel
id.definition: A tetracyclic diterpenoid isolated originally from the bark of the Pacific yew tree, Taxus brevifolia. It is a mitotic inhibitor used in cancer chemotherapy. Note that the use of the former generic name 'taxol' is now limited, as Taxol is a registered trade mark.

id.name: trifluoroacetic acid
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid that is the trifluoro derivative of acetic acid.

id.name: tert-butanol
id.definition: A tertiary alcohol alcohol that is isobutane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2.

id.name: 5,6,7,8-tetrahydro-1-naphthol
id.definition: 1-naphthol hydrogenated at C-5, -6, -7 and -8.

id.name: tridecanoic acid
id.definition: A C13 straight-chain saturated fatty acid.

id.name: trimethoprim
id.definition: An aminopyrimidine antibiotic whose structure consists of pyrimidine 2,4-diamine and 1,2,3-trimethoxybenzene moieties linked by a methylene bridge.

id.name: trifluoperazine
id.definition: A member of the class of phenothiazines that is phenothiazine having a trifluoromethyl subsitituent at the 2-position and a 3-(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)propyl group at the N-10 position.

id.name: thiabendazole
id.definition: A member of the class of benzimidazoles carrying a 1,3-thiazol-4-yl substituent at position 2. A mainly post-harvest fungicide used to control a wide range of diseases including Aspergillus, Botrytis, Cladosporium and Fusarium.

id.name: tacrine
id.definition: A member of the class of acridines that is 1,2,3,4-tetrahydroacridine substituted by an amino group at position 9. It is used in the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.

id.name: ribothymidine
id.definition: A methyluridine having a single methyl substituent at the 5-position on the uracil ring.

id.name: tetramethylammonium
id.definition: The simplest quaternary ammonium cation, comprising a central nitrogen linked to four methyl groups.

id.name: benzene-1,3,5-tricarboxylic acid
id.definition: A tricarboxylic acid that consists of benzene substituted by carboxy groups at positions 1, 3 and 5.

id.name: docosane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with 22 carbon atoms.

id.name: 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene
id.definition: A trinitrotoluene having the nitro groups at positions 2, 4 and 6.

id.name: fluconazole
id.definition: A member of the class of triazoles that is propan-2-ol substituted at position 1 and 3 by 1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl groups and at position 2 by a 2,4-difluorophenyl group. It is an antifungal drug used for the treatment of mucosal candidiasis and for systemic infections including systemic candidiasis, coccidioidomycosis, and cryptococcosis.

id.name: picric acid
id.definition: A C-nitro compound comprising phenol having three nitro substtituents at the 2-, 4- and 6-positions.

id.name: paracetamol
id.definition: A member of the class of phenols that is 4-aminophenol in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amino group has been replaced by an acetyl group.

id.name: O(4')-sulfo-L-tyrosine
id.definition: An O-sulfoamino acid that is L-tyrosine in which the phenolic hydrogen has been replaced by a sulfo group.

id.name: UDP-alpha-D-glucose
id.definition: The alpha-anomer of UDP-alpha-D-glucose. It is used in nucleotide sugars metabolism.

id.name: ubiquinone-1
id.definition: A compound composed of the standard 2,3-dimethoxy-5-methylbenzoquinone nucleus common to ubiquinones; and a side chain of a single isoprenoid unit.

id.name: coenzyme Q10
id.definition: A ubiquinone having a side chain of 10 isoprenoid units. In the naturally occurring isomer, all isoprenyl double bonds are in the E- configuration.

id.name: 2'-deoxyuridine 3'-monophosphate
id.definition: A pyrimidine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 3'-monophosphate having uracil as the nucleobase.

id.name: ubiquinone-5
id.definition: A compound composed of the 2,3-dimethoxy-5-methylbenzoquinone nucleus common to ubiquinones; and a side chain of five isoprenoid units.

id.name: undecane
id.definition: A straight-chain alkane with 11 carbon atoms.

id.name: 5-fluorouracil
id.definition: A nucleobase analogue that is uracil in which the hydrogen at position 5 is replaced by fluorine. It is an antineoplastic agent which acts as an antimetabolite - following conversion to the active deoxynucleotide, it inhibits DNA synthesis (by blocking the conversion of deoxyuridylic acid to thymidylic acid by the cellular enzyme thymidylate synthetase) and so slows tumour growth.

id.name: UTP(4-)
id.definition: A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of UTP; major species present at pH 7.3.

id.name: N-s-butyl-N-[(2R,3S)-3-({[(3aS,5R,6aR)-hexahydro-2H-cyclopenta[b]furan-5-yloxy]carbonyl}amino)-2-hydroxy-4-phenylbutyl]-4-(hydroxymethyl)benzenesulfonamide
id.definition: An N,N-disubstituted toluene-p-sulfonamaide, with a structure close to that of darunavir. It is found to inhibit dimerization of HIV-1 protease subunits.

id.name: virginiamycin S1
id.definition: A cyclodepsipeptide that is N-(3-hydroxypicolinoyl)-L-threonyl-D-alpha-aminobutyryl-L-prolyl-N-methyl-L-phenylalanyl-4-oxo-L-pipecoloyl-L-2-phenylglycine in which the carboxy group of the 2-phenylglycine moiety has undergone formal intramolecular condensation with the hydroxy group of the N-(3-hydroxypicolinoyl)-L-threonyl to give the corresponding 19-membered ring lactone. It is one of the two major components of the antibacterial drug virginiamycin, produced by Streptomyces virginiae, S. loidensis, S. mitakaensis, S. pristina-spiralis, S. ostreogriseus, and others.

id.name: vanadate(3-)
id.definition: A vanadium oxoanion that is a trianion with formula VO4 in which the vanadium is in the +5 oxidation state and is attached to four oxygen atoms.

id.name: tungstate
id.definition: A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from tungstic acid.

id.name: cis-zeatin
id.definition: The cis-isomer of zeatin.

id.name: 2,4-dichloroaniline
id.definition: A dichloroaniline carrying chloro substituents at positions 2 and 4.

id.name: (1E,4S,5E,7R)-germacra-1(10),5-dien-11-ol
id.definition: A germacrane sesquiterpenoid obtained from germacrane by hydroxylation at C(11) together with dehydrogenation across the C(1)-C(10) and C(5)-C(6) bonds.

id.name: glycino group
id.definition: The C-terminal proteinogenic amino-acid residue derived from glycine.

id.name: hygrine
id.definition: A 1-(1-methylpyrrolidin-2-yl)acetone that has R configuration. It is a pyrrolidine alkaloid found in the coca plant, Erythroxylum coca.

id.name: dipeptide
id.definition: Any molecule that contains two amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.

id.name: (E,E,E)-geranylgeraniol
id.definition: A geranylgeraniol in which all four double bonds have E- (trans-) geometry.

id.name: diglyme
id.definition: A polyether that is the dimethyl ether derivative of diethylene glycol.

id.name: 2-ethoxyethanol
id.definition: A hydroxyether that is the ethyl ether derivative of ethylene glycol.

id.name: 2-methoxyethanol
id.definition: A hydroxyether that is ethanol substituted by a methoxy group at position 2.

id.name: poly(ethylene glycol)
id.definition: A polymer composed of repeating ethyleneoxy units.

id.name: thioglycine
id.definition: A monothiocarboxylic acid that is the thiolacid analogue of glycine. The parent of the class of thioglycines.

id.name: dipicolinic acid
id.definition: A pyridinedicarboxylic acid carrying two carboxy groups at positions 2 and 6.

id.name: polidocanol
id.definition: A hydroxypolyether that is nonaethylene glycol in which one of the terminal hydroxy functions is substituted by a lauryl (dodecyl) group.

id.name: alpha-amino acid ester
id.definition: The amino acid ester derivative obtained the formal condensation of an alpha-amino acid with an alcohol.

id.name: primary amino group
id.definition: An amino group formed by replacement of one of the hydrogen atoms in ammonia by a group or atom other than a hydrogen atom.

id.name: cholesteryl oleate
id.definition: The (Z)-stereoisomer of cholesteryl octadec-9-enoate.

id.name: (R)-pantothenic acid
id.definition: A pantothenic acid having R-configuration.

id.name: oxane
id.definition: A saturated organic heteromonocyclic parent that is cyclohexane in which one of the carbon atoms has been replaced by an oxygen atom.

id.name: 3-(2,3-dihydroxyphenyl)propanoate
id.definition: The conjugate base of 3-(2,3-dihydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid.

id.name: 3-(2-hydroxyphenyl)propanoate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid anion that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carbosylic acid group of 3-(2-hydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid.

id.name: L-erythro-sphingosine
id.definition: A (2R,3S)-2-aminooctadec-4-ene-1,3-diol in which the double bond has E geochemistry.

id.name: premnaspirodiene
id.definition: A vetispirane with (2R,5S,10R) stereochemistry.

id.name: alpha-L-arabinopyranose
id.definition: A L-arabinopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.

id.name: beta-D-ribose
id.definition: A D-ribofuranose in which the anomeric centre has beta-configuration.

id.name: D-ribofuranose
id.definition: A ribofuranose having D-configuration.

id.name: 1,4-dioxane
id.definition: A dioxane with oxygen atoms at positions 1 and 4.

id.name: 5-bromouridine 5'-monophosphate
id.definition: A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 5-bromouracil as the pyrimidine component.

id.name: pentachlorobenzene
id.definition: A member of the class of pentachlorobenzenes that is benzene in which five of the hydrogens are replaced by chlorines. Now classed as a persistent organic pollutant under the Stockholm Convention.

id.name: 4-bromophenol
id.definition: A bromophenol containing only hydroxy and bromo substituents that are para to one another.

id.name: hydrogen bromide
id.definition: A diatomic molecule containing covalently bonded hydrogen and bromine atoms.

id.name: L-6'-bromotryptophan
id.definition: A bromoamino acid that is L-tryptophan in which the hydrogen at position 6 of the indole ring is substituted by bromine.

id.name: N-acetyl-L-phenylalanyl-4-[difluoro(phosphono)methyl]-L-phenylalaninamide
id.definition: A subsituted L-phenylalanyl-L-phenylalaninamide dipeptide. It is a potent inhibitor of protein tyrosine phosphatase.

id.name: diclofenac
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid consisting of phenylacetic acid having a (2,6-dichlorophenyl)amino group at the 2-position.

id.name: furosemide
id.definition: A chlorobenzoic acid that is 4-chlorobenzoic acid substituted by a (furan-2-ylmethyl)amino and a sulfamoyl group at position 2 and 5 respectively. It is a diuretic used in the treatment of congestive heart failure.

id.name: haloxyfop-P
id.definition: A 2-(4-{[3-chloro-5-(trifluoromethyl)pyridin-2-yl]oxy}phenoxy)propanoic acid that has R configuration. It is the most active enantiomer of the (racemic) herbicide haloxyfop and is used (particularly as the corresponding methyl and ethoxyethyl ester proherbicides (haloxyfop-P-methyl and haloxyfop-P-etotyl, respectively) to control annual and perrenial grasses in a variety of crops.

id.name: imipramine
id.definition: A dibenzoazepine that is 5H-dibenzo[b,f]azepine substituted by a 3-(dimethylamino)propyl group at the nitrogen atom.

id.name: ketoconazole
id.definition: A racemate consisting of equimolar amounts of (2R,4S)- and (2S,4R)-ketoconazole.

id.name: L-glucaric acid
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of glucaric acid.

id.name: chloroethane
id.definition: The simplest and least toxic member of the class of chloroethanes, that is ethane in which a single hydrogen is substituted by a chlorine. A colourless gas at room temperature and pressure (boiling point 12degreeC), it is used as a mild topical anaesthetic to numb the skin prior to ear piercing, skin biopsies, etc., and is also used in the treatment of sports injuries. It was formerly used in the production of tetraethyllead.

id.name: bezafibrate
id.definition: A monocarboxylic acid amide obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-chlorobenzoic acid with the amino group of 2-[4-(2-aminoethyl)phenoxy]-2-methylpropanoic acid. Benafibrate is used for the treatment of hyperlipidaemia.

id.name: acetate ester
id.definition: Any carboxylic ester where the carboxylic acid component is acetic acid.

id.name: 2,4,6-tribromophenol
id.definition: A bromophenol that is phenol substituted by bromo groups at positions 2, 4 and 6. It is commonly used as a fungicide and in the preparation of flame retardants.

id.name: (R)-1,2-distearoylphosphatidylethanolamine
id.definition: An optically active form of 1,2-distearoylphosphatidylethanolamine having (R)-configuration.

id.name: beta-tocopherol
id.definition: A tocopherol in which the chroman-6-ol core is substituted by methyl groups at positions 5 and 8. While it is found in low concentrations in many vegetable oils, only cottonseed oil contains significant amounts.

id.name: delta-tocopherol
id.definition: A tocopherol in which the chroman-6-ol core is substituted by a methyl group at position 8. It is found particularly in maize (corn) oil and soya bean (soybean) oils.

id.name: glyceride
id.definition: Any ester resulting from the condensation of one or more of the hydroxy groups of glycerol (propane-1,2,3-triol) with fatty acids.

id.name: clomipramine
id.definition: A dibenzoazepine that is 10,11-dihydro-5H-dibenzo[b,f]azepine which is substituted by chlorine at position 3 and in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a 3-(dimethylamino)propyl group. One of the more sedating tricyclic antidepressants, it is used as the hydrochloride salt for the treatment of depression as well as obsessive-compulsive disorder and phobias.

id.name: desipramine
id.definition: A dibenzoazepine consisting of 10,11-dihydro-5H-dibenzo[b,f]azepine substituted on nitrogen with a 3-(methylamino)propyl group.

id.name: 16-oxo steroid
id.definition: Any oxo steroid carrying an oxo group at position 16.

id.name: 11-oxo steroid
id.definition: Any oxo steroid that has an oxo substituent at position 11.

id.name: 3-oxo steroid
id.definition: Any oxo steroid where an oxo substituent is located at position 3.

id.name: 7-oxo steroid
id.definition: Any oxo steroid carrying an oxo group at position 7.

id.name: (methylthio)acetic acid
id.definition: A sulfur-containing carboxylic consisting of thioglycolic acid carrying an S-methyl substituent.

id.name: alkanesulfonic acid
id.definition: Organic derivatives of sulfonic acid in which the sulfo group is linked directly to carbon of an alkyl group.

id.name: 3-oxo-Delta(5)-steroid
id.definition: Any 3-oxo steroid which also contains a double bond between positions 5 and 6.

id.name: alkanethiol
id.definition: An alkanethiol is a compound in which a sulfanyl group, -SH, is attached to an alkyl group.

id.name: 3-oxo-Delta(4) steroid
id.definition: A 3-oxo steroid conjugated to a C=C double bond at the alpha,beta position.

id.name: S-prenyl-L-cysteine
id.definition: A prenylcysteine where the prenyl moiety is attached to the side-chain sulfur atom of L-cysteine.

id.name: flavonoid
id.definition: Any member of the 'superclass' flavonoids whose skeleton is based on 1-benzopyran with an aryl substituent at position 2. The term was originally restricted to natural products, but is now also used to describe semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds.

id.name: tripeptide
id.definition: Any molecule that contains three amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.

id.name: nicotinic acetylcholine receptor agonist
id.definition: An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a nicotinic acetylcholine receptor.

id.name: 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose
id.definition: A D-glucosamine whose structure comprises D-glucopyranose having an amino substituent at position 2.

id.name: threo-3-methyl-L-aspartic acid
id.definition: An aspartic acid derivative having a 3-methyl substituent.

id.name: (2S)-dihydrotricetin
id.definition: The (2S)-enantiomer of dihydrotricetin.

id.name: tetrapeptide
id.definition: Any molecule that contains four amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.

id.name: 4-methylene-L-glutamic acid
id.definition: The L-enantiomer of 4-methyleneglutamic acid.

id.name: dihydroflavonols
id.definition: Any hydroxyflavanone in which a hydroxy group is present on the position 3 of the heterocyclic ring.

id.name: (S)-5-oxo-2,5-dihydro-2-furylacetic acid
id.definition: The (S)-enantiomer of 5-oxo-2,5-dihydro-2-furylacetic acid.

id.name: keto-D-fructose
id.definition: The open-chain form of D-fructose.

id.name: nitric acid
id.definition: A nitrogen oxoacid of formula HNO3 in which the nitrogen atom is bonded to a hydroxy group and by equivalent bonds to the remaining two oxygen atoms.

id.name: phosphono group
id.definition: The inorganic group -P(=O)OH2.

id.name: nucleotide-amino acid
id.definition: An amino acid derivative that is any conjugate between a nucleotide and an amino acid.

id.name: azelaic acid
id.definition: An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is heptane substituted at positions 1 and 7 by carboxy groups.

id.name: D-erythrose 4-phosphate
id.definition: An erythrose phosphate that is D-erythrose carrying a phosphate group at position 4. It is an intermediate in the pentose phosphate pathway and Calvin cycle.

id.name: nanaomycin A
id.definition: A pyranonaphthoquinone antibiotic from strain OS-3966 of Streptomyces rosa var. notoensis.

id.name: p-menthane-3,8-diol
id.definition: A p-menthane monoterpenoid in which p-menthane carries hydroxy groups at C-3 and C-8.

id.name: tubercidin
id.definition: An N-glycosylpyrrolopyrimidine that is adenosine in which the in the 5-membered ring that is not attached to the ribose moiety is replaced by a carbon. Tubercidin is produced in the culture broth of Streptomyces tubericidus.

id.name: (R)-3-sulfolactic acid
id.definition: The (R)-enantiomer of 3-sulfolactic acid.

id.name: N-methylserotonin
id.definition: A member of the class of tryptamines that is serotonin in which one of the hydrogens attached to the primary amino group is replaced by a methyl group.

id.name: 2-aminobut-2-enoic acid zwitterion
id.definition: An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 2-aminobut-2-enoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

id.name: amidyl group
id.definition: The substituent group formed by loss of a proton from azanide.

id.name: ethyl vanillin
id.definition: A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is vanillin in which the methoxy group is replaced by an ethoxy group.

id.name: angiogenesis inhibitor
id.definition: An agent and endogenous substances that antagonize or inhibit the development of new blood vessels.

id.name: N-formimidoyl-L-aspartic acid
id.definition: An aspartic acid derivative that is the N-formimidoyl derivative of L-aspartic acid.

id.name: N-formyl-L-aspartic acid
id.definition: A N-formyl amino acid that is the N-formyl-derivative of L-aspartic acid.

id.name: 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid
id.definition: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pentanoic acid (valeric acid) substituted with a keto group at C-2 and a methyl group at C-4. A metabolite that has been found to accumulate in maple syrup urine disease.

id.name: 2-methyl-1-hydroxypropylthiamine diphosphate
id.definition: The diphosphate of thiamine(1+), substituted at C-2 of the thiazole ring by a hydroxylated sec-butyl group.

id.name: phenylbutazone
id.definition: A member of the class of pyrazolidines that is 1,2-diphenylpyrazolidine-3,5-dione carrying a butyl group at the 4-position.

id.name: fumagillin
id.definition: A meroterpenoid resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of fumagillol with the carboxylic acid group of (all-E)-deca-2,4,6,8-tetraenedioic acid. Originally isolated from the fungus Aspergillus fumigatus, it is used for the control of Nosema infection in honey bees.

id.name: (2Z)-2-hydroxypenta-2,4-dienoic acid
id.definition: A 2-hydroxypenta-2,4-dienoic acid in which the double bond between positions 2 and 3 has Z- (trans-) geometry.

id.name: L-sorbopyranose
id.definition: The L-stereoisomer of sorbopyranose.

id.name: mononitroanisoles
id.definition: Any member of the class of nitroanisoles in which a single nitro group is attached to the anisole ring.

id.name: (-)-lobeline
id.definition: An optically active piperidine alkaloid having a 2-oxo-2-phenylethyl substituent at the 2-position and a 2-hydroxy-2-phenylethyl group at the 6-position.

id.name: beta-phellandrene
id.definition: One of a pair of phellandrene cyclic monoterpene double-bond isomers in which one double bond is exocyclic (cf. alpha-phellandrene, where both of them are endoocyclic).

id.name: dimethylarsinic acid
id.definition: The organoarsenic compound that is arsenic acid substituted on the central arsenic atom with two methyl groups.

id.name: ethyl(trimethyl)silane
id.definition: An organosilicon compound that is silane in which the hydrogens have been replaced by three methyl and one ethyl group.

id.name: 1'-(dimethylcarbamoyl)ferrocene-1-carboxylic acid
id.definition: A ferrocene inhibitor of the synthetic exo Diels-Alderase catalytic antibody 13G5, where the (dimethylamino)carbonyl group represents the dienophile and the carboxyl group represents the side chain of the diene.

id.name: iron-sulfur-molybdenum cluster
id.definition: An iron-sulfur cluster containing 7 iron atoms, 9 sulfur atoms and a molybdenum atom.

id.name: trichloroacetaldehyde
id.definition: An organochlorine compound that consists of acetaldehyde where all the methyl hydrogens are replaced by chloro groups.

id.name: 2-trans,6-trans,10-trans-geranylgeranyl diphosphate
id.definition: The all-trans-isomer of geranylgeranyl diphosphate.

id.name: phycocyanobilin
id.definition: A bilin that consists of 8,12-bis(2-carboxyethyl)-18-ethyl-3-ethylidene-2,7,13,17-tetramethyl-2,3-dihydrobilin bearing two oxo substituents at positions 1 and 19.

id.name: N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid
id.definition: Any L-alpha-amino acid carrying an N-acyl substituent.
